<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, May 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Rebels Free 139 U.N. Personnel
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's rebels freed 139 of more than
500 U.N. personnel held captive into Liberian custody, Liberia's President
Charles Taylor said Sunday, after U.N. officials secured the release of 18
others. Taylor said 15 of the freed captives had been flown by helicopter to
Monrovia, while the remaining 124 were waiting to be evacuated from the Liberian
border town of Foya. There was no immediate U.N. confirmation of the report.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Palestinians Charge Israeli Army Base
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Frustration over stalled negotiations exploded into
violence Sunday as thousands of Palestinian protesters clashed with Israeli
troops -- demonstrations that left one Palestinian dead and about 38 people
injured. In the Gaza Strip, more than 500 Palestinians charged an Israeli army
base near the Jewish settlement of Netzarim, hurling stones and Molotov
cocktails over the fence. Similar clashes took place in the West Bank cities of
Nablus and Ramallah. Those clashes began as marches marking Monday's 52nd
anniversary of al-Nakba or ''the catastrophe'' -- the term Palestinians use to
refer to Israel's creation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Women Said Expelled From Singapore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- A newspaper report said Sunday nine foreign women married
to Singaporeans have been expelled because they have contracted HIV, the virus
that causes AIDS. The Sunday Times, citing unidentified sources, said that the
women were mainly from Thailand, Indonesia, China and the Philippines. The
women, who are not Singaporean citizens, carry social passes, which allow them
to stay in Singapore for a period of up to a year. The report said another 10
women infected with the virus were expecting to be sent home.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mothers Rally for Strict Gun Control
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tens of thousands of mothers rallied in sight of the
Capitol Sunday to demand strict control of handguns. Participants in the
''Million Mom March'' aimed to send Congress a ''Mother's Day'' message: A new
movement of mainstream Americans is getting politically active, ready to battle
the gun lobby and to work against lawmakers who oppose gun control. Crowds
ranging from a few hundred to an estimated 4,000 in Chicago and 5,000 in Denver
showed up at similar rallies in dozens of cities across the country -- from
Maine to Michigan to Oregon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Residents Tour Damage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- Hundreds of evacuated residents of Los Alamos
returned Sunday to seared homes, blackened yards and still-smoking vistas of
their abandoned town. Families without homes came together in Red Cross shelters
to mark the holiday, while churchgoers mourned their own losses but expressed
relief that nobody was hurt. The 7,000 people of neighboring White Rock,
meanwhile, were allowed to go home. The buses left Santa Fe for Los Alamos
throughout the day, carrying counselors, clergy and 389 residents.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Obuchi Remembered As Changing Japan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Former Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, an unassuming
ruling party stalwart who defied early predictions of failure as premier, died
Sunday at age 62, more than a month after suffering a debilitating stroke while
in office. Obuchi was prime minister when he was stricken and hospitalized April
2. He later lapsed into a coma and days later, parliament elected Yoshiro Mori
as his successor.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Earthquake Strikes Indonesia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A strong earthquake hit a remote area of Indonesia
on Monday, shaking houses and damaging buildings. No casualties were immediately
reported. The 6.2 magnitude quake struck central Sulawesi Island, 120 miles from
the site of an even stronger temblor May 4 that killed more than 46 people,
injured more than 100 others and left 30,000 homeless.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drama Desk Awards Handed Out
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Copenhagen'' was chosen best play of the New York theater
season and ''Contact'' best musical Sunday by the Drama Desk, an organization of
theater journalists and critics. A revival of ''Kiss Me, Kate'' picked up six
awards, more than any other show. In addition to its prize for best musical
revival, the 1948 Cole Porter musical won awards for its star, director, set
design, costume design and orchestrations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Monday in light trading ahead of a key
U.S. monetary policy meeting on Tuesday. The Nikkei fell 36.93 points to
17,320.93. On Friday, the average closed up 457.40 points, or 2.8 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astros Defeat Reds 10-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Mitch Meluskey hit a three-run homer and Scott Elarton
limited Cincinnati to four hits in seven innings as the Houston Astros Beat the
Reds 10-3 Sunday night. Houston won for the first time in three games and
improved to 6-12 at Enron Field, the Astros' new home ballpark.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
