<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syracuse University will spend up to $185 million on improvements  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Syracuse University is about to enter
uncharted territory: The board of trustees has approved a building
and renovation plan that could amount to as much as $185 million.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the school taken such a comprehensive approach to
building and renovating in such a short period of time, officials
said after approving the spending on Saturday. It will affect
nearly every school and department over the next five or six years.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the plan is the expansion of the School of
Management, E.S. Bird Library, S.I. Newhouse School of Public
Communications, more than doubling the space at the Center for
Science and Technology, and finding a home for a new college.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new space is built for those schools and programs, the
focus will shift to modernizing other buildings. The plan would
change 13 buildings and possibly add a building. It would renovate
350,000-square feet and might add at least that much more.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to move from planning a building to planning a
campus,'' Chancellor Kenneth Shaw said. ''Historically, we put up
one building at a time. We're no longer in a position to be able to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the university is in a sound financial position with an
endowment of more than $1 billion, it can afford this project, Shaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think (the plan) allows us to remain at the cutting edge
with our buildings,'' the chancellor said. ''We want
state-of-the-art, for today and tomorrow's world.''
</P>
<P>
   About six months ago, the 57-member board of trustees approved a
bond issue of $180 million, of which $30 million will go to
refinancing old debt. That leaves $150 million to pay for this
project. The balance of $35 million will be paid through fund
raising, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ''hopefully positions us for the next 10 to 15 years
after completing it to better serve the students and the whole
community,'' said Joseph Lampe, chairman of the university's board
of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   At least 18 months of design and planning are ahead before
construction begins, officials said. And the trustees still must
approve each individual project.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse University has the resources to be ranked among the top
30 research universities in the country, said Deborah Freund, vice
chancellor and provost. To do that, it needs modern facilities, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an integral part of who we know we can be in the
future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   University officials hired the consulting firm of Dober, Lidsky,
Craig &AMP; Associates of Belmont, Mass., to help put the plan
together. The consultant compared Syracuse University to 11
institutions similar in size and structure. Boston College, Brown,
Cornell, Duke, Northwestern and Notre Dame universities were among
those on that list.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant found that Syracuse has, on average, about
600,000-square feet less academic space than those universities.
</P>
<P>
   Annual operating costs are expected to increase between $4
million and $5 million. The university will increase enrollment by
about 75 students in each entering class to pay for maintenance of
the new space.
</P>
<P>
   City and economic development officials welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is exciting for us,'' said Irwin Davis, executive vice
president of the Metropolitan Development Agency and president of
the University Hill Corp. ''This is a major step for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
