<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Short-staffed Danbury Police Dept. still reeling from recent setbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The town's tainted police department
is not only beleaguered, it's also the walking wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Eight officers currently are either on sick or injury leave,
adding additional pressure to a department already undermanned and
reportedly polarized by the recent criminal convictions of two of
its officers.
</P>
<P>
   The department is slated to have 45 sworn officers, but has only
28 who are active. The shortage has all but stopped a plan to have
one officer stationed at New Milford High School and another at
Schaghticoke Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to deal with the situation the best we can,'' Acting
Police Chief Colin McCormack told the Danbury News-Times. ''We are
still meeting all our staffing requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormack acknowledged it's unusual to have eight officers out
on injury or sick leave, but denied the officers are out because of
problems coping with the convictions of former Officer Scott Smith
and Officer William Scribner.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was fired after he was convicted of intentional
manslaughter for shooting a suspect in the back. Last week, he was
sentenced to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner remains on desk duty pending sentencing June 14 after
being convicted this spring of negligent homicide for having killed
a teen-age girl when his cruiser crashed into her car at a New
Milford intersection. He faces six months in jail.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack said his missing officers are out because of injuries
they received in the line of duty. Six officers are out on injury
leave and receiving workers' compensation. Two others are on sick
leave, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack currently is trying to recruit new officers but said
it takes five to six months before a recruit is trained to handle
regular patrol duties. Meanwhile, the department has used up its
$81,600 overtime budget and had to get an additional $75,000 to
cover overtime until the end of the fiscal year, June 30.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, it received a federal grant for a community
policing initiative that would pay the salary of two officers. That
grant has never also been unused because of staffing woes and it's
not clear if and when it will be.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCormack's fate is uncertain. The department has been
without a permanent police chief since August, and the town's
police search committee hasn't met in months.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack says his officers are doing the best job they can,
under tough circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have worked in a professional manner under obviously very
difficult situations,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
