<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Opposition Threatened  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic's
government is threatening a major crackdown on government
opponents, blaming them for the recent slaying of a ruling
Socialist Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be the first confrontation in a renewed campaign
against the opposition, officials have promised to arrest
participants at a major anti-government rally today in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''All who perform activities against the state will be treated
in accordance with the law and prevented. The time of their street
actions is over,'' Goran Matic, Yugoslavia's information minister
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if opposition activists would face arrest for attending
today's rally, Matic said: ''That is correct.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally was scheduled after organizers caved in to government
pressure last week not to hold a protest in Milosevic's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions in Serbia have soared following the slaying Saturday of
Bosko Perosevic, 43, the head of the Vojvodina provincial
government and chief of a Socialist party branch there. Milosevic's
top aides said the pro-democracy student group Otpor and the
opposition Serbian Renewal Movement party masterminded the attack
on behalf of NATO and would be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Perosevic was touring a trade fair in Novi Sad, the capital of
the northern province, when a guard, identified as 50-year-old
exhibition hall security guard Milan Gutovic, fatally shot him in
the head. Gutovic was immediately arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Police said in a statement they found ''beyond doubt'' the
suspect was an activist with Otpor and the Serbian Renewal Movement
and that a search of his home turned up ''posters and propaganda
material'' belonging to the groups, along with ''brochures on
terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Both groups have rejected the allegations and denied any
connection with the gunman.
</P>
<P>
   However, the government appears ready to seize on the killing to
crack down on dissent, which has been fed by growing poverty and
isolation brought on during Milosevic's more than ten years in
power.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Gutovic, a number of other people have also been
detained for interrogation, Matic said. He declined to specify how
many had been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Marovic, a top leader of Otpor, which means resistance in
Serbo-Croatian, said several of the group's activists have been
questioned and detained. He called Matic's allegations ''lies'' and
''political marketing'' in an attempt to use the tragedy ''to crack
down on political opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   The private Beta news agency reported six other arrests, mostly
in Vojvodina, in connection with the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Matic also blamed the killing on NATO countries that launched a
78-day air war against Yugoslavia last year to force Milosevic to
abandon a crackdown against Muslims in Kosovo. The attack was
organized ''with a deep political background, with the aim to
destabilize Yugoslavia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The NATO aggressors are now putting their weapons in the hands
of their servants here, to do for them the dirty job, to spread
fear and chaos,'' said Gorica Gajevic, secretary general of the
socialists.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian Renewal Movement denied the government allegations
and rejected any connection with Gutovic, calling him ''a
monster.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If the murder has a political background, the real culprits
should be sought within the regime, which is ... instigating bloody
conflicts,'' a statement from the opposition party said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
