<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York chancellor is giving school system a cultured kick  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A tombstone. A jar of Twizzlers. A teetering
tower of playing blocks.
</P>
<P>
   They're just a few of the things Harold Levy moved into his
office when he accepted one of the most challenging jobs in America
-- running the country's largest school system.
</P>
<P>
   The small granite tombstone inscribed ''Levy'' sits on his
windowsill overlooking downtown Brooklyn at Board of Education
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tombstones are what life is about: Do what you can before you
die. And it's entertaining,'' Levy says with an easy smile.
</P>
<P>
   As he sits at his conference table, the 47-year-old lawyer is
wearing an impeccably tailored dark suit -- a leftover from his job
as a Citigroup executive.
</P>
<P>
   He was named interim schools chancellor three months ago,
following the swift departure of Rudy Crew amid policy clashes with
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   After a nationwide search for a new chancellor, Levy is now the
sole candidate when the seven-member school board votes this week --
a virtual shoo-in as the permanent head of a system with more than
1.1 million students, 78,000 teachers and 130,000 other employees.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the winter, Levy's first move was as fresh as he was: He
sent three poems by Wallace Stevens to the 43 school
superintendents, with a memo telling them he's interested in ''the
inner souls of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he made the city's school superintendents play -- by
arranging a group violin lesson at Carnegie Hall with virtuoso
Isaac Stern.
</P>
<P>
   And how does one turn such cultured oomph into academic
achievement?
</P>
<P>
   ''From music can come order,'' Stern told the superintendents
last week in a Carnegie studio somewhere above the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Like musical soldiers in formation, 40 black violin cases stood
at the ready, lined with cheap blue velour. Rented at $10 apiece,
they were hardly Stradivaris.
</P>
<P>
   But the fiddles delivered the message.
</P>
<P>
   Just holding the instrument took discipline; one superintendent
put hers on the wrong shoulder -- upside down. Somehow, amid the
cacophony and fits of laughter, the educators managed to accompany
their 79-year-old master as he played ''Did You Ever See a
Lassie.''
</P>
<P>
   Music ''is one of the most disciplined teachers,'' Stern told
them. ''And if it doesn't start with you, who the hell is it going
to start with?''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson was not lost on Paula LeCompte Speed, superintendent
of Brooklyn's District 18, which covers the Canarsie and East
Flatbush neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very powerful,'' she said. ''Everything is related. We
need more arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy concedes the half-hour session was ''a marketing ploy -- I
want the kids to be excited, not just treat learning like spinach.
Art and music are the hook by which we get the attention of
students who might otherwise drift away.''
</P>
<P>
   It's his way of tackling his top concerns: ''Can we get good
teachers? Can we get the students to perform on these damned tests?
And if you can't, then everything else doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding brains to the marketing, Levy has a resident intellectual
in the chancellor's office -- his old friend Jonathan Levi, a jazz
violinist, writer and founding editor of the Granta literary
magazine who is overseeing the existing arts programs.
</P>
<P>
   The schools chancellor is pushing music and poetry in a system
plagued with rats, guns and crumbling school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   An earthy New Yorker with a fine-tuned mind, Levy occasionally
targets such problems by softly spitting out four-letter words --
between smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Glee fills his face as he rails against the physical state of
the Board of Education headquarters, a Kafkaesque labyrinth of
rooms connected by long, dreary corridors.
</P>
<P>
   The day Levy first arrived -- exactly 109 days earlier, he
reminds a visitor -- the mammoth edifice at 110 Livingston Street
''was filthy. There was garbage in the halls. The word that leapt
out was Windex!''
</P>
<P>
   With signs warning Board of Ed employees not to bring in guns,
he added, ''this place was more depressing than Attica,'' the state
prison famous for a 1971 riot against the dreadful conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On a table outside Levy's office are pamphlets with lists of
weapons prohibited in city schools -- everything from shotguns,
switchblade knives and stilettos to scissors and broken glass. And
there's a list of punishments for students who do bring weapons to
class.
</P>
<P>
   Levy takes on such big issues -- as well as other ''stuff,'' as
he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   In January, with the temperature below freezing, he first walked
into his 10th-floor office and found two air conditioners going
full blast. He was told they were needed to regulate the antiquated
heating system, and the windows had to stay shut.
</P>
<P>
   On this warm spring day, the sun shone through an open window.
And ''open'' is the key word in changing what Levy calls the
board's ''barricade mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Livingston Street was a castle with high walls,'' he says.
''And people couldn't get through.''
</P>
<P>
   He's posted the direct phone numbers of top board officials on
the Internet ''so every parent knows,'' and he's streamlined the
organizational chart, ''which was two years old and looked like
plumbing.''
</P>
<P>
   A human meteor moving through the building, Levy fields urgent
messages from aides who pop up every few minutes, quickly returns
phone calls and pitches jokes -- all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Then he relaxes behind the conference table, shoving his
tasseled corporate shoe under his left leg as he answers a
reporter's questions. Behind him sits the jar of Twizzlers, twisted
red candy sticks, and the alphabet blocks, ''which I put in that
basket and offer to visitors to play with,'' he says jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Working 14-hour days, Levy returns to his Upper West Side home
late each night, seeing little of his wife and two children, a
9-year-old daughter and a 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ''I answer my e-mail in the middle of the night. I don't need
much sleep,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Levy has no formal background in education, though he belonged
to the city Bar Association's education committee and the state
Board of Regents, which oversees exams required for graduation.
</P>
<P>
   It's his corporate career that honed his skills for handling
problems ranging from violence to an often paralyzed bureaucracy.
From a Park Avenue office, Levy was director of global compliance
for Citigroup, and before that he was the chief litigator at what
was then known as Salomon Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, ''I was in charge of screwups,'' he adds, his eyes
twinkling behind wire-rim glasses.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked at a commodities firm, where lucite blocks
marking successful deals were dubbed ''tombstones.'' He had his own
granite slab made ''because I was trying to get the point across
that those lucite blocks are not what life is about.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's obviously not about the $245,000 salary he draws as
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   For him now, it's about injecting some corporate savvy -- ''and
humanity'' -- into a dusty bureaucratic dinosaur with a $10.6
billion annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Levy's 100-plus-day performance has been so
effective that last week, the last rival candidate pulled out of
the race for chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendents -- whose credentials Levy plans to
re-evaluate -- should now get ready for more inspired mail.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he's sending them replicas of a sign he keeps on his
work-littered desk.
</P>
<P>
   It says: ''I'm responsible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 0131 </TRAILER>
