<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peach Sculptor Creates Delicate Art  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID DISHNEAU
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICK, Md. (AP) -- Inside every peach is a pit, and inside
each pit is something Alfred LaBrush wants to show you.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a soaring eagle. Or a bear. Or a family of bears,
one with a salmon flapping in its jaws. It might be all these
things, set against a tumbling waterfall, painstakingly carved in a
three-dimensional, inch-high tableau.
</P>
<P>
   ''I should have been a surgeon,'' LaBrush says. Instead, the
self-taught artist, 58, has used his steady hands for 46 years to
chip away at the brittle stones, creating delicate, fanciful
sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   He has more than 75 of them, but the disabled printer never
exhibited his collection until last summer when he showed it at a
peach festival in nearby Thurmont.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for money -- he won't sell the carvings -- but for
charity. His booth was sponsored by a group opposed to drunken
drivers. Like the driver who smashed into LaBrush's pickup truck in
1996, leaving the artist's left arm and hand partially paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of the young people, when they see the collection, say,
'Gee, I thought just about everything had been done that can be
done,''' LaBrush says. ''There's still simple things out there,
just like finding these images in peach pits. You don't have to
drink and do drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash, along with injuries from an accident at work in 1992,
have slowed LaBrush's output, but speed isn't a concern. A
sculpture can take three months of work, on-again, off-again. He
finishes just one or two a year.
</P>
<P>
   And he treasures them all: the praying man that was his first
attempt at age 12; the whimsical human figure astride a giraffe;
the red-tailed hawk with paper-thin wings swooping down on a
mallard duck; the waterfall scene with two eagles, three bears and
a freshly caught salmon.
</P>
<P>
   A whittler since boyhood, he studies peach pits for images
outlined by surface ridges and creases -- ''Every one you pick up,
you can find something,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He cleans them in the washing machine and cures them in bleach
and water, a process that takes eight months or more. Then he chips
off everything that isn't part of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Some are relief carvings, like the painted climber in green
shirt and red pants crawling up the seed's horny surface. And there
are 3-D works so fragile that LaBrush sometimes snaps the figures
off while carving.
</P>
<P>
   A collector of waterfowl art once offered him $2,000 for one of
his works, LaBrush says.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was tempted,'' he admits. ''But I'd never be able to find
another one like that. They're one-of-a-kind and you just can't go
back and duplicate them.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBrush picks up extra cash by selling his more modest peach pit
pendants, engraved with images of flowers or the church spires of
Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   Peach-pit carving originated in China, where the fruit is a
symbol of longevity, according to Tim Hallman of the Asian Art
Museum in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, it flourishes in the South, where peach
orchards are plentiful, says Matt Lippa, a folk-art dealer in
Mentone, Ala. Baskets and monkeys are common themes; nature scenes
are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably more detailed than I have ever heard,'' Lippa
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Freeze, manager of the Thurmont peach festival, calls
LaBrush's work amazing. ''I can't even imagine being able to see
that teeny, tiny thing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   LaBrush expects to donate the collection to a museum and hopes
to teach the art to others.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be kind of selfish to be able to have all this and
not share it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 0153 </TRAILER>
