<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't, Rebels Set Terms  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- The government and Muslim guerrillas
both set new conditions Monday for the start of talks on freeing 21
Western and Asian hostages being held by the rebels in a southern
Philippine jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf rebel spokesman Abu Ahmad said the military must stop
all operations in the provinces where the rebels are holding
captives and allow the guerrillas to meet face-to-face with the
armed forces chief of staff and the national police chief.
</P>
<P>
   The government must also allow Abu Sayyaf leaders on the island
of Basilan to travel to the nearby island of Jolo, where the 21
hostages are held, so they can join in the talks, Ahmad told DXRZ
radio.
</P>
<P>
   The government, meanwhile, insisted on receiving a single
written set of demands from the rebels rather than the piecemeal,
informal demands they have been making for the release of the
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want them to make collective decisions,'' negotiator Robert
Aventajado said Monday. ''Otherwise, how can we hold negotiations
at all?''
</P>
<P>
   Aventajado, who flew to Manila late Sunday to consult with
President Joseph Estrada, said he planned to return to Jolo on
Tuesday and hoped to begin formal negotiations based on written
demands from the rebels the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without them putting their demands in writing, we'll just be
confused,'' Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage situation is one incident in the widespread rebel
violence -- the worst in years -- that has engulfed the southern
Philippines of late. Rebels and government troops have fought a
number of battles. In Basilan province, where rebels are holding a
separate group of hostages, four captives were shot and killed
during a May 3 firefight between rebels and troops.
</P>
<P>
   On the impoverished southern island of Mindanao on Sunday,
troops rescued 183 villagers who had been captured by the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front, the larger Muslim rebel group. Three
rebels died in a gun battle with the troops, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers had been seized Saturday by rebels who went from
house to house stealing food, officials said. They had spent the
night in the mountains in southern Sultan Kudarat province.
</P>
<P>
   A third group fighting the government, the communist insurgents
of the New People's Army, killed five people, including two
civilians, when its fighters ambushed a security patrol Saturday in
Mindanao, the military said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting in the region flared last month after the military
attacked MILF rebels occupying a section of highway near their main
camp on Mindanao. The MILF withdrew from peace talks after the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels have threatened to retaliate by striking government
targets in Manila, and early Sunday, a rocket-propelled grenade was
fired at national police headquarters in the city. Damage was
limited and no one was injured. A MILF leader would not comment on
whether his group was responsible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
