<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeders Party Returns To Power  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL GEITNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's biggest state returned Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats to power despite an attempt by
the scandal-plagued Christian Democrats to win votes by criticizing
the government's plans to import foreign high technology workers.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary results showed the Social Democrats finishing
Sunday's election in North Rhine-Westphalia with 42.8 percent of
the vote. Though enough to win, that was less than the 46 percent
they received in the western industrial state five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Christian Democrats received 37 percent of the
vote, according to ARD television, slightly less than the 37.7
percent they received in the last election in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbent Gov. Wolfgang Clement said he would open talks today
with his coalition partners, the Greens, even though they fell from
third-strongest in the statehouse to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens dropped from 10 percent of the vote in 1995 to 7
percent, while the pro-business Free Democrats -- who last time
didn't even clear the 5 percent threshold to enter parliament --
finished as the big gainers with nearly 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ''red-green'' coalition mirrors the one in Berlin,
leading many commentators to portray the state vote as a referendum
on the national government.
</P>
<P>
   Both Schroeder and Clement have cast themselves as
business-friendly centrists and sharply disagree with some of the
Greens' positions on issues such as energy taxes and transportation
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Moellemann, state chairman of the Free Democrats, called
on Clement to negotiate a coalition with his party rather than
stick with a ''coalition of the losers.'' Clement said he was ''in
principle'' ready to talk to all parties -- possibly a reminder to
the Greens not to overestimate their influence in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Democrats appeared to benefit the most from the slush
fund scandal that has plagued their erstwhile coalition partners,
the conservative Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The state election is the first since the Christian Democrats'
new, untainted leader -- a woman from former East Germany, Angela
Merkel -- took over the party last month with the promise of a fresh
start.
</P>
<P>
   Yet analysts said exit polls show the scandal over off-the-books
donations, secret bank accounts and possible influence peddling
under former Chancellor Helmut Kohl continued to cost the Christian
Democrats votes.
</P>
<P>
   The party's lead candidate, Juergen Ruettgers, sought to refocus
the campaign by attacking Schroeder's plans to issue 20,000 work
permits to foreigners to fill a critical labor shortage in the
high-tech and software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although his slogan ''Kinder statt Inder'' -- ''children instead
of Indians'' -- was even criticized by some members of his own party
as borderline xenophobic, Ruettgers credited it with helping the
party regain some lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers' position urges better training of German workers
rather than importing high-tech specialists, many of whom would
come from India.
</P>
<P>
   ''That motivated the people,'' he told German television. ''We
were able to focus on education and jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, voter turnout in the election was sharply lower. ARD said
around 56 percent of the state's 13 million eligible voters cast
ballots, down from 64 percent in the last election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
