<BODY>
<HEADLINE> He's on trial, she's under microscope  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- Westchester County's district
attorney, Jeanine Pirro, has not been accused of anything, but she
still finds herself embroiled in a $1 million tax fraud case that
begins this week against her husband.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six weeks or so, journalists and spectators will be
camped out at the federal courthouse, just outside Mrs. Pirro's
office, straining to hear any mention of her as testimony about
household expenses, family relationships and joint tax returns go
into the public record.
</P>
<P>
   With prosecutors already alleging that an auto loan she took out
was a sham used by her husband to cover tax fraud, there's a good
chance the trial will amount to another in a series of spousal
roadblocks that have limited Mrs. Pirro's political career.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Albert Pirro, and his brother and accountant,
Anthony, are accused of claiming business write-offs for
nondeductible expenses ranging from baby sitters to family
vacations to the investigators Albert hired during his unsuccessful
fight against a paternity suit.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' defense is to blame each other, with cutthroat
tactics that make it seem as if Cain and Abel had run afoul of the
Internal Revenue Service. Each has aired embarrassing family
laundry, and Albert, a top Republican fund-raiser and one of the
state's leading lobbyists, even hid a camcorder in his office and
tried to wheedle an unwitting Anthony into clearing him.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, Albert Pirro blames the feds, claiming his troubles
are part of a Clinton administration plan to hold down potential
GOP stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows that my wife could have been and should have
been a statewide candidate for political office by now,'' he said
in his office last month, with pictures of his wife arrayed behind
him. ''The only thing that has held her back is the fact that her
husband ... has been subjected to constant spotlight, scrutiny and
criticism.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White refused to comment on his
allegations, although the assistants who are prosecuting the case,
Elliott Jacobson and Cathy Seibel, requested a gag order after
Pirro made his comments.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro also would not comment on her husband's claims --
or any other questions about the trial or her relationship with her
husband. Defense attorneys have asked her not to comment, and she
fears anything she says might be misconstrued, her office says.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband was indicted in February 1999, however, Mrs.
Pirro expressed confidence he would be exonerated, providing the
rare sight of a top prosecutor predicting an acquittal. She also
said the federal investigation had been ''a very invasive and
hostile process for my husband and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would say whether Mrs. Pirro is to be called as a
witness.
</P>
<P>
   Now 48, the district attorney has been mentioned time and again
as a likely candidate for higher office, having won national
attention with appearances on ''Geraldo,'' ''Larry King Live'' and
People magazine's ''50 Most Beautiful People'' list. She has
specialized in prosecuting domestic violence and Internet
pedophilia cases and is Westchester's leading vote-getter.
</P>
<P>
   But her husband keeps getting in the way, politically:
</P>
<P>
   --In 1986, she withdrew as the Republican nominee for lieutenant
governor because he refused to divulge information about his law
practice.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1995, the paternity suit was filed and Albert Pirro
eventually acknowledged he is the father of an Indiana teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1997, a federal bribery investigation was launched after a
Yonkers official claimed Albert Pirro bribed him to expedite the
approval of a 10-screen theater. No charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   During that investigation, Jeanine Pirro angrily said,
''Whenever I run, there will be questions about my husband. That's
not only holding women to a different standard, that's saying,
'We're not looking at you as a person on your own.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the current case, Albert Pirro, 52, acknowledges problems
with his tax returns but notes they were prepared by his brother.
He blames the errors on ''Anthony's incompetence and his personal,
psychological and legal problems,'' including a 1992 cocaine
possession conviction in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In the camcorder escapade, which Judge Barrington Parker ruled
inadmissible, Pirro recorded his brother admitting that he prepared
the tax returns negligently and that Albert never asked him to do
anything illegal. Anthony, 45, also said investigators are ''trying
to put heat on me to come in and roll on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, in turn, revealed that Albert Pirro was admitted to a
psychiatric hospital in 1986 and has been treated with
anti-depressants and mood-stabilizing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gustave Newman, one of Albert Pirro's six defense lawyers, said
the hospitalization was for ''situational depression ... related to
the scrutiny that he experienced as the spouse of a person seeking
statewide elected office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Drafts Social Security Reforms  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- With the Social Security system now as old
as the retirees eligible to reap its benefits, George W. Bush today
was outlining his principles for reform -- including allowing
younger workers to privately invest some of their payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The principles, many of which have already trickled into stump
speeches by the Republican presidential contender, could present
one of the defining issues of the general election campaign.
Traditionally, touching the 65-year-old system has been considered
akin to grabbing a political third rail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody said, 'Why are you bringing up such a touchy
issue?''' the Texas governor said Friday. ''I said, 'Because I'm
running to lead, is why.'''
</P>
<P>
   He was outlining his plan during a speech at a senior citizens
center outside Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Besides pushing for private accounts, Bush is expected to pledge
to maintain current benefits for those at or near retirement; to
''lockbox'' payroll taxes to prevent borrowing against the Social
Security trust fund; and to refuse to increase the current 12.4
percent payroll tax used to fill the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Bush's Democratic opponent, calls Bush's
plans ''vague'' and has warned against privately managed Social
Security investments, labeling the idea ''stock market Roulette.''
</P>
<P>
   He also argues that Bush cannot afford his reforms because he
wants to use some of the projected federal budget surplus to
finance a five-year, $460 billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Gore favors paying down the national debt and using the savings
in interest payments to shore up the existing Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, delivering his own speech Social Security
today at Beaver College in Amber, Pa., said last week: ''Think
about what happens when that first generation of Americans retires
in a bear market. They would be left trying to live on worthless
paper and we as a nation could be left stuck with sky-high bailout
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of Social Security reform is driven by several
factors: an increase in life expectancy, the impending retirement
of the 77-million strong baby boom generation and the resulting
decline in the number of workers to support the retirees' benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The current system is funded through a ''tax-and-transfer''
method, in which benefits are paid directly with money collected
from payroll taxes. That leaves it vulnerable to a declining work
force and an increasing number of dependents. The existing system
is now projected to become insolvent in 2037.
</P>
<P>
   Bush argues that private investment accounts are a necessary and
cost-effective way to keep the system solvent.
</P>
<P>
   The private investment accounts he wants would be voluntary.
Although Bush has not specified how they would be funded, the most
commonly discussed method is diverting 2 percent of the
12.4-percent payroll tax.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts would face some regulation to guard against
speculation, but Bush argues that if the money is invested over
time, retirees will get the long-term benefits of compounding
interest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a 22-year-old earning $20,000 per year were
allowed to invest 2 percent of his payroll tax at the relatively
modest rate of return of 5.5 percent, by the time he retired at age
67, his account would be worth $101,775 -- plus his remaining Social
Security benefit.
</P>
<P>
   A person the same age earning $30,000 would be left with an
account of $152,675.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the existing system pays benefits derived from a
variety of factors, including a worker's former salary. The average
monthly check is $660, or about $8,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is betting his proposal will be embraced by the new class
of investors and e-traders who have propelled the stock market to
unprecedented heights.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating Gore's criticism, Bush told a group of senior
citizens in Davenport, Iowa, last week: ''It's become part of the
political process to say, 'OK, George Bush, don't vote for him,
he's going to take away your Social Security check.' People, I
think, in America are more sophisticated than that now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 0217 </TRAILER>
