<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, May 15, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Facing Showdown on Kosovo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- This week could be a decisive one for President Clinton's
policy of keeping U.S. troops in Kosovo, with showdowns likely in the Senate and
House that could ultimately force withdrawal of the peacekeepers next year. In
the Senate, there will be a tangle over bipartisan language in a routine
military construction spending bill requiring the Americans' removal from the
breakaway Yugoslav province beginning July 1, 2001, unless Congress votes to
keep them there. And there will be a renewed effort by a group of Democrats and
Republicans in the House to require the troops' withdrawal unless Clinton
certifies that Europeans are delivering promised aid for rebuilding the
violence-shattered Balkan enclave. The deadline would be next April 1.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Rocket To Soar With Russian Engine
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- In another symbolic farewell to the Cold War,
the rocket that served as America's first intercontinental ballistic missile and
carried John Glenn into orbit is set to lift off with the former enemy's engine.
Lockheed Martin Corp.'s Atlas III will be the first "Made-in-the-USA" rocket to
use Russian propulsion. It was scheduled to be launched Monday. U.S. and Russian
engineers behind the mission applaud this blasting away of barriers on the final
frontier.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Moms Rally for Strict Gun Control
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advocates of tighter gun control laws hope a mass turnout
of mothers and families at a weekend march will spur activism that breaks the
gridlock in the Republican-run Congress. Organizers of the "Million Mom March"
principally want trigger locks to protect children and a national system that
would register handguns and license their owners. They intend to maintain an
activist movement that will endorse and oppose political candidates based on gun
control positions. All major gun control legislation before Congress has been
stalled for a year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Rebels Free 139 UN Personnel
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) -- Sierra Leonean rebels holding 500 U.N.
peacekeepers have released 139 of their captives into Liberian custody,
according to Liberia's president. Charles Taylor said 15 of the freed captives
were flown by a government-chartered helicopter to Liberia's capital, Monrovia,
on Sunday evening while the remaining 124 were waiting to be evacuated from the
town of Foya on Liberia's border with Sierra Leone. A U.N. spokesman in Sierra
Leone's capital said he was unaware of the reported releases and officials at
the United Nations headquarters in New York were also unable to immediately
confirm the report.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Drafts Social Security Reforms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- With the Social Security system now as old as the
retirees eligible to reap its benefits, George W. Bush Monday was outlining his
principles for reform -- including allowing younger workers to privately invest
some of their payroll taxes. The principles, many of which have already trickled
into stump speeches by the Republican presidential contender, could present one
of the defining issues of the general election campaign. Traditionally, touching
the 65-year-old system has been considered akin to grabbing a political third
rail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Schroeders Party Returns To Power
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's biggest state returned Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democrats to power despite an attempt by the scandal-plagued
Christian Democrats to win votes by criticizing the government's plans to import
foreign high technology workers. Preliminary results showed the Social Democrats
finishing Sunday's election in North Rhine-Westphalia with 42.8 percent of the
vote. The opposition Christian Democrats received 37 percent of the vote,
according to ARD television, slightly less than the 37.7 percent they received
in the last election in the state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Saturn Cars To Offer Side Air Bags
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. will offer side curtain air bags on all
its Saturn models late this year and next year will begin installing dual-stage
air bags that can decide whether to inflate with less force. But GM will not
meet a deadline it had set for this year to roll out a system that stops the
passenger air bag from inflating if a child or child seat is in front of it. GM
said it had nearly perfected a suppression system but ran into problems in
testing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stock Prices Close Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 44.17 points to close at 17,313.69. 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Angels 7, Rangers 6
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Troy Glaus and Scott Spiezio hit back-to-back home
runs with one out in the ninth inning, and Mo Vaughn homered twice Sunday as the
Anaheim Angels beat the Texas Rangers 7-6. Ivan Rodriguez had put Texas ahead in
the ninth with a homer off Shigetoshi Hasegawa (2-0) that made him 3-for-3 with
two home runs as a pinch-hitter this season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
