<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 03:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Avoids a Big Hole in Schedule  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC can finally relax: Ross, Joey, Phoebe,
Rachel, Chandler and Monica are returning to the Central Perk next
season, ensuring the network doesn't have to worry about having to
fill a big hole on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The six cast members of ''Friends'' agreed in the predawn hours
Sunday to return for two more seasons, in a deal that will pay each
actor $20 million per year, according to executives close to the
talks who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had set a Sunday afternoon deadline for an agreement, or
else it had promised to go forward today with a schedule that
didn't include ''Friends'' in its customary 8 p.m. time slot on
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   All seven broadcast networks unveil their fall schedules to
advertisers this week, launching a rush to buy millions of dollars
in commercials.
</P>
<P>
   NBC enters into the week with several of its building blocks
already in place for several more years, including ''ER,'' ''Law
and Order'' and ''Law and Order: Special Victims Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The network was reportedly considering moving one of its most
popular comedies, ''Frasier,'' away from Thursday nights. The
long-running show starring Kelsey Grammer has been weakened
somewhat this year by ABC's ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing ''Friends'' would have been a major blow to NBC, which
has had trouble developing new comedies. Many people in the TV
industry believed the deal would get done, since the show was so
important to NBC and the cast members didn't seem eager to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Aniston, Courteney Cox Arquette, Lisa Kudrow, Matt
LeBlanc, Matthew Perry and David Schwimmer all will be getting a
big raise from the reported $125,000 they made for each of the 22
episodes this season.
</P>
<P>
   The six ''Friends'' will be paid $750,000 per episode for each
year. They also were given a greater percentage of the profits from
the sitcom's lucrative syndication deals, giving them each a total
of $40 million over two years, executives said Sunday. The stars
had reportedly been demanding $1 million each per episode to return
-- a sum NBC paid Helen Hunt and Paul Reiser for the final year of
''Mad About You.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators beat NBC's deadline by about 12 hours. The actors
reached the deal with Warner Brothers Television, the studio that
produces the show.
</P>
<P>
   '''Friends' is one of the best written, produced and directed
shows on television. We are thrilled and excited to continue,'' the
actors said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   The show finishes its sixth season with a one-hour special this
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nbc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 0337 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
