<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston, Santana Salute Clive Davis  </HEADLINE>
By BETH HARRIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Barry Manilow is having a flashback of the
musical kind. It's the early '70s and he's opening for Dionne
Warwick in New York's Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Davis comes to check out Manilow for the new record label
Davis has founded, called Arista. Manilow, signed to another label
to be absorbed by Arista, passes muster with Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came back to my trailer and said, 'Hi. Welcome to
Arista,''' Manilow said. ''I'm the oldest living Arista act. It
feels like it was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Manilow went on to score Arista's first No. 1 hit, ''Mandy,'' in
1975. He'd have 13 chart-toppers for the label that Davis named
after the honor society at his Brooklyn high school.
</P>
<P>
   Manilow is one of a dozen artists saluting Davis in ''25 Years
of No. 1 Hits: Arista Records' Anniversary Celebration,'' airing
Monday at 8 p.m. EDT on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour special serves up a star-studded parade of Arista
performers singing their biggest hits, which, in the case of Aretha
Franklin, Whitney Houston, Manilow and Santana, means medleys.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's portion of the April 10 taping was heavily scrutinized
after her unpredictable behavior resulted in her being dropped from
the Academy Awards telecast. A voiceover leading into a commercial
break teases viewers about ''the performance you've been hearing
about.''
</P>
<P>
   What viewers won't see is Houston tripping as she walks onstage,
and they won't hear her duet with Deborah Cox on ''Shoop Shoop.''
</P>
<P>
   But editing didn't remove all the spontaneity, including husband
Bobby Brown's two unscripted moments onstage. First, he appears
from the wings with a glass of water when Houston abruptly stops
before the high voltage conclusion to ''I Will Always Love You.''
They kiss and he dabs her sweaty forehead.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston is joined by Cox, Faith Evans, Monica and Angie
Stone on a free-for-all version of ''My Love is Your Love,'' Brown
pops out again. Houston hands him the microphone to jabber, and he
cavorts while she blends into the background.
</P>
<P>
   Houston belts out five songs before leaving the stage with the
cryptic line, ''The record's not over yet, remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's best moments are Santana's opening jam,
Franklin's three songs (taped in New York), Sean ''Puffy'' Combs
and a 30-member choir on ''I'll Be Missing You,'' and Patti Smith's
tear-it-up version of ''Because The Night,'' with Sarah McLachlan
on piano.
</P>
<P>
   Blessedly, the music is the focus. No time is wasted on thank
yous or testimonies on Davis' behalf. The songs speak for
themselves, which has always been Davis' aim.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the subsequent ouster of Davis as Arista CEO, the
show is an ironic valentine to the 66-year-old who nurtured the
careers of dozens of superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Even those he dismissed, such as Melissa Etheridge, have nothing
but kind words for Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not on Arista, but Clive was the first one to reject my
demo,'' said Etheridge, who introduces Annie Lennox on the show.
''He is the last of an amazing kind of musical businessman, musical
genius who supports the artist. I really admire Clive for sticking
to his principles, staying there and seeing it through.''
</P>
<P>
   BMG Entertainment, Arista's parent company, ended months of
speculation early this month when it replaced Davis with new CEO
Antonio Reid, 43. Reid co-founded LaFace Records in 1989 with
Kenneth ''Babyface'' Edmonds in a joint venture with Arista.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, whose Arista contract was not renewed, said he was the
victim of BMG's mandatory retirement age of 60, while the company
maintained the issue was Arista's long-term direction.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he plans to start a record company this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never count him out,'' Warwick told reporters backstage at the
tribute. ''Clive will come up with something absolutely incredible
and there he'll be all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' musical tastes run the gamut from country to rock to
soul, and he's signed hitmakers in all categories, including
country stars Alan Jackson and Brooks &AMP; Dunn, who perform a rousing
version of ''My Maria.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He seems to have a great expertise in all of it,'' Kix Brooks
said. ''He definitely has the respect of all genres.''
</P>
<P>
   Vintage clips interspersed throughout the show feature such
diverse Arista acts as the Bay City Rollers, big-haired '70s
singers Melissa Manchester and Eric Carmen, Air Supply, The Kinks
and the Grateful Dead. The mercifully brief song snippets also
serve up such one-hit wonders as Ace of Base, Ray Parker Jr., Real
McCoy and Lisa Stansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gets his moment in the spotlight at the end, and his
comments made a month before his ouster seem prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a ride it's been,'' he says, thanking colleagues at
Arista and BMG. ''This special night says everything. It's all
about the music and it's all about the artists.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   HIGH PROFILE: ''Bravo Profiles'' kicks off a season of 40 new
episodes with a look at the career of actress Goldie Hawn, from
giggling go-go dancer on TV's ''Laugh-In'' to Oscar-winning actress
(''Cactus Flower'') and film producer. ''Bravo Profiles: Goldie
Hawn,'' debuting 10 p.m. EDT Monday, also looks at Hawn's personal
life, including her longtime relationship with Kurt Russell and the
emergence of her daughter, Kate Hudson, as an actress. Among those
featured in upcoming profiles: designer Vera Wang, director Julie
Taymor and actor John Leguizamo.
</P>
</TEXT>
