<HEADLINE> Troubled office supply company taps new CEO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CORTLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- The troubled office supply company that
last month lost its Nasdaq slot has named a new leader.
</P>
<P>
   Martin D. Wilson, 40, has been named chief executive officer of
Smith Corona, replacing John A. Bermingham and ending Bermingham's
two-year reign. Company officials did not give a reason for
Bermingham's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson retains the titles of president, chief financial officer
and treasurer, positions he's held since October 1998 and May 1999,
respectively. He joined the company in 1994 as director of
accounting and financial reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Boden, who had served as chief operating officer for
the last three months, will continue to work with the company as a
consultant, company officials said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Boden is the managing partner of Positive Business Change, a
Cincinnati-based company that consults on marketing and finances.
</P>
<P>
   Smith Corona -- which traces its roots to the L.C. Smith &AMP; Bros.
Typewriter Co. founded in Syracuse in 1903 -- stopped making
products when it emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings in
1997. The firm's subsequent transformation from a manufacturer to
seller has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Nasdaq told Smith Corona its shares could no longer
trade on that stock market because the company had slipped below
its financial requirements.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in four years an exchange dropped Smith
Corona's stock. In June 1996, the New York Stock Exchange removed
the stock from its listing after Smith Corona's bankruptcy
reorganization plan proposed making the stock worthless.
</P>
<P>
   The company has lost 43 workers since January, and now has about
50 employees. The company reported its net worth as $560,000 for
the six months ending Dec. 31, compared with $4.4 million for the
same period the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
