<HEADLINE> Dow Up 45; Nasdaq Down 29  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, but as the Federal
Reserve's decision on interest rates drew near, few investors were
taking on major new positions.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 45.23 at 10,654.60.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 29.78 at 3,499.28 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 0.81 at 1,421.77.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers were anticipating a quiet session. On Tuesday,
the Fed's Open Market Committee is widely expected to raise
interest rates for the sixth time since last June in its continuing
effort to cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Fed offered the latest indication that the economy
remains extremely robust. The Fed said industrial production posted
its biggest leap in April in more than a year, as output at the
nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq Stock Market, Lycos rose 6{ to 60|. The Wall
Street Journal reported that Spain's Terra Networks SA is in
serious discussions to acquire Lycos for at least $10 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many other high-profile technology names were lower, however.
Cisco Systems was down 1 3/16 to 58} and PMC-Sierra was down 3
19/64 to 142 41/64.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow components, Philip Morris rose 1 9/16 to 25~. The Wall
Street Journal reported the company has offered to buy the food
business of Nabisco Group Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to a paltry 99.7
million shares, compared with 117.4 million at the same time on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.13 to 486.81.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.3 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 0.4 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.03 percent.
</P>
