<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Lobbyist Tax Challenge  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge
to the way the federal government taxes the lobbying expenses of
nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away arguments by the
American Society of Association Executives that the tax is higher
than ordinary rates and therefore amounts to an unfair levy on
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1993, businesses and nonprofit associations could deduct
lobbying expenses from their taxes. That year, Congress eliminated
the deduction for commercial businesses and established a new tax
applying to nonprofit organizations, other than charities.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations subject to the new tax include professional
societies, trade associations, advocacy groups, labor unions and
other not-for-profit associations.
</P>
<P>
   They must either pay a flat 35 percent tax rate on lobbying
expenses or have their dues-paying members pay the tax directly to
the government.
</P>
<P>
   If a group chooses the second option, all of the tax liability
is passed on to its members even if some of the lobbying was funded
with other income besides dues. Some non-dues income also is
taxable under another federal provision.
</P>
<P>
   The association executives' group, representing about 22,000
executives and staff members of nonprofit professional
associations, sued the federal government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said either form of the tax is higher than ordinary
tax rates, and therefore the tax is a penalty on lobbying that
violates the Constitution's free-speech and equal-protection
guarntees.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge and the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia upheld the tax. The appeals court said in a
ruling last November that organizations can avoid an extra tax
burden by splitting into two associations -- one that does no
lobbying and one that only lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying group could be funded by taxable dues, and the
non-lobbying group could be funded with non-taxable dues, the
appeals court said.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, the association's lawyers said
that alternative would not work because the government still can
tax such dual organizations as if they were one entity.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers said the tax ''was not enacted to
penalize speech nor does it have that effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is American Society of Association Executives vs. U.S.,
99-1321.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov./links.html and click on District of
Columbia Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1022 </TRAILER>
