<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Clarifies Traffic Stop Rules  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to let police
in Florida order passengers to remain in vehicles, along with the
driver, during routine traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, without comment, rejected an appeal in which
prosecutors said a state court was wrong to rule that such a police
order violated passengers' privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, the nation's highest court ruled in a
Maryland case that passengers -- as well as drivers -- can be ordered
to get out of vehicles during routine traffic stops. The Florida
case presented the opposite situation, one in which police want
everyone to remain inside the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Today's action is not a decision and sets no legal precedent
outside Florida. It does not preclude the possibility the justices
will choose to address the issue in another case in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wilson was a passenger in a car stopped by Palm Beach
Sheriff's Deputy Sean Murray on July 6, 1997. The deputy said the
car had been speeding and bore a license tag registered to another
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   As Murray approached the car from the driver's side, Wilson got
out and began walking to a tavern just five to 10 feet away. Murray
ordered him to return to the car and remain inside until the
traffic stop was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Murray later testified he did so out of concern for his safety
but acknowledged that he had no reason to suspect that Wilson posed
any threat.
</P>
<P>
   After Wilson returned to the car, Murray noticed that the car's
driver was extremely nervous, and that he had attempted to conceal
something under the front seat. After discovering the driver had no
license, Murray arrested him and placed him in his cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Murray testified that when he returned to the stopped car he saw
Wilson trying to conceal something on the floorboard. He then saw a
marijuana pipe sticking out from under the front seat. Murray
ordered Wilson out of the car and patted him down, finding cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson pleaded no contest, reserving the right to appeal a trial
judge's ruling that the seized evidence could be used against him.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court ruled last year that the evidence should
have been suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The traffic violation sufficiently justifies subjecting the
driver to detention -- in or outside the vehicle,'' the state court
said. ''There is a legitimate need for adequate police control over
the traffic violator for the time necessary to conclude the
business of the stop.
</P>
<P>
   ''The restraint on the liberty of the blameless passenger is, in
contrast, an unreasonable interference,'' the state court said.
Police may not order passengers to remain with a stopped car ''as a
matter of course'' when there's no reason to suspect they present a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Supreme Court rejected the state's appeal last
December.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, state prosecutors said,
''Authorizing the police to determine how to best proceed with a
traffic stop, including when passengers are present, will minimize
the risk of harm to both the police and the car's occupants.''
</P>
<P>
   The case is Florida vs. Wilson, 99-1468.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1023 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Sidesteps U.S.-Iceland Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today steered clear of a
shipping dispute between a company in Iceland and the U.S.
government.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, turned away the company's argument
that contracts awarded in 1998 for shipping military cargo to a
U.S. base in Iceland violated a 14-year-old treaty between Iceland
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration waived its right to file a response
to the appeal, and the justices did not request one as they do in
some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal had been filed by the Iceland Steamship Co.
Ltd.-Eimskip. The Republic of Iceland government had supported the
company as a ''friend of the court'' when the case was in the
appeals court but did not file a similar brief in the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Military supplies for the U.S.-operated North Atlantic Treaty
Organization base at Keflavik, Iceland, were carried exclusively by
Icelandic-owned and operated shipping companies from the late 1960s
to 1984, the year a U.S.-flag carrier was created to serve the same
route.
</P>
<P>
   Under U.S. law, that company was entitled to carry 100 percent
of the military cargo shipped to the base, which caused a
diplomatic rift between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute was resolved in 1986 when the two signed a treaty to
ensure ''that both United States flag carriers and Icelandic
shipping companies are able to maintain a viable presence in the
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty's terms, Icelandic and U.S. companies compete
periodically for the military cargo shipping contracts. The lower
bidder is awarded 65 percent of the cargo-shipping contracts; the
remaining 35 percent is awarded to the next lowest bidder of the
other country.
</P>
<P>
   That system worked without controversy for 12 years, until in
1998 the two companies awarded contracts were TransAtlantic
Lines-Iceland EHF and U.S.-based TransAtlantic Lines LLC.
</P>
<P>
   One person, Gudmundur Kjarnested, effectively managed both
firms. A citizen of Iceland who is a U.S. resident alien, he was
president of one of the firms and vice president of the other and
signed both companies' bids.
</P>
<P>
   After the U.S. Department of the Army made those awards,
Iceland's government sent a diplomatic note to the U.S. State
Department. It said the contracts violated the 1986 treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland Steamship sued the Army in 1998, and a federal judge in
the District of Columbia ruled that the 1986 treaty had been
violated.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia
reversed that ruling, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''TLI and TLL are separate entities and are entitled to be
treated as such,'' the appeals court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Iceland Steamship said
the appeals court wrongly deferred to the State Department's
interpretation of the treaty while ignoring the Iceland
government's conflicting interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   The case is The Iceland Steamship Co. Ltd.-Eimskip vs. U.S.
Department of the Army, 99-1631.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on D.C. Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1023 </TRAILER>
