<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Nixes Louisiana Campaign Law  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to revive
Louisiana's ban on political campaign contributions by some people
licensed to operate video poker machines.
</P>
<P>
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal in which state
officials argued that the ban was a valid attempt to avoid ''the
appearance of corruption'' by gambling interests.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana is one of eight states with some type of ban on
campaign contributions by people involved in the gambling industry.
The justices were told that other states are Indiana, Iowa,
Kentucky, Michigan, Nebraska, New Jersey and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana's law, enacted in 1996, bans contributions to state
and local political candidates by people licensed to distribute
video poker devices or people who own truck stops or other
facilities licensed to offer video poker.
</P>
<P>
   The ban applies to anyone who directly owns at least 10 percent
of such a facility, or indirectly owns at least 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The law was challenged last year by a group of truck stop owners
licensed to operate video poker. They said the law discriminated
against them and violated their free-association rights as
protected by the Constitution's First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   A state judge struck down the law and the Louisiana Supreme
Court agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state offers no support for its contention that these
prohibitions will prevent corruption,'' the state's highest court
ruled, noting that Louisiana limits the size of all contributions
to state and local candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The state court also noted that the ban applied only to some
video poker licensees but not others, and that it did not apply to
the actual owners of the machines.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on today, the state's lawyers said there is
a ''public perception that gaming is associated with political
corruption'' and that those in the gambling industry can be barred
from making political contributions as a ''trade-off'' for their
state licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The video poker operators' lawyers said, ''The state cannot say
that the gaming industry is inherently vulnerable to corruption.''
There is no ''vice exception'' to the First Amendment, they added.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Louisiana vs. Penn, 99-1473.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the state court ruling in Penn v. Louisiana:
http://www.courts.net and click on Louisiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
