<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital Bribes Can Be Federal Crime  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The money hospitals receive for treating
Medicare patients subjects people who bribe hospital officials to
federal prosecutions, the Supreme Court ruled today.
</P>
<P>
   By a 7-2 vote in a case from Volusia County, Fla., the court
said such Medicare funding can be the basis for invoking a law that
makes it a crime to bribe agents of organizations and programs that
receive federal money.
</P>
<P>
   The law, enacted by Congress in 1984, federalized what otherwise
would be considered an ordinary case of commercial bribery
routinely handled in state courts, the decision said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has a legitimate and significant interest in
prohibiting financial fraud or acts of bribery being perpetrated
upon Medicare providers,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the
court. ''Fraudulent acts threaten the program's integrity. They
raise the risk participating organizations will lack the resources
... to provide the level and quality of care envisioned by the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Allan Fischer was convicted of violating the federal law
and was sentenced to five years and five months in prison after a
company he ran and partially owned received a $1.2 million loan in
1993 from the West Volusia Hospital Authority, a county agency that
used to run two hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The law at issue bans bribes involving the business of any
organization that ''receives in any one-year period benefits in
excess of $10,000 under a federal program involving ... federal
assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The West Volusia Hospital Authority had received between $10
million and $15 million in Medicare payments in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer had been president of Quality Medical Consultants, a
company that performed billing audits for health care providers.
Federal prosecutors said he paid $10,000 to a hospital official's
mother in return for the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer was convicted after a federal trial in Orlando. In
addition to his prison time, he was sentenced to three years of
supervised release and ordered to pay $1.2 million in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   He previously had left his job at QMC, and the company had filed
for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer early on challenged the legitimacy of his federal
prosecution, contending that ''payments to health care providers
for services to Medicare patients do not meet the jurisdictional
requirements'' of the federal law used to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rejected
that argument, but other federal appeals courts have ruled that
Medicare money cannot be the basis for such prosecutions. Today's
decision resolved those conflicting rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Health care providers such as the one defrauded by (Fischer)
receive benefits within the meaning of the statute,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia dissented. Writing
for the two, Thomas said, ''The only persons who receive 'benefits'
under Medicare are the individual elderly and disabled Medicare
patients, not the medical providers who serve them.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's highest court gave a broad reading to the same
federal law when it ruled in 1997 that it targets any transaction
of federally funded organizations and not merely transactions
involving or affecting federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   But that ruling left open the possibility that some connection
between a bribe and the expenditure of federal money might be
required.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors had urged the justices to rule that the
federal law applies to cases like Fischer's. But his call for a far
narrower interpretation of the law was supported by the National
Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Fischer vs. U.S., 99-116.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/ Click on ''this month's
decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
