<HEADLINE> Viag, Veba To Merge Chemical Units  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- In advance of their planned merger,
German energy powerhouses Veba AG and Viag AG said today they would
combine their chemical subsidiaries into a company focusing on
specialty chemicals by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The newly merged company, to be called Degussa AG, will bring
together chemical groups Degussa-Huels AG, owned by Veba, and SKW
Trostberg AG, owned by Viag.
</P>
<P>
   Veba and Viag announced last September plans to merge in a $12.6
billion deal, but the deal has yet to gain antitrust approval
because of their holdings in other German utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The core of the merged Viag and Veba will be its electricity
division, but the company also said it plans to enlarge its gas and
water business as well as beef up its chemical arm in the United
States and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Degussa will aim to become the world's largest specialty
chemicals company in terms of sales, doubling revenue to between
$16.4 billion and $18.2 billion within the next four years, the
parent companies said.
</P>
<P>
   By combining operations, the streamlined company also hopes to
cut costs and boost earnings by $273 million within the next three
years, they added. Part of that will entail nearly 3,000 layoffs
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Degussa's chairman Uwe-Ernst Bufe resigned Monday and will be
replaced temporarily by current chief financial officer
Heinz-Joachim Wagner. The chairman of the new Degussa will be
Utz-Hellmuth Felcht from SKW Trostberg, while Wagner will become
chief financial officer of the new company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
