   BEIJING (AP) -- Amid guarded optimism on prospects for a deal,
Chinese and European trade negotiators resumed talks today on
China's hoped-for entry into the World Trade Organization. Pascal
Lamy, the European Union's trade commissioner, and Chinese foreign
trade minister Shi Guangsheng met for more than 90 minutes. They
left technical teams to hash out details, Lamy said, and he and Shi
agreed to try again for an agreement tomorrow. Shortly after
arriving in Beijing this morning, Lamy said he hoped that this
round of talks, the fourth this year, would yield agreement.
</P>
<P>
   German Travel Co. To Buy Brit rival
</P>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany (AP) -- Europe's largest package tour provider,
Germany's Preussag AG, is buying Thomson Travel Group PLC for $2.73
billion, topping a German competitor that had also been pursuing
Britain's biggest travel company. Preussag said today that
Thomson's board had accepted the bid -- which values Thomson at
$2.73 a share -- and has decided to recommend that shareholders
approve the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Faults Deutsche Bank Unit
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's securities watchdog said today it has
formally recommended penalties for Deutsche Bank AG's securities
unit in Tokyo after an inspection disclosed illegal transactions.
The penalties were not disclosed, but Japanese media reported today
that regulators will likely order the unit later this month to stop
trading bonds and bond futures for several weeks. The Securities
and Exchange Surveillance Commission said the Tokyo branch of
Deutsche Securities Co., a wholly owned subsidiary of Deutsche
Bank, was involved in several illegal transactions including
soliciting clients with financial products intended to hide their
trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   Caller ID Traced 'Love Bug' Virus
</P>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A local Internet provider said today
it used caller ID to trace the origin of the ''Love Bug'' e-mail
virus to a Manila phone line that had been used before for breaking
into its computer network. The disclosure explained how
investigators were quickly able to center their investigation on
the residents of an apartment in a lower middle-class Manila
neighborhood, including a young computer student who has
acknowledged he may have accidentally unleashed the ''ILOVEYOU''
virus. Sky Internet said the rogue program first sent copies of
itself to e-mail addresses contained on victimized computers. It
then used the computer's Internet browser to run a program placed
on a Sky Internet Web server to steal passwords stored in the
computer and send them to an e-mail address at another Philippine
Internet access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Readies Land for Disney
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- The government signed the first land
reclamation contract for Hong Kong's planned Disney theme park
today with a local construction company. Y.C. Lo, the territory's
civil engineering director, signed a $510 million contract with
HAM-HK Construction Joint Venture to reclaim an area of about 494
acres at Penny's Bay off the outlying Lautau Island, a government
statement said. The reclamation project is scheduled to be
completed by January 2003. Environmentalists say extensive
reclamation at the uninha ited area may damage marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks Eyes Asia Coffee Plant
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE (AP) -- Starbucks Coffee Co. said Monday it may build a
coffee roasting plant in Asia to replace imports from its
Seattle-based plant. Peter Maslen, president of Starbucks Coffee
International, said that Starbucks was looking at several
locations, such as the Philippines, Hong Kong and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia Growth Less Than Expected
</P>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's economy had slower growth
than expected in the first quarter, leading a senior government
official to warn that political instability could set back the
country's recovery. The gross domestic product grew by 3.21 percent
this past quarter from a year ago, the Central Bureau of Statistics
said today, less than the 4 percent to 5 percent growth that had
been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Asian Stock Markets Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower today on
expectations of a rise in U.S. interest rates. In Hong Kong, the
blue-chip Hang Seng Index shed 230.64 points, or 1.53 percent,
closing at 14,881.30. On Friday, the index had soared 619.02
points, or 4.3 percent. The U.S. Federal Reserve is expected to
raise interest rates at a meeting tomorrow. The Hong Kong market
was also pushed down by rising tensions between Taiwan and China
pending the inauguration of Taiwanese president-elect Chen
Shui-bian later this week, they said. The Japanese benchmark
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 44.17 points, or 0.25 percent,
to 17,313.69 points. In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was
quoted at 108.90 yen, up 0.60 yen from Friday in Tokyo and
marginally above its level of 108.89 yen late Friday in New York.
Indonesian shares closed sharply lower, with blue chips sustaining
heavy losses after investors were rattled by riots in Jakarta on
Saturday.
</P>
