<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Down on Weather News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices plunged in early dealings today on
the Chicago Board of Trade after new forecasts called for midweek
showers in the soybean belt. Grain prices also tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   The changing weather outlook sent the near-term soybean contract
to its lowest level in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures also fell sharply, pressured by forecasts calling
for favorable weather in the second half of May.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat sank, too, although the decline was not as steep. Prices
were pushed lower by the big dips in soybeans and corn.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 4} cents to $2.79{ a bushel; July
corn fell 6\ cents to $2.39{ a bushel; July oats fell 2\ cents to
$1.20 a bushel; July soybeans fell 18} cents to $5.47 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were mixed in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were lower.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle were unchanged at 67.92 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle rose .30 cent to 83.90 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell 1.15 cent to 71.70 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 2.48
cents to 86.62 cents a pound.
</P>
