<HEADLINE> Report: Others Sought Nabisco  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos., France's Danone SA and
Britain's Cadbury Schweppes PLC have reportedly made preliminary
offers for all or part of Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food company
that makes Ritz crackers and Oreo cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported today that R. J. Reynolds
Tobacco Holdings Inc. has also indicated it is interested in
bidding for Nabisco's controlling shareholder, Nabisco Group
Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nabisco Group Holdings and Nabisco Holdings soared on
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The bids were reportedly made as part of the auction process
that Nabisco Group Holdings launched last month after financier
Carl Icahn said he was prepared to make an offer for the 90.4
percent of Nabisco Group that he doesn't already own.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn, who owns about 31 million of the company's 326 million
shares, disclosed Friday that he told the auctioneers he would pay
$22 a share for the rest, or about $6.49 billion. The Journal said
it couldn't determine a value for the other offers.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group owns 80.5 percent of the food company Nabisco
Holdings, and hired investment bankers to explore its options,
including selling itself or its stake in Nabisco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   In trading today on the New York Stock Exchange, Nabisco Group
shares climbed 13.3 percent, or $2.06\, to $22.31\ by midday while
Nabisco Holdings stock rose 7 percent, or by $3.06\, to $47 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group, the successor to the company that spun off R.J.
Reynolds Tobacco last summer, has been trading at a discount to the
food company in part because of fears that those who may win legal
claims against the tobacco company could press for payment from its
former parent.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group, based in Parsippany, N.J., declined to comment on
who may have submitted bids.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal, citing unidentified people familiar with the
matter, said Philip Morris, owner of Kraft Foods as well as the
nation's biggest cigarette company, and Danone, which has a large
cookie and cracker business, had each bid for the food business.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Cadbury Schweppes PLC has bid for the
non-biscuit portion of Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said bankers have speculated that Nabisco Holdings
might fetch as much as $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal said R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, which was spun off by
the predecessor to Nabisco Group last year, formally expressed an
interest in buying the holding company once it sells the food
business.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Cadbury Schweppes and R.J. Reynolds declined
comment and calls to Philip Morris and Danone were not immediately
returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
