<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three cities say programs taking guns off streets  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three Connecticut cities participating in a federal initiative
to buy back guns say they have retrieved hundreds of weapons and
taken a small but sure step toward stopping gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Officials concede few criminals are likely to turn in their
weapons in exchange for a gift certificate. But they say they are
cutting the risk that guns kept in homes will be stolen or
mishandled by children.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can prevent one gun from being taken, one child from
getting hurt, it's a good program,'' said New Britain Police Chief
William Sencio.
</P>
<P>
   New Britain, Hartford and Stamford are taking part in Buyback
America, a $10.5 million initiative by the U.S. Department of
Housing and Urban Development. More than 80 cities are
participating in the program launched in September 1999 by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   HUD officials reported last week that more than 10,000 guns have
been collected so far in 43 cities. The program has come under
fire, though, from Republicans who claim HUD does not have the
authority to spend anti-drug money on gun buybacks, and the
National Rifle Association which says the money would be better
spent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buyback programs help communities feel empowered when you have
state legislatures that won't do anything to stop violence and
Congress bottles up gun safety bills for years,'' said Brian
Morton, a spokesman for Handgun Control Inc., a Washington
D.C.-based gun control organization. ''And they take guns out of
places where tragedies can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hartford, where the city put up $10,000 to buy back guns, 80
weapons have come in since April 28, said Hartford police Sgt. Neil
Dryfe. In exchange, people receive $100 vouchers to an area
restaurant or store.
</P>
<P>
   The guns -- a mix of handguns, rifles and shotguns -- came in more
quickly than expected and city officials were considering
allocating more money for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford conducted its program on five Saturdays in April and
collected 77 guns, said Edward Schwartz, executive director of the
city's Housing Authority. Vouchers were handed out in varying
amounts depending on the type of weapon and whether it worked. A
rusted pellet gun would merit $10 while a functional assault weapon
would be worth $200.
</P>
<P>
   Forty of the weapons were handguns, and all but three were still
operational, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The continuing theme of returns was, 'I'm so glad to get this
out of the house,''' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The city earmarked $71,500 for the program -- $21,000 of that
from HUD. A portion of the funding will go toward handing out
thousands of trigger locks at community events this summer.
</P>
<P>
   New Britain's program began Friday with the retrieval of one
gun, a .22-caliber Colt revolver from a mother of four who no
longer wanted her late father's weapon in her home, Sencio said.
With an allocation of $7,500, the city can give out $75 vouchers
for 100 guns.
</P>
<P>
   The guns are traced to ensure they were not stolen or used in a
crime and then destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 1254 </TRAILER>
