<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ullman Directs Bergman Tale  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France (AP)-- Almost 30 years ago, she appeared on the
world's movie screens in Ingmar Bergman's ''Scenes From a
Marriage,'' a searing look at marriage, infidelity and divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Now at 60, Liv Ullman again examines the corrosive force of
infidelity, this time from behind the camera. But the link to
Bergman remains; ''Faithless'' is based on a painful episode in his
life. When the 79-year-old Swedish legend couldn't bear to direct
it himself, he turned to Ullman, his longtime muse.
</P>
<P>
   The film has drawn attention at Cannes not only for the highly
personal nature of the story, but for the powerhouse performance of
its lead actress, Lena Endre, who appears in nearly every frame and
is already being touted for a best actress award.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bergman was unable to turn his story, about his own
destructive affair with a married woman, into a film for many years
-- until he saw Endre, an accomplished stage actress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only when he saw this face, and this actress, could he make
the movie,'' Ullman says.
</P>
<P>
   Ullman, with 40 films as an actress and several Oscar
nominations to her name, has directed only four films, including
''Faithless.'' But the Norwegian star says firmly that now, she
sees herself behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm 60 years old, and they don't make parts for me anymore,''
she says. ''I love to direct. That's what I want to do now. Maybe
when I am 70, I will change again.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her longtime collaboration with Bergman -- the two had a
five-year relationship that produced a daughter -- it is both a
blessing and a constraint, but mostly the former.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes I get a little tired of it,'' Ullman says. Then she
laughs. ''But you know, what a privilege, to get tired of working
with Ingmar Bergman.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three hours long, ''Faithless'' is heavy going, and won't
be everyone's cup of tea. But it is undeniably powerful in the same
way as the 1973 ''Scenes from a Marriage,'' a seminal film about
infidelity. And Endre's performance, which seems to run the entire
gamut of human emotions, more than carries the film.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what life experiences she used to portray her character,
Endre replies simply: ''Every personal experience I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman is incarnated in two characters in the film. His elder
self is an aging director, named Bergman, who is trying to write a
screenplay about the breakup of a marriage. This character is
played by Erland Josephson, who played Ullman's husband in ''Scenes
from a Marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The director summons an actress -- Endre -- to help him by telling
the story of Marianne (also played by Endre). Bergman's younger
self is David -- the narcisisstic lover with whom Marianne becomes
entangled, destroying her marriage and harming her child.
</P>
<P>
   David is a director too, and his last name is Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne starts out happily married to Markus, a world-renowned
conductor. The two have a 9-year-old daughter to whom they are
devoted. But one day, David, the couple's best friend, happens to
spend a night at Marianne's house while Markus is gone. This
launches an affair that is consummated in a romantic getaway in
Paris. Marianne is swept up in the desire to live a little
dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy begins in earnest with a powerful scene in which
Markus arrives at David's small apartment and catches the couple in
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Markus, in utter shock and horror, the naked couple
laughs, as people sometimes do when they are in distress, then
cries, then laughs and cries again. Ullman says that when the scene
was completed, the actors didn't even know they'd been laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage over, an awful legal ordeal ensues, and the film
hurtles toward a surprising and tragic climax.
</P>
<P>
   Some viewers may find the film too long, or David's character
somewhat unsympathetic -- but that seems to be the intent. Bergman
is known for being hard on himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
