<DOCNO> APW20000515.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani: No decision yet on cancer treatment or Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said today he hasn't
decided on what treatment he will get for his prostate cancer, let
alone whether he will continue his bid for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have not completed the external or internal process that I
have put in place,'' he said, disputing a Newsweek magazine report
that he had decided to undergo surgery and radiation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has learned from talking with others with cancer that
''you change your mind about it probably 10 times before you make
the decision'' on treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes I wake up and think one way will be best, and
sometimes I wake up and think the other way will be best,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did say he had canceled planned fund-raisers in California
that had been scheduled for Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Told by reporters that Giuliani had not yet made a decision,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, his Democratic Senate rival, said today at
a Manhattan news conference: ''I have no control over what the
Republicans do. ... I'm just not thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was unable to focus on medical decisions last
week, when he announced that he and his wife of 16 years, Donna
Hanover, were discussing a separation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last week, because of things involving my personal life, my
family and everything else, I didn't have the time,'' he said about
his need to consult physicians and decide what to do next. ''So I'm
going to need to do that this week. I'm going to need to do it
today, tomorrow, the next day. I don't know. You can't put a time
frame on this.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing the very very best that I can to make the decisions
that have to be made and I will focus on it very much this week,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Democrats were predicting that his Senate campaign was
finished.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all over but the shouting,'' Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
said on CNN's ''Late Edition'' on Sunday. ''As far as becoming the
next U.S. senator, forget it! He never really wanted the job.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to withdraw, and it has to be before the end of the
month because the Republican convention is taking place,'' former
Mayor Ed Koch told ABC's ''This Week.'' ''There's no question in my
mind he will drop out.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sources would only say that Giuliani hadn't yet made up his
mind, while Giuliani's campaign spokesman, Bruce Teitelbaum,
stated, in a gloomy tone of voice, ''I've got no comment on
anything. I've got nothing to say on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Molinari, a Republican former congresswoman from
Staten Island, told NBC's ''Meet the Press'': ''Nobody knows at
this point. I talked to the mayor's staff as late as yesterday
(Saturday). They are still waiting for him to come to a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ''If there is one person in the United States of
America who can handle that pressure and rise to the challenge and
in fact may even be spurred on by that pressure, it's Mayor
Giuliani. ... He's tougher and stronger than anyone ever gives him
credit for, so don't count him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinari added that neither she nor her husband, former Rep.
Bill Paxon, R-Buffalo, was interested in running if Giuliani does
not.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover publicly accused Giuliani of having had an affair with a
former City Hall aide. The mayor is also flaunting an ongoing
relationship with a third woman, Judith Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on ''Fox News,'' Rep. Vito Fossella, R-Staten Island,
added: ''He needs to take the bullets if he can, and I think there
will be a lot of people in New York who are still very much behind
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, the GOP's strongest potential candidate, has
said he's not interested in taking Giuliani's place, but Rep. Rick
Lazio, R-Long Island, and Wall Street multimillionaire Ted
Forstmann have expressed interest in running if Giuliani drops out.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, R-Long Island, told ''Meet the Press'' he would
pursue the nomination but said it was too soon to write Giuliani
off.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in Sunday's New York Post showed Clinton and
Giuliani neck and neck, with 42 percent supporting the first lady
and 40 percent supporting the mayor. Clinton's small lead is well
within the poll's 4.5-point margin of error. Only a third of voters
said Giuliani's troubles ''diminish his stature.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AP Political Writer Marc Humbert contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
