<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two S.C. Republicans Jump Ship  </HEADLINE>
By LEIGH STROPE
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Bill Clinton is almost gone from the White
House, crime is down and tax cuts don't sell the way they used to.
Some Republicans figure they might as well be Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In a single week recently, two Republicans in the Legislature
jumped to the Democratic Party in what former Democratic National
Committee chairman Don Fowler said was the first such switch in
South Carolina since Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Mickey Whatley and Margaret Gamble, both moderate
Republicans, said they were fed up with being bullied to vote
against Democratic measures on education and health care at the
expense of their districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am loyal first to the people I represent and will never put
a political party's agenda over the needs of this district,'' said
Whatley, a retired North Charleston police chief.
</P>
<P>
   His district leans Democratic, with a large black population. He
won as a Republican in 1998 with 53 percent of the vote against a
Democrat who dropped out but whose name remained on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Gamble's suburban Columbia district leans Republican, but she
voted for Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges' new school-readiness program
and his prescription drug plan for senior citizens against the GOP
leadership's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have seniors who are having to decide between food and
prescription drugs. My district has children who are being left
behind in school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders dismissed the party-switching as an election-year
convenience. Gamble and Whatley would have had primary opponents
next month had they stayed in the party. ''It's called
self-preservation,'' said House Majority Leader Rick Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the defections moved the Democrats to
within four seats of regaining control of South Carolina's House.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere around the South, Georgia state Rep. Randy Sauder
decided last month to seek re-election as a Democrat because of
Republican opposition to Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes' education
reform bill. In Alabama, state Sen. Jeff Enfinger jumped to the
Democratic Party in January because he said it had broader issues.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland state Sen. Robert Neall became a Democrat in November
because of GOP criticism that he was not conservative enough.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Whit Ayers doesn't deny Democrats have had
recent successes.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the fact that you had two House Republicans about ready to
lose a Republican primary and they switched to the Democratic Party
in an effort to save their seats says absolutely nothing about
party competition in the South,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bigger picture is the growth of the Republican Party,''
said Earl Black, a Rice University political scientist who
specializes in Southern politics.
</P>
<P>
   The longer and broader trend over the past generation has seen
the once reliably Democratic South become a Republican power base.
The recent Republican-to-Democrat switching in South Carolina is
nowhere near in size to the groundswell of state Democrats who
jumped to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler said 15 to 20 Democratic legislators in South Carolina
have switched to the GOP since the 1960s. Nine of them jumped after
the 1994 election, giving the Republicans control of South
Carolina's House for the first time this century. The Democrats
control the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, however, Democrats regained the
governors' offices in South Carolina, Alabama and Mississippi. They
control 24 of 30 Southern legislative chambers.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, the Democrats' education platform and health
care agenda seemed to resonate with voters more than the GOP
staples of tax cuts and smaller government.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a winning message,'' said the governor, who wants a
lottery to support the state's lagging public schools.
''Republicans have tended to stick to the same messages that they
had in the 1980s that were appealing to voters at that time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1324 </TRAILER>
