<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unicredito To Buy Pioneer Group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Italy's second-largest banking firm has agreed to
purchase the investment operations of Boston mutual fund house
Pioneer Group Inc. for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal announced Monday, Unicredito Italiano Group will
combine Pioneer's $24 billion in investment operations in the
United States, Europe and Asia with its own to create a $100
billion global investment company.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.2 billion price tag represents about 5 percent of
Pioneer's assets under management. Industry experts said the price
is expensive, but it will let the Italian bank come a step closer
to becoming one of Europe's biggest asset management groups.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer shareholders, meanwhile, will get a price that should
satisfy some investors who have been lobbying for a sale,
especially Southeastern Asset Management of Memphis, Pioneer's
biggest investor with 18 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sale, Pioneer plans to distribute its other
investments including venture capital, real estate and Russian
financial services to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Unicredito will pay $43.50 per share in cash for Pioneer shares,
40 percent more than the stock's $31 closing price Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange,
Pioneer shares climbed 36.3 percent, or $11.25, to $42.25 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The sale follows a tumultuous two years at the 72-year-old
Pioneer which saw the company lose tens of millions of dollars in
risky investments, such as a failed Russian bank and a South
African gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   Its flagship fund, Pioneer Fund, was founded in 1928 and is the
fourth oldest mutual fund in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both Pioneer stockholders, as well as trustees and shareholders
of its funds, must vote to approve the sale.
</P>
<P>
   There will be little immediate change for Pioneer fund
investors. UniCredito's Pietro Modiano will be the chairman of the
newly created Pioneer Global Asset Management, based in Italy. But
Pioneer chief executive John F. Cogan will become deputy chairman.
David D. Tripple, who currently heads Pioneer Investment
Management, will become CEO of Pioneer U.S.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
