<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Bullet-Proof Vests  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today proclaimed his effort
to buy more bullet-resistant vests for police officers a success,
and announced additional money for the program this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also honored 139 police officers killed in the line of
duty last year and announced a new presidential award for police
valor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their purpose and passion was the safety of the people,''
Clinton said at a ceremony honoring fallen police officers. ''We
can never repay them ... but we can honor them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton put in a plug for stalled legislation requiring trigger
locks on handguns and more background checks for handgun buyers,
things many police support. The president noted that better gun
control was the aim of Sunday's Million Mom March.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope we will listen to what they had to say. It will also
save a lot of police officers' lives,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In its first full year last year, the federal vest program
helped buy more than 92,000 armored vests for state police and
local officers nationwide, Clinton said. The three-year Justice
Department program, which Clinton created in June 1998, makes
grants for up to half the price of vests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the $24 million available this year should help buy
approximately 90,000 more vests. Police departments have until next
week to apply.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said he supports a proposal in Congress to
extend the vest program for another three years, through 2004, and
to double funding from $75 million to $150 million over that
period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1404 </TRAILER>
