<HEADLINE> Expert: Rail Killer Not in Control  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A defense expert for admitted serial killer Angel
Maturino Resendiz acknowledged today that the rail-riding drifter
knew his deadly spree was illegal, but maintained he did not know
right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After Dr. Bruce Cohen wrapped up a third day of testimony in
Maturino Resendiz's capital murder trial, defense attorney Allen
Tanner rested his case. Prosecutors were expected to call a
court-appointed psychiatrist this afternoon to rebut Cohen's
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is trying to win an innocent verdict by reason of
insanity, saying the Mexican citizen was delusional when he killed
nine Americans, including the death he is on trial for, the
December 1998 slaying of Houston-area physician Claudia Benton.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the defendant has ''delusional beliefs'' brought
about by acute paranoid schizophrenia, because he believed that he
was on a divine mission to eliminate evil and that public opinion
was on his side.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz chose not to testify on his behalf. Besides
Benton, he is accused of killing five other people in Texas, two in
Illinois and one in Kentucky from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant prosecutor Lyn McClellan confronted Cohen with
statements made by the defendant's only known surviving victim -- a
female friend of slain University of Kentucky student Christopher
Maier -- that he attacked them because he wanted sex. It made no
mention of his purported delusions.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen replied that Maturino Resendiz said he did not remember
much about killing Maier and raping the friend near some railroad
tracks in Lexington, Ky., in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also restated to the jury that Maturino Resendiz's IQ is
120, above average. He added that many people with serious mental
illness are extremely intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   When he began cross-examining Cohen on Friday, McLellan accused
the psychiatrist of tailoring his testimony to fit the insanity
defense strategy. Cohen responded that he found only 10 percent of
the several hundred defendants he has evaluated for sanity to be
insane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
