<HEADLINE> Dow Up 153; Nasdaq Down 28  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as the Federal Reserve's
decision on interest rates loomed over the market. Blue-chip shares
showed some strength, but few investors were taking on major new
positions.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 153.52 at 10,762.89.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 28.70 at 3,500.36 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 15.79 at 1,436.75.
</P>
<P>
   Market watchers said trading was likely to be light until
Tuesday afternoon, after the Fed's meeting. The Fed's Open Market
Committee is widely expected to raise interest rates for the sixth
time since last June in its continuing effort to cool the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Fed offered the latest indication that the economy
remains extremely robust. The Fed said industrial production posted
its biggest leap in April in more than a year, as output at the
nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq Stock Market, Lycos rose 5 15/16 to 60 1/16. The
Wall Street Journal reported Spain's Terra Networks SA is in
serious discussions to acquire Lycos for at least $10 billion in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   But many other high-profile technology names were lower. Cisco
Systems was down 1 15/16 to 58 and PMC-Sierra was down 2| to 143
5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said investors remain leery of highly-priced technology stocks in
the wake of a steep selloff in April. The Nasdaq has recovered some
of its footing, yet remains more than 30 percent below its March 10
peak.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's widespread agreement that tech stocks will continue to
be the leaders,'' Yardeni said. But the shakeout in April forced
investors to become more discerning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq debacle has been led by tech stocks that have no
earnings and were priced off inflated revenue estimates,'' he said.
''The quality of earnings is suddenly being talked about a great
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow components, Philip Morris rose 2 7/16 to 26}. The Wall
Street Journal reported the company has offered to buy the food
business of Nabisco Group Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Also, International Paper rose 3 117/128 to 40}, fueling the
Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose on speculation that if the Fed raises
rates by a half-percentage point on Tuesday, central bankers may be
finished with their cycle of rate increases. J.P. Morgan rose 2
5/16 to 132 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot rose 2 11/16 to 56 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 529.01 million
shares, compared with 593.11 million at the same time on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.59 to 489.35.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
