<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rehnquist Talks on Disclosure  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's federal judges may ask Congress
to consider changing a financial-disclosure law to better protect
them from ''the criminal element in our society,'' Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The risks to federal judges are real and deserving of careful
consideration,'' Rehnquist said in a speech to the American Law
Institute, a group of lawyers and judges.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rehnquist's first public explanation of his
behind-the-scenes role in a dispute over release of
financial-disclosure reports for 1,600 federal judges to a news
organization that plans to post them on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the deadline for all federal judges and other
high-ranking federal employees to submit financial-disclosure
reports for calendar year 1999. Those reports will be available for
public scrutiny soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the organization seeking all reports for 1998 has not
yet received one, APBnews.com's Joe Krakoviak said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Judicial Conference, a 27-judge board of directors for
the federal judiciary, overturned a decision by one of its
committees and said last March that the reports must be made
available to APBnews.com. Rehnquist, the nation's highest-ranking
federal judge, chairs the conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''A large majority of the members -- myself included -- felt that
the ... committee's willingness to withhold financial-disclosure
reports in their entirety, well-intentioned as it might be, could
not be supported in view of the statutory language,'' Rehnquist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress specifically provided in the Ethics in Government Act
an exemption from the prohibition on the use of the reports for
commercial purposes to news and communications media for
dissemination to the general public. ... And there are no
exceptions to this for the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist did not suggest there should be such an exception, but
said the Judicial Conference is working on regulations that would
allow sensitive information that ''could endanger'' the judges to
be removed from the reports before they are posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He said federal trial judges ''are exposed to the criminal
element in our society in ways that most federal employees who must
file financial-disclosure reports, such as senators, congressmen
and perhaps appellate judges for that matter, are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the current law, judges' reports conceivably could
disclose where a spouse works, where a family member is attending
school or even where a judge lives ''if, for example, the judge is
on a condominium board,'' Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ''With regard to the issue of posting all judges'
financial-disclosure statements on the Internet, I believe the
Judicial Conference has acted responsibly and demonstrated a
good-faith effort to comply with a law that frankly poses some
risks to judges,'' Rehnquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The conference now hopes that Congress will also act
responsibly and balance the legitimate needs for public disclosure
of judges' financial holdings with the judges' need for security,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1427 </TRAILER>
