<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Coal Minister Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By BEATA PASEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Poland's top government official in charge
of reforming the unprofitable coal mining industry resigned Monday,
apparently in protest over the Finance Ministry's recent demands
that the sector pay its mounting tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy economy minister Jan Szlazak had preferred a softer
approach to clearing up the coal industry's tax arrears than the
crackdown ordered by finance minister Leszek Balcerowicz.
</P>
<P>
   Balcerowicz, who has frequently criticized the slow pace of
restructuring in the coal industry, has begun legal action to
collect overdue social security and corporate income tax payments
for Poland's cash-strapped budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''Already 41 mining managers face lawsuits,'' Szlazak told the
public news agency PAP in explaining his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, including Balcerowicz, said Szlazak's
resignation was not related to the overdue taxes or mining reform,
but they refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Prime minister Jerzy Buzek will discuss Szlazak's resignation
with economics minister Jerzy Steinhoff later in the week, said
government spokesman Krzysztof Luft.
</P>
<P>
   Coal production was heavily subsidized during the communist era,
when it was Poland's main hard-currency earner. Since the onset of
market-oriented reforms after 1989, the government has struggled to
reorganize the sector in the face of intense union opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Monday, Balcerowicz presented measures to limit
corruption, which according to World Bank reports has been on the
rise in Poland's post-communist economy, due to old regulations
inadequate to a free market.
</P>
<P>
   To combat corruption, a special group will draft legal
regulations by June 20 to introduce competition for public posts,
more transparency in public tenders, equality in access to
information and limit licensing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
