<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinian Fight Worsens  </HEADLINE>
By DANA BUDEIRI
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank (AP) -- Guests, bystanders and journalists
took cover in the lobby of Ramallah's New City Inn Monday, after
Israeli snipers commandeered their rooms and the worst
Israeli-Palestinian fighting in years kept them from going outside.
</P>
<P>
   Bullets shattered the glass walls of the top floor restaurant
where patrons once enjoyed a sweeping view of Ramallah's
construction boom, one of the fruits of the 1993
Israeli-Palestinian peace accords. But on Monday Israeli soldiers
used the windows to fire on stone-throwing demonstrators and
Palestinian gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a fake peace they speak of,'' said Fouad Shadeed, 55,
a Palestinian who was considering moving back to Ramallah from Abu
Dhabi. ''My room was broken into by five soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine Americans were trapped in the hotel, including three
Palestinian-American owners, three staff members, and three guests.
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian man who had taken cover in the lobby tried to
leave, but was shot when he ventured out. Israeli soldiers treated
him in the lobby and evacuated him by ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters hovered overhead as shots continued to ring out.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes began as marches marking ''Al Naqba,'' Arabic for
the catastrophe, which is how Palestinians view Israel's founding
52 years ago. They quickly spun out of control, though no one
seemed to know just how.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went out and threw stones at the soldiers,'' said Fayez
Akub, a 30-year old marketing student who was hit in the face with
a rubber bullet. ''There was a lot of anger and frustration, then
the soldiers started shooting heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   Another demonstrator, 22-year old Eyad Assi, said he heard from
ambulance drivers that some of the wounded had been hit with
regular bullets instead of the rubber-coated steel pellets usually
used during demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bullets started coming from our side, from our soldiers,'' he
said, referring to Palestinian police. Assi was being treated for a
bullet wound in the upper arm at Ramallah Hospital, where friends
and relatives gathered to give blood and visit the scores of
injured.
</P>
<P>
   In the New City Inn's lobby, retired U.S. naval officer Jim
Parrish, 73, took cover with his friend, George Prignano, after
they were forced out of their rooms by soldiers. Parrish, of Morton
Grove, Ill., watched half-hour news updates and leaned on his cane,
his hands shaking from Parkinson's' disease. ''It's too much for an
old man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prignano, also from Morton Grove, said the gunfire took him by
surprise, despite the stone-throwing incidents of the past few
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had demonstrations in Chicago,'' he said, ''but nothing
like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
