<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Nuclear Reactor Shuts Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) -- A small electrical fire caused a
reactor at the Diablo Canyon nuclear plant to shut down early
Monday, releasing steam that could contain tiny amounts of
radioactivity, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Such radioactivity would be well below federal limits and no
public health impacts were anticipated, the federal Nuclear
Regulatory Commission said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no measurable amount of radioactivity. The plant
operates perimeter monitors that would indicate any appreciable
amount,'' said Breck Henderson, a spokesman for the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission's Region 4 in Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported when an electric short and fire
happened at 12:25 a.m. in a turbine generator building. The blaze
was put out with a fire extinguisher by 1 a.m., said Jeff Lewis,
spokesman for the plant's operator, Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   A firefighting unit from the California Department of Forestry
was summoned to assist in putting out the blaze, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Unit 1 reactor automatically shut down when the emergency
lasted beyond 15 minutes, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Plant operators reported an ''unusual event,'' the lowest level
of emergency declarations required by the NRC. The cause of the
fire in electrical switching equipment was not immediately
determined.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to assess what happened, and why, before putting Unit
1 back into operation,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC resident inspector viewed the fire damage and will be
involved in the investigation of the cause, the NRC spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Diablo Canyon, which has two nuclear reactors, is on
California's central coast. Some 237,000 people live in surrounding
San Luis Obispo County, including 43,000 in the nearby city of San
Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   Unit 1 went into operation in 1985. Unit 2, in operation since
1986, was continuing to operate Monday, officials said. Each unit
produces about 1,100 megawatts of electricity -- equivalent to the
electric needs of about 1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown came five days after a drill held by about 300
emergency workers to prepare for the possibility of a disaster at
the plant. In the drill, monitored by the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, a mock radioactive release was tracked to decide
what areas would have to be evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nrc.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
