<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Monday, May 15, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Industrial Output Rises in April
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Industrial production posted its biggest leap
in more than a year in April as the output of utilities rebounded,
the Federal Reserve said today. Output at the nation's factories
mines and utilities rose 0.9 percent, right on target with many
analysts' expectations and the largest increase since a 1.8 percent
gain posted in August 1998. Factories, mines and utilities were
operating at 82.1 percent of capacity, up from 81.7 percent in
March. However, The pickup in operating capacity remained below
levels usually associated with increasing inflation. Generally, a
reading of 84 percent makes economists start to worry. Some
economists say the increase in production would justify a
half-point hike in interest rates by the Fed's policy makers when
they meet tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Rises 155, Nasdaq Falls 10
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today as the Federal Reserve's
decision on interest rates loomed over the market. Blue-chip shares
showed some strength, but few investors were taking on major new
positions. In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 155.75 at 10,765.12. Broader stock
indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index was down 10.01 at
3,519.05 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down up 15.79 at
1,436.75. Market watchers said trading was likely to be light until
after the Fed's meeting tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   New York (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:
