</P>
<P>
   Report: Others Sought Nabisco
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Philip Morris Cos., France's Danone SA and
Britain's Cadbury Schweppes PLC have reportedly made preliminary
offers for all or part of Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food company
that makes Ritz crackers and Oreo cookies. The Wall Street Journal
reported today that R. J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings Inc. has also
indicated it is interested in bidding for Nabisco's controlling
shareholder, Nabisco Group Holdings Corp. Shares of Nabisco Group
Holdings and Nabisco Holdings soared on the report. The bids were
reportedly made as part of the auction process that Nabisco Group
Holdings launched last month after financier Carl Icahn said he was
prepared to make an offer for the 90.4 percent of Nabisco Group
that he doesn't already own.
</P>
<P>
   UAE Minister: US Makes OPEC Request
</P>
<P>
   ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- United Arab Emirates oil
minister Obaid bin Saif al-Nasseri said today that the United
States has again asked the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to increase oil production when it meets June 21 in
Vienna. He said the U.S. request was conveyed to him at a meeting
yesterday with a team of U.S. officials led by David Goldwyn,
assistant energy secretary for international affairs. Al-Nasseri
didn't say by how much the United States wants OPEC to increase
production or give any further details about the talks.
</P>
<P>
   World Leaders Fight Internet Attacks
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Love Bug virus has given a new sense of
urgency to the world's leaders as they gathered today to brainstorm
about combating cybercrime, a transgression that knows no
boundaries. Leaders from Group of Eight countries were in Paris
today for a three-day discussion of Internet crime. Separately, the
41-nation Council of Europe working with the United States, Canada,
Japan and South Africa -- is drafting a treaty to standardize
cybercrime laws. Though their efforts preceded the appearance of
the ''Love Bug'' virus, the attack that crippled corporate and
government networks around the globe earlier this month may have
boosted their undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   Unicredito To Buy Pioneer Group
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Italy's second-largest banking firm has agreed to
purchase the investment operations of Boston mutual fund house
Pioneer Group Inc. for $1.2 billion. Under the deal announced
today, Unicredito Italiano Group will combine Pioneer's $24 billion
in investment operations in the United States, Europe and Asia with
its own to create a $100 billion global investment company. The
$1.2 billion price tag represents about 5 percent of Pioneer's
assets under management. Industry experts said the price is
expensive, but it will let the Italian bank come a step closer to
becoming one of Europe's biggest asset management groups. Pioneer
shareholders, meanwhile, will get a price that should satisfy some
investors who have been lobbying for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's Terra Networks Eyes U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Terra Networks, an ambitious cyberspace
powerhouse barely a year old but strong in Europe and with a
dominant presence in Latin America, is angling to take a big bite
of the U.S. Internet market. Terra confirmed Friday it is in talks
with Lycos Inc., one of the United States' top Internet portals.
Terra told stock market regulators in Madrid that no deal has been
signed, but analysts said some kind of alliance was likely. The
Wall Street Journal reported today that Terra was in serious
discussions to acquire Lycos for at least $10 billion in stock. But
there is a significant chance the two sides will fail to reach a
deal, the newspaper said, quoting people close to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Viag, Veba To Merge Chemical Units
</P>
<P>
   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- In advance of their planned merger,
German energy powerhouses Veba AG and Viag AG said today they would
combine their chemical subsidiaries into a company focusing on
specialty chemicals by 2001. The newly merged company, to be called
Degussa AG, will bring together chemical groups Degussa-Huels AG,
owned by Veba, and SKW Trostberg AG, owned by Viag. Veba and Viag
announced last September plans to merge in a $12.6 billion deal,
but the deal has yet to gain antitrust approval because of their
holdings in other German utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Official Dies in Fall
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's top foreign exchange regulator died after
falling from a building, a Chinese official confirmed today, but
the official declined to say whether the death was a suicide. Hong
Kong media have reported that Li Fuxiang, director of China's State
Administration of Foreign Exchange, was admitted to a Beijing
hospital and died Wednesday after jumping from the seventh floor of
the building. The death came amid speculation in the Hong Kong
media that he killed himself over health problems, stress from work
or worries about a corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   German Travel Co. To Buy Brit rival
</P>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany (AP) -- Europe's largest package tour provider,
Germany's Preussag AG, is buying Thomson Travel Group PLC for $2.73
billion, topping a German competitor that had also been pursuing
Britain's biggest travel company. Preussag said today that
Thomson's board had accepted the bid -- which values Thomson at
$2.73 a share -- and has decided to recommend that shareholders
approve the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Faults Deutsche Bank Unit
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's securities watchdog said today it has
formally recommended penalties for Deutsche Bank AG's securities
unit in Tokyo after an inspection disclosed illegal transactions.
The penalties were not disclosed, but Japanese media reported today
that regulators will likely order the unit later this month to stop
trading bonds and bond futures for several weeks. The Securities
and Exchange Surveillance Commission said the Tokyo branch of
Deutsche Securities Co., a wholly owned subsidiary of Deutsche
Bank, was involved in several illegal transactions including
soliciting clients with financial products intended to hide their
trading losses.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
