<HEADLINE> Dow Up 157; Nasdaq Up 63  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned higher today as investors
anticipated that the Federal Reserve's meeting on Tuesday will
bring the central bank close to the end of a year-long cycle of
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 157.29 at 10,766.66.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also turned higher after weakness early
in the session. The Nasdaq composite index was up 63.45 at 3,559.70
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 24.47 at 1,445.43.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was extremely light, indicating that few investors were
willing to take on major new positions. But rate-sensitive stocks
posted strong gains, buoying the Dow as investors speculated that
if the the Fed raises rates by a half-percentage point on Tuesday,
central bankers may be finished with their cycle of rate increases.
J.P. Morgan rose 1 11/16 to 132 3/16 and Home Depot rose 2 1/16 to
55 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's Open Market Committee is widely expected to raise
interest rates for the sixth time since last June in its continuing
effort to cool the economy. Today, the Fed offered the latest
indication that the economy remains extremely robust. The Fed said
industrial production posted its biggest leap in April in more than
a year, as output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities
rose 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's advance was helped along by Philip Morris, which rose
2| to 26 15/16. The Wall Street Journal reported the company has
offered to buy the food business of Nabisco Group Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Also, International Paper rose 3 117/128 to 40}.
</P>
<P>
   While blue-chip names racked up substantial gains, the volatile
technology sector was mixed. On the Nasdaq Stock Market, Lycos rose
6 13/16 to 60 15/16. The Wall Street Journal reported Spain's Terra
Networks SA is in serious discussions to acquire Lycos for at least
$10 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   But many other high-profile technology names were lower. Cisco
Systems was down 1[ to 58 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank Securities,
said investors remain leery of highly-priced technology stocks in
the wake of a steep selloff in April. The Nasdaq has recovered some
of its footing, yet remains more than 30 percent below its March 10
peak.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's widespread agreement that tech stocks will continue to
be the leaders,'' Yardeni said. But the shakeout in April forced
investors to become more discerning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq debacle has been led by tech stocks that have no
earnings and were priced off inflated revenue estimates,'' he said.
''The quality of earnings is suddenly being talked about a great
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 633.15 million
shares, compared with 693.28 million at the same time on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.16 to 492.10.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
