<HEADLINE> Officials Begin IRA Weapons Mission  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The two independent statesmen
appointed to inspect secret Irish Republican Army weapons dumps
pledged Monday that they would ensure weapons revealed by the
outlawed group would never be used.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not underestimate the profound importance and the
unprecedented nature of the task which we have been asked to
undertake,'' said a joint statement from former Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari and Cyril Ramaphosa, an African National Congress
veteran who helped topple apartheid in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The pair arrived in Belfast nine days after the outlawed IRA, in
a major breakthrough, announced it would put its weapons stockpiles
''completely and verifiably beyond use,'' a euphemism for the
gradual disarmament proposed by 1998's Good Friday peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's refusal to make any disarmament commitments in
February forced Britain to withdraw powers from the province's
fledgling Catholic-Protestant administration, the intended
centerpiece of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, Ahtisaari and Ramaphosa will travel under IRA
escort to at least three hidden arms bunkers somewhere in the
neighboring Republic of Ireland. Other dumps are to be identified
and neutralized, by a method yet to be agreed, if political
progress continues elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The two men promised Monday to ''regularly reinspect these dumps
to ensure that the weapons have remained secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, the British and Irish governments have been
trying to build sufficient Protestant support for resuming the
power-sharing Cabinet, which includes politicians from the
IRA-linked Sinn Fein party.
</P>
<P>
   Britain hopes to transfer considerable powers back to the
four-party coalition next week.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the major Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists,
must vote Saturday on whether the IRA's pledges are sufficient to
merit returning to office alongside Sinn Fein -- and a positive
verdict is by no means guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to sway Protestants, Britain said Monday it would
allow the government's senior minister in Northern Ireland, Peter
Mandelson, to have the final say over whether the British flag
continues to fly over government buildings. Sinn Fein ministers had
ordered the flag removed from offices under their stewardship
during the Cabinet's brief 11 weeks in power.
</P>
<P>
   Britain also unveiled a new scholarship foundation for members
of Northern Ireland's predominantly Protestant police force, which
is due to be reformed as part of the Good Friday package.
</P>
<P>
   However, both measures failed to address the Ulster Unionists'
fundamental demand for the police force's name, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, to be retained.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists insist that, regardless of the IRA's latest
concessions, they won't resume work alongside Sinn Fein unless
Britain drops plans to rename the force the more neutral-sounding
Police Service of Northern Ireland. Sinn Fein just as adamantly
demands the abolition of the RUC name.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble, the senior minister
within the suspended Cabinet, warned after meeting Ahtisaari and
Ramaphosa that he still needed to know whether the IRA ever
intended to allow its weapons to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Revealing some dumps was ''not the permanent solution,'' Trimble
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
