<DOCNO> APW20000515.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Friends' Is Back; 'Frasier' Moves  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is moving ''Frasier'' from Thursdays to
Tuesdays, cutting the newsmagazine ''Dateline NBC'' from five
nights to three and welcoming the man who made Jerry Seinfeld's
buddy Kramer back to TV this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The network, which announced its fall schedule today, avoided a
big hole on Thursday nights when the six ''Friends'' actors agreed
to return for two more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Aniston, Courteney Cox Arquette, Lisa Kudrow, Matt
LeBlanc, Matthew Perry and David Schwimmer will all be paid $20
million each to film 24 episodes next year, according to an
executive close to the talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity.	   NBC is
adding four new comedies and three dramas to its
schedule. It is eliminating its Saturday night lineup of dramas
''Profiler,'' ''Pretender'' and ''The Others,'' and also axing the
comedies ''Suddenly Susan,'' ''Veronica's Closet,'' ''Jesse'' and
''Stark Raving Mad.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Frasier'' moves to Tuesdays at 9 p.m., back to where it spent
four years before switching, with great fanfare, to Thursday to
replace ''Seinfeld'' in 1998. The younger comedies ''Will &AMP; Grace''
and ''Just Shoot Me'' will fill the 9 p.m. hour on Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dateline NBC'' has been the network's workhorse over the past
few years. But with evidence that the glut of newsmagazines is
causing audience fatigue, NBC is eliminating the Monday and
Wednesday editions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Michael Richards Show,'' with the actor who played
Seinfeld's sidekick, will debut on Tuesdays at 8 p.m. Richards
plays an unconventional private investigator in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Movies will be shown on Saturday nights until February, when NBC
broadcasts games from the new football league it is starting with
the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's four canceled comedies all drew tepid reviews but big
audiences when given starts on the network's powerful Thursday
schedule. This fall NBC will launch one new Thursday comedy, ''The
Steven Weber Show,'' starring the former ''Wings'' actor as an
executive whose life unravels after a blind date puts a hex on him.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is the first of seven broadcast networks to present its new
schedule to advertisers this week.
</P>
<P>
   The network set a deadline of 3 p.m. EDT on Sunday to conclude
negotiations with the ''Friends'' actors, or else promised to go
ahead without its most popular comedy. But the deal was reached
about 12 hours before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The six ''Friends'' will be paid $750,000 per episode for each
year, compared with a reported $125,000 this year. They also were
given a greater percentage of the profits from the sitcom's
lucrative syndication deals, giving them each a total of $40
million over two years, executives said Sunday. The stars had
reportedly been demanding $1 million each per episode to return -- a
sum NBC paid Helen Hunt and Paul Reiser for the final year of ''Mad
About You.''
</P>
<P>
   The actors reached the deal with Warner Bros. Television, the
studio that produces the show. It finishes its sixth season with a
one-hour special this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The five other new shows NBC will premiere in the fall:
</P>
<P>
   --''Dag,'' a comedy which stars David Alan Grier as a demoted
Secret Service agent who must guard the First Lady, played by Delta
Burke.
</P>
<P>
   --''Tucker,'' modeled after Fox's successful ''Malcolm in the
Middle,'' is a comedy about a 14-year-old boy and his newly
divorced mother who are forced to move in with her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   --''Deadline'' gives producer Dick Wolf (''Law and Order,'' ''Law
and Order: Special Victims Unit'') his third hour on NBC's
schedule. It's a drama about a columnist working on a New York City
tabloid newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   --''Titans'' is another nighttime soap opera from producer Aaron
Spelling. It centers on a 26-year-old fighter pilot who returns to
Beverly Hills to find his family torn apart.
</P>
<P>
   --''Ed'' marks the return of David Letterman to NBC -- sort of.
The drama about a New York attorney who moves back to his
Midwestern hometown comes from Letterman's production company and
was created by two ''Late Show'' producers and writers.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and the WB network will announce their schedules Tuesday,
CBS and Pax TV on Wednesday, and Fox and UPN on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nbc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
