<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Ruling on Rape Suits  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   From the Supreme Court's ruling Monday that threw out
a
provision of the Violence Against Women Act that allowed rape
victims to sue their attackers in federal court:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   From Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist's majority decision:
</P>
<P>
   Gender-motivated crimes of violence are not, in any sense of the
phrase, economic activity... thus far in our nation's history our
cases have upheld commerce clause regulation of intrastate activity
only where that activity is economic in nature...
</P>
<P>
   If accepted, (Brzonkala's) reasoning would allow Congress to
regulate any crime as long as the nationwide, aggregated impact of
that crime has substantial effects on employment, production,
transit or consumption. Indeed, if Congress may regulate
gender-motivated violence, it would be able to regulate murder or
any other type of violence... (and) family law and other areas of
traditional state regulation...
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires a distinction between what is truly
national and what is truly local... The regulation and punishment
of intrastate violence that is not directed at the
instrumentalities, channels or goods involved in interstate
commerce has always been the province of the states...
</P>
<P>
   Petitioner Brzonkala's complaint alleges that she was the victim
of a brutal assault... If the allegations here are true, no
civilized system of justice could fail to provide her a remedy for
the conduct of respondent (Antonio) Morrison. But under our federal
system that remedy must be provided by the commonwealth of
Virginia, and not by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   From Justice David H. Souter's dissenting opinion:
</P>
<P>
   Congress has the power to legislate with regard to activity
that, in the aggregate, has a substantial effect on interstate
commerce. The fact of such a substantial effect is not an issue for
the courts in the first instance, but for the Congress...
</P>
<P>
   One obvious difference from (a 1995 case in which a federal
gun-possession law was struck down) is the mountain of data
assembled by Congress, here showing the effects of violence against
women on interstate commerce...
</P>
<P>
   Gender-based violence in the 1990s was shown to operate in a
manner similar to racial discrimination in the 1960s in reducing
the mobility of employees and their production and consumption of
goods shipped in interstate commerce... Violence against women may
be found to affect interstate commerce and affect it
substantially...
</P>
<P>
   Today's majority, however, finds no significance whatever in the
state support for the act based upon the states' acknowledged
failure to deal adequately with gender-based violence in state
courts, and the belief of their own law enforcement agencies that
national action is essential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1556 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Bomb Key Chechen Targets  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Russian bombers targeted rebels Monday in
Chechnya's southern mountains following overnight attacks on
federal posts, and Russian troops said they ambushed several
militant bases.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel forces shelled Russian police stations and traffic
checkpoints at least 18 times overnight, the military command said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal posts were hit in the Vedeno gorge in the east, the
Argun Gorge and the Shatoi region in the south-central mountains,
and near Nozhai-Yurt close to the border with the neighboring
Russian region of Dagestan, officials said. There were also four
smaller attacks in the capital, Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Some federal troops were wounded and taken to a hospital in
Mozdok just west of Chechnya, but figures were not provided.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, reconnaissance planes flew over the Vedeno Gorge,
followed by attack jets that pounded the area for several hours,
the Russian command said. The rugged area is a key rebel refuge
from Russian forces, which seized lowland areas of Chechnya after
entering the rebellious republic in September.
</P>
<P>
   The military command also claimed Monday that 22 militants were
killed when Russian troops found an empty rebel camp near Gonsolchu
on Sunday. The Russians waited for militants to return to the camp,
then opened fire, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian special forces unit trapped another group of rebels in
a forest near Samashki in western Chechnya, killing 15, the
military said. And Russian ground troops combing mountain areas
during the weekend uncovered a rebel base near Shatoi, killing five
rebels, the military claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The claims could not be confirmed. Casualty figures are
difficult to verify and both sides exaggerate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an amnesty that Moscow offered to rebel fighters was
to expire Monday at midnight, after little success.
</P>
<P>
   Since the amnesty offer took effect in December, just 150 rebels
have taken advantage of the chance to turn in their weapons and be
released if Russian authorities find they have committed no serious
crimes, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Most rebels have scorned the deal, and hard-line Russian
officials have criticized it as too lenient toward the militants.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky,
played down its limited results.
</P>
<P>
   ''The amnesty has played its positive role,'' he told a news
conference. Still, he said the Kremlin ''should not be in a hurry''
to extend the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Russian forces found wreckage of an Su-24
reconnaissance jet that disappeared last week in the eastern region
of Benoi-Vedeno, the Interfax news agency quoted the air force
headquarters as saying. Officials gave no information about the
fate of the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The military said the plane could have crashed because of bad
weather. The rebels say they shot it down with a shoulder-fired
missile.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war with
separatist guerrillas. They went back in after Chechnya-based
militants seized villages in neighboring Dagestan, and after about
300 people died in apartment bombings blamed by the government on
Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1602 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kids, Staff Held Hostage in Norway  </HEADLINE>
By KAARE LUNDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   HJELMELAND, Norway (AP) -- A gunman barged into a preschool in
western Norway on Monday, taking 25 children and 10 staff members
hostage before agreeing to meet with a defense lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   About seven hours into the standoff, the man released all but
five children and two adult hostages from the old, wooden
schoolhouse in Hjelmeland, a town of 2,500 people 185 miles west of
the capital, Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to release the hostage taker's name or say
anything about potential motives, although news media speculated
that one of the female hostages was somehow involved in a rape case
in which the man was a suspect. Police confirmed that the hostage
taker was armed but refused to say what kind of weapon he had.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope I haven't scared anyone more than necessary,'' the
hostage taker told the husband of one hostage by telephone,
according to a report in the Internet newspaper Nettavisen. It was
the worst hostage case in this peaceful nation of 4.5 million since
1994, when an elderly couple and a police woman were taken hostage
in a bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ''The children who were released are fine, all things
considered,'' said Olav Sonderland, chief of police in Stavanger,
the region's main town.
</P>
<P>
   One of Norway's most prominent defense lawyers, Tor Erling
Staff, was allowed to try to mediate an end to the crisis after the
gunman released most of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Staff entered the preschool just after 8 p.m. for face-to-face
talks with the hostage-taker, the Norwegian news agency NTB
reported. He told NTB that he had made a proposal by telephone,
without getting much of a response. Staff refused to give any
details.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining hostages were being held inside the building,
although many of the children earlier were allowed outside in the
schoolyard. During the day, toddlers could be seen playing on
swings inside the chain-link fence that surrounded the building.
Most of the youngsters were later freed.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Anders Bang-Andersen said police quickly ruled
out any attempt to rescue the children playing outside because of
concerns the man, reported to be about 40, would become violent or
break off talks with police if they moved into the schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   The man's lawyer, Odd Forsell, said his client was charged in a
rape case that goes to court this month and was involved in a child
custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the moment, I can't see that either the child custody or
the rape case have anything to do with this situation,'' Forsell
was quoted as telling the Norwegian news agency NTB.
</P>
<P>
   The man stormed into the school at about 11 a.m., police said.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said they knew something was wrong when they
called the city-run school at 11:30 a.m. and a man answered the
phone and hung up. No men work at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a tragedy for a small, quiet and peaceful township like
Hjelmeland,'' city manager Fred Johansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sonderland said it would be tragedy anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Using children for something like this, in Norway or anywhere
else, is a very serious matter ... these are children who are under
age 6,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1611 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inspector General criticizes furniture sales  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- An Assemblyman may have violated New York's
Public Officers Law by selling furniture to a state agency through
a business co-owned with his wife, according to an inspector
general's report.
</P>
<P>
   The state Inspector General investigated the no-bid sales of
$30,507 worth of items to the state Office of Mental Retardation
and Developmental Disabilities from a Chenango County furniture
store co-owned by Republican Assemblyman Clifford Crouch.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch is a member of the Assembly Mental Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, elected officials cannot sell anything to a
state agency worth more than $25 unless the purchase goes out to
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Two OMRDD employees made 31 purchases for agency facilities from
December 1997 to February 1999 at Country Settings, which is owned
by Crouch and his wife, Barbara, according to the report. The
report concluded that the two employees made the purchases ''in a
manner intended to avoid proper oversight and in apparent violation
of state procurement rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That these purchases were made at Country Settings, a retail
establishment owned by an assemblyman who serves on a committee
affecting OMRDD issues, created the appearance of a conflict of
interest,'' according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The IG's report said that as the sales appear to violate Public
Officers Law, it was forwarded to the Legislative Ethics
Commission. The commission can impose civil fines and refer matters
for criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch did not return a call to his office seeking comment. He
told investigators that he did not know OMRDD was a customer. He
said his involvement in the business is limited to helping with the
payroll and occasional deliveries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 1614 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
