<HEADLINE> Rain Outlook Sinks Grains, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures sank Monday on the
Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by rainy weather forecasts that
bode well for newly planted crops but not for prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both corn and soybeans fell about 3 percent in a decline that
was even steeper until a new long-range forecast for a dry summer
revived drought fears and pumped up prices late in the trading day.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans posted their lowest price for the near-term contract in
two weeks. Predictions of midweek rains in the Midwest prompted the
dive immediately after the session's opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   Additional pressure came from the U.S. Department of
Agriculture's supply-demand report for May, which projected large
stockpiles of soybeans at the end of the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also benefited from a two-week forecast calling for
favorable conditions for Midwestern crops.
</P>
<P>
   The market for both farm commodities rebounded late in the day
after the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration signaled
that dry conditions would continue in June, July and August.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat fell and rose again along with soybeans and corn, only
less sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery fell 2 cents to $2.82\ a bushel; July
corn fell 7 cents to $2.38} a bushel; July oats fell 2{ cents to
$1.19} a bushel; July soybeans fell 16 cents to $5.49} a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
while pork futures settled sharply lower.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle were unchanged at 67.92 cents a pound; August
feeder rose 0.35 cent to 83.95 cents a pound; June lean hogs fell 2
cents to 70.85 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 2.95 cents to
86.15 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
