<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Polio Campaign Suffers Setbacks  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- Wars, a vaccine shortage, and logistical problems
have set back a campaign to eradicate polio, but the dreaded
disease should be wiped out by 2005, the World Health Organization
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign begun in 1998, WHO set a goal of certifying the
last transmission of polio by the end of 2000, with the whole world
declared polio-free five years later.
</P>
<P>
   However, WHO Director-General Gro Harlem Brundtland said Monday
at the annual meeting of the agency's governing body that the
organization would fail to stop polio infection by the end of this
year. WHO includes 191 member nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''All these factors mean that a year from now the wild virus
will still be infecting children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Hemisphere has been certified polio-free since 1994.
But up to 20 other countries are likely to still have the virus in
circulation at the end of this year, said a joint statement by WHO,
Rotary International, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention and the U.N. Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The countries weren't listed, but Brundtland said there were
predictions of ''a high risk of continued polio transmission at the
end of the year in parts of sub-Saharan Africa and the Indian
subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   To declare the world polio-free in 2005, Brundtland said efforts
must be redoubled, with commitments from manufacturers to assure
supplies of vaccine and promises from warring factions to allow
immunization of every child.
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland also said ''the tide is turning'' in efforts to
provide AIDS drugs to Africans. Brundtland welcomed the move last
week by five pharmaceutical companies to slash the cost of such
drugs in Africa, but said more was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of drugs remains a crucial issue for combatting disease
in poor countries, Brundtland said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot accept that important drugs -- which have been
discovered, produced and made available -- can only be used by a
fortunate few. We cannot accept that for the millions who need them
most, they might as well be on another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brundtland said other steps are being taken to improve health in
developing countries by combatting malaria and tuberculosis,
providing more vaccines and making pregnancy safer.
</P>
<P>
   She appealed to delegates to the assembly to back a ban on
advertising tobacco products ''because it is absolutely right. It
has been proven again and again that it makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Time is not on our side,'' Brundtland said. ''Do not allow any
extra millions to be added to the death row of tobacco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1621 </TRAILER>
