<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel OKs Handover of Villages  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel's parliament on Monday approved turning
over three Arab villages next to Jerusalem to the Palestinians, but
the vote showed how shaky Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition is
on peace issues.
</P>
<P>
   The majority was obtained only because ministers and deputy
ministers from two parties in Barak's coalition stayed away instead
of voting against the measure, which passed 56-48, with one
abstention.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, members of three parties representing Israel's Arab
minority and two other left-leaning parties outside Barak's
coalition voted in favor, compensating for his lack of support from
coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is hoping to recreate this ad hoc peace team in future
votes, but if his coalition crumbles, he might be forced to call
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to violent Palestinian demonstrations and exchanges of
gunfire between Israeli soldiers and Palestinian police as the
parliament debate was in progress, Barak said it showed the way to
peace is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration in downtown Jerusalem, opposition leader
Ariel Sharon charged that Israel's government is allowing the
Palestinians to lay siege to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of opponents of the government's peace moves carried
signs opposing handing territory to the Palestinians. Most of the
demonstrators were teen-agers. Gila Nizri, 15, from Petah Tikva,
outside Tel Aviv, said, ''Every time they give away a little more,
and in the end there will be nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy announced the vote in parliament
to the crowd, which responded with boos. Levy said he would take
his National Religious Party out of Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-compromise Peace Now group counter-demonstrated by
projecting a laser image of assassinated Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin on a wall overlooking the demonstration. In 1995, Rabin was
killed by an Israeli extremist opposed to his peace moves. Police
stopped the projection.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Barak's Cabinet approved the transfer of Abu Dis and
two other villages next to Jerusalem to full Palestinian control.
Up to now they have been in a zone where Israel and Yasser Arafat's
Palestinian Authority share responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing parliament, Barak warned that absence of an agreement
would lead to ''Belfast or Bosnia, an interminable, bloody
conflict, with much bloodshed on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the National Religious Party, two other members of
Barak's coalition opposed the handover of the villages, but angled
to stay in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, the second-largest party in Barak's coalition, has
withheld support for peace moves, demanding money for its bankrupt
school system. Six Shas ministers and deputies absented themselves
from the vote, while ten other Shas members of parliament voted
against.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Interior Minister Natan Sharansky, head of the Israel
B'Aliya party, stayed away while his three members voted against.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver of ministers and deputies skipping the vote allows
their parties to stay in the coalition. If they had voted against,
Barak could have ordered them out.
</P>
<P>
   Under the step-by-step approach to Israel-Palestinian
peacemaking started in 1993, the Palestinians gradually gain
control of most of the West Bank. At the same time, the two sides
are to negotiate a permanent peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Barak's policy say the Palestinians have not
fulfilled their part and are allowing armed elements to plan and
carry out attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   They charged that Arafat was responsible for the violence
Monday, when Palestinians marked the anniversary of the 1948
creation of the state of Israel, which they call ''Al Naqba,'' the
catastrophe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1626 </TRAILER>
