<HEADLINE> Putin Foe Wins St. Petersburg Vote  </HEADLINE>
By KRISTINA SHEVORY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- The main liberal candidate for
governor of St. Petersburg said Monday he was preparing a court
challenge to the election results after the incumbent -- a longtime
foe of President Vladimir Putin -- scored a lopsided victory.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Yakovlev received 73 percent to Igor Artemyev's 15
percent in unofficial returns from Sunday's voting, with 100
percent of polling stations reporting, election officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote followed an election campaign marked by accusations of
dirty tricks and the incumbent's alleged ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Artemyev said slow reporting of results overnight made him
suspect ballot-box stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are dealing with open fraud which must be investigated,''
Artemyev said at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yakovlev didn't address Artemyev's accusations, saying he was
''pleased but not surprised'' at the results giving him a second
four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to work for the good of the city,'' he said.
''There is a lot we can do together.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a St. Petersburg native who was a top aide to Yakovlev's
rival and predecessor Anatoly Sobchak, carefully congratulated the
incumbent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The trust placed in you is not only a high evaluation of your
work, but also of people's hopes for positive changes in St.
Petersburg,'' Putin said in a statement. ''I strongly believe that
professionalism, experience and a demanding attitude toward work
will allow you to successfully solve the problems of Russia's
northern capital.''
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Artemyev, a former city financial official,
accused Yakovlev of ties to underworld figures and blamed him for
St. Petersburg's reputation as Russia's organized crime capital.
Organized crime is a major problem in Russia, with gangs extorting
money from private companies and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sovershenno Sekretno, a national magazine, produced a special
St. Petersburg edition earlier this month accusing Yakovlev of ties
to organized crime. Police confiscated thousands of copies, which
were distributed free through mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg has been the scene of a rash of mob-style
killings of political and business figures. A member of the city
legislature, Yuri Shutov, is in jail on charges of ordering seven
contract killings, and prosecutors have described him as the head
of an organized crime group.
</P>
<P>
   Yakovlev denies the allegations of links to organized crime and
bills himself as a strong manager. As an example, he points to the
city's newly built hockey stadium, site of the world championships
which ended on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
