<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Cancels 57 More Flights  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines canceled 57 additional flights
Monday, 40 because of bad weather and the rest due to a continuing
shortage of pilots at the world's largest airline.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the weather-related cancellations resulted from poor
visibility conditions along parts of the West Coast, airline
spokesman Joe Hopkins said. A storm system was bringing
thunderstorms to northern California, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue during a series of cancellations in recent days is
United's crew-staffing policies. Some pilots have declined to work
overtime, upset at what they say is the airline's failure to hire
more pilots, according to the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, pilot shortages and bad weather resulted in the
cancellation of 108 of United's 2,400 flights.
</P>
<P>
   Union spokesman Herb Hunter, a United pilot, denied any job
action was being encouraged by the union and said pilots are not
refusing regular assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody's calling in sick. Nobody's not doing their job,''
Hunter said Monday. ''We've advised the company over the last six
to nine months that we're going to be short of pilots ... and now
it is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot criticized as ''not a wise strategy'' United's
practice of counting on pilots to work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   United's Hopkins said the policy has worked -- until pilots began
refusing overtime after their contract status changed on April 12,
when an employee stock-option plan expired. The airline is beefing
up its force of 10,000 pilots and cutting its schedule back
accordingly by canceling some flights, he said. Customers are
notified ahead of time and United tries to assist with their plans,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''United and its pilots are not in a labor dispute and pilots
continue to fly their assigned flights,'' Hopkins emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   United, which is 55 percent employee-owned, and the pilots
submitted their contract standoff to federal mediation last month
when the airline's employee stock-option plan ran out. Pilots'
wages were linked closely to that plan because they agreed to lower
salaries in 1994 when it was adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots are now seeking sharply higher pay in addition to other
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   United has declined to discuss specifics of contract talks, the
latest round of which reportedly was taking place Monday in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, airline contracts do not expire and most
airline workers are prohibited from striking unless they receive
permission from the National Mediation Board.
</P>
<P>
   While the law allows airline employees to picket, union
spokesman Hunter said there are no plans for United pilots to do so
at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said it is not unusual for airline contract to take a
year or two to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said United wants to reach agreement as quickly as
possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1651 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Ethiopians Demonstrate  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia -- Tens of thousands of Ethiopians vented
their anger Monday against a U.N. resolution threatening sanctions
if Ethiopia and Eritrea don't end the latest round of fighting in
their two-year border war.
</P>
<P>
   The protest came as an Ethiopian offensive rolled across the
northern Badme front into Eritrea, its much smaller neighbor in the
Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In Addis Ababa, well-coordinated demonstrators, including groups
of schoolchildren, men on horseback and priests from the Ethiopian
Orthodox Church, marched in Meskel Square. Many carried banners in
English and Amharic warning the United Nations not to repeat an
arms embargo imposed by its precursor, the League of Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936 the League imposed sanctions against Italy and Ethiopia,
then known as Abyssinia, after Italy invaded. At that time,
Ethiopia was the only independent nation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the U.N. Security Council prepared to discuss how
to ensure compliance with the resolution calling for ''immediate
steps'' if the two countries don't stop fighting by Tuesday and
resume peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   A British diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Britain planned to introduce another resolution calling for an arms
embargo on both impoverished countries, which have already spent
millions of dollars obtaining weapons and warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they have appealed to international donors for
help in dealing with widespread hunger in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The war is ostensibly about the two nations' poorly demarcated
border. But observers say it is driven as much as anything by the
rivalry between Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and Eritrean
President Isaias Afwerki. Eritrea, once a province of Ethiopia,
gained its independence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A military analyst, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said it appeared that Ethiopia clearly had the upper hand and had
broken through Eritrean defenses in the northern Badme front along
the disputed 620-mile border as well as at Zalambessa, 255 miles
northwest of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst said Ethiopian aircraft were supporting the infantry
offensive, which he called much bigger than the one in February
1999 when Ethiopia retook Badme with thousands of casualties on
both sides. The war was sparked by Eritrea's seizure of Badme, 400
miles north of Addis Ababa, in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eritrean capital, Asmara, government spokesman Yemane
Gebremeskel said Eritrean forces shot down an Ethiopian SU-27 jet
fighter and a Mi-24 helicopter gunship during what he called
''extremely heavy fighting'' at the Mereb-Setit front, the Eritrean
name for the Badme region.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to disclose Eritrean casualties in the four days of
fighting since the Ethiopians launched their offensive on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite numerous attempts at shuttle diplomacy by U.S. and U.N.
diplomats, there have never been face-to-face talks between the two
belligerents. The closest they got was separate rooms last month in
Algiers for ''proximity talks,'' which collapsed over disagreement
on implementing a peace agreement drawn up by the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries have accepted the blueprint. But Eritrea wants a
cease-fire first, which would include a pullback by both sides and
a U.N.-supervised demarcation of the border that has separated the
two countries since Eritrea gained independence. Ethiopia wants the
implementation first and says Eritrea's position amounts to
''setting preconditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
