<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rail Suspect's Jail Mate Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A former prison mate of Texas Railroad Killer
Angel Maturino Resendiz testified Monday that they worked together
coaching inmates on using insanity claims to overturn sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mitchell Rollins, 43, said he worked with Maturino
Resendiz in the law library at the Marianna Federal Correctional
Institute in Florida for about 16 months, starting in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ordered some books and read up on it,'' said Rollins, who
noted that the defendant helped him file his own incompetence
brief.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has pleaded innocent by reason of
insanity in the 1998 slaying of Houston-area physician Claudia
Benton, one of nine killings he acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins, a bank robber serving a 25-year sentence, was called to
the stand by the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins conceded under cross-examination that the writs he and
Maturino Resendiz helped file were little more than
fill-in-the-blank forms.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, a Mexican citizen, was serving a 2{-year
sentence for illegal re-entry into the United States when he met
Rollins.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution began calling rebuttal witnesses Monday
following four days of defense testimony, including two psychiatric
experts who said delusions stirred by paranoid schizophrenia caused
the defendant to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz is on trial only for the rape, stabbing and
bludgeoning death of Benton. Lawyers believe he killed six people
in Texas, two more in Illinois and on in Kentucky from 1997 to
1999.
</P>
<P>
   If found innocent, Maturino Resendiz would probably be sent to a
mental hospital for an undetermined time and still would face at
least six more capital murder cases. A guilty verdict would mean
either lethal injection or life in prison, with no chance of parole
for 40 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
