<HEADLINE> Man Releases Hostages in Norway  </HEADLINE>
By KAARE LUNDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   HJELMELAND, Norway (AP) -- A man who took 25 children and 10
staff hostage at a Norwegian nursery school surrendered today,
releasing all the hostages unharmed after 10 hours, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified gunman surrendered after meeting with a
well-known criminal defense lawyer and speaking on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who said he had taken hostages because he had been
denied the right to see his own child, was driven away in a police
car with his attorney. The schoolhouse is located in Hjelmeland, a
town of about 2,500 people some 185 miles west of the capital,
Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   Police and ambulance crews immediately moved in to get the five
children and two female staff that had remained trapped by the man
after he released 28 others earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sitting here knowing that my first teen-ager just turned
13 in May, and I'm not even allowed to call,'' the man said in a
telephone call broadcast live by the TV-2 network before he
surrendered. ''Many would kill themselves because they couldn't
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to release the hostage taker's name or say
anything about potential motives, although news media speculated
that one of the female hostages was somehow involved in a rape case
in which the man was a suspect. Police confirmed that the hostage
taker was armed but refused to say what kind of weapon he had.
</P>
<P>
   The man had called the television station and demanded the right
to hold a news conference to present his side of a child custody
case. He lost the right to see his children because he had been
charged with rape, the network reported. TV-2 said he had also been
in contact with the station before the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His desperation resulted in the worst hostage case in this
peaceful nation of 4.5 million since 1994, when an elderly couple
and a police woman were taken hostage in a bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have nothing to lose. I have several times had a rope around
my neck,'' he said in the telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone call was broadcast on the Sentrum news show along
with a televised panel of psychologists and experts who listened in
and urged the man to think things through and not make good on his
threat to kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining hostages were being held inside the building,
although many of the children earlier were allowed outside in the
schoolyard.
</P>
<P>
   One of Norway's best known criminal lawyers, Tor Erling Staff,
who was mediating at the hostage-taker's request, had also entered
the building for face to face talks with the hostage-taker, the
Norwegian news agency NTB reported. Staff told NTB that he had made
a proposal by telephone, with getting much of a response. He
refused to give any details about the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The man stormed into the school at about 11 a.m., police said.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said they knew something was wrong when they
called the city-run school at 11:30 a.m. and a man answered the
phone and hung up. No men work at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a tragedy for a small, quiet and peaceful township like
Hjelmeland,'' city manager Fred Johansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sonderland said it would be tragedy anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''Using children for something like this, in Norway or anywhere
else, is a very serious matter ... these are children who are under
age 6,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1702 </TRAILER>
