<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen Divided Over 'Gender' Fight  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN'A, Yemen (AP) -- The women's studies program at San'a
University has been shut down and its director has fled the
country, leaving students in limbo. And all over a word -- gender.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim clergymen and some of the university's professors insist
''gender'' is an English word -- with no Arabic equivalent -- that
was being used at the women's institute as part of a conspiracy by
Westerners to bring in homosexuality and sexual freedom for women.
</P>
<P>
   Other professors and students say the controversy was
deliberately ignited by conservatives because they don't want to
have institutions in Yemen that spread liberal ideas like equality
between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real reason for the center's closure is political. The
Islamists didn't want it,'' said Fatima Jubran, 35, who was
studying for a master's degree at the women's program.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the conservatives won. The Empirical Research and
Women Studies Center has been closed since October while the
university revises the program's curriculum and looks for a new
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Mansour al-Zindani, a political science professor at the
university who pushed for the closure, said the Dutch-financed
center -- one of the most active women's institutes in Yemen --
''provoked this conservative Yemeni society by using 'gender' over
and over in its publications.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Every educated person knows that gender is a vague word that
some may interpret as kind, others as same-sex relationships and
some as equality of men and women,'' said al-Zindani, who's also a
high-ranking member of the Islamic Islah Party.
</P>
<P>
   The professor's brother, Sheik Abdul-Majeed al-Zindani, is a
well-known radical within the Islah party and heads its
policy-making Shura council.
</P>
<P>
   Many defend the women's studies program.
</P>
<P>
   ''The center was established to help in women's development and
look into women's issues through research and studies. There was
nothing immoral or decadent about its activities,'' said Mohammed
Ba Obeid, a professor of psychology at San'a University who also
taught at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Raoufa Hassan, director of the four-year-old center, went to the
Netherlands after mosque preachers denounced her as immoral. Some
100 male and female students preparing for one-year diplomas and
master's degrees in women's studies are left waiting while the
university examines the center's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   As the university deals with the controversy, tapes of rousing
mosque sermons denouncing the ''genderites'' at the center can be
found at stores.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an evil conspiracy under way. It's the gender
conspiracy,'' Sheik Mohammed al-Unsi says on one tape. ''Gender is
total decadence, meaning families constituting of men married to
men or women married to women. It also means that a woman can offer
herself to any man she fancies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
