<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBC Swaps 'Frasier,''Will &AMP; Grace'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is shifting ''Frasier'' to Tuesdays in the
fall, cutting back ''Dateline NBC'' to three nights and hoping to
resurrect the genre of nighttime soap operas with the man who made
''Dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The network, which announced its fall schedule on Monday, will
put the actor who played Jerry Seinfeld's buddy Kramer back on TV
but had bad news for Jerry's old nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The seven broadcast networks present their schedules to
advertisers this week, with ABC and the WB network Tuesday, CBS and
Pax TV on Wednesday, and Fox and UPN on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NBC is adding four new comedies and three dramas to its
schedule. It is eliminating its Saturday night lineup of dramas --
''Profiler,'' ''Pretender'' and ''The Others'' -- and axing the
comedies ''Suddenly Susan,'' ''Veronica's Closet,'' ''Jesse'' and
''Stark Raving Mad.''
</P>
<P>
   The network avoided a major problem when the six actors on
''Friends'' agreed this weekend to two more seasons at $20 million
a year each. Some other popular NBC shows, including ''ER,'' ''Law
and Order'' and ''Will &AMP; Grace,'' have multi-year commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Its boldest schedule move was bumping ''Frasier'' from the
popular Thursday lineup to Tuesday and replacing it with ''Will &AMP;
Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC expects ''Will &AMP; Grace,'' entering its third season, to have
a longer future and believes the best way to attack ABC's ''Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' is by appealing to a younger audience,
said Garth Ancier, NBC entertainment president.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dateline NBC'' has been the network's workhorse over the past
few years. But with evidence that the glut of newsmagazines is
causing audience fatigue, NBC is eliminating the Monday and
Wednesday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Neal Shapiro said he expects more editions of
''Dateline'' will be added if other shows fail.
</P>
<P>
   NBC hopes a new Aaron Spelling series, ''Titans,'' can revive
the genre of nighttime serials. It centers on a 26-year-old fighter
pilot who returns home to find his dad engaged to a former lover
who's about to bear the son's child.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the kind of total guilty pleasure fans of this genre
love,'' Ancier said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Michael Richards Show,'' with the actor who played
Seinfeld's sidekick, will feature Richards as an unconventional
private investigator. But the network passed on a pilot featuring
Wayne Knight. The public so identifies him with his ''Seinfeld''
character, Newman, that it isn't ready to accept him as a dad, said
Scott Sassa, president of NBC West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Movies will be shown on Saturday nights until February, when NBC
broadcasts games from the new football league it is starting with
the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   The usually jaded audience of advertisers watching NBC's
schedule announcement gave a standing ovation to the cast of the
freshman drama, ''The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   The five other new shows NBC will premiere in the fall:
</P>
<P>
   --''Dag,'' a comedy starring David Alan Grier as a demoted Secret
Service agent guarding the First Lady, played by Delta Burke.
</P>
<P>
   --''Tucker,'' a comedy modeled after Fox's successful ''Malcolm
in the Middle'' about a 14-year-old boy and his newly divorced
mother who move in with her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   --''The Steven Weber Show,'' which stars the former ''Wings''
actor as an executive whose life unravels after a blind date puts a
hex on him.
</P>
<P>
   --''Deadline,'' which gives producer Dick Wolf (''Law and
Order,'' ''Law and Order: Special Victims Unit'') his third hour on
NBC's schedule. It's a drama about a columnist working on a New
York City tabloid newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   --''Ed,'' a drama about a New York attorney who moves back to his
Midwestern hometown. It comes from David Letterman's production
company and was created by two ''Late Show'' writers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nbc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1717 </TRAILER>
