<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Last Chance for Knight  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is absolutely, positively the last defense of Bob Knight
you will read in this space.
</P>
<P>
   Until he gets caught.
</P>
<P>
   Practicing thought control.
</P>
<P>
   Or running a coven.
</P>
<P>
   Or implanting microchips in the cerebellums of his ballplayers,
buddies and bosses.
</P>
<P>
   On videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Knight stayed or went Monday was almost beyond the
point. The damage has been done. His run at Indiana will be history
soon, too.
</P>
<P>
   He is one dog who revels in refusing to learn new tricks. So
Indiana University president Myles Brand giving Knight one last
chance is as good a solution as any. This way, the next time
Brand's phone rings in the middle of the night, there will be no
questions about who is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Taping the university code of conduct to the front of Knight's
sweater like some scarlet letter would have been a waste of paper.
Forcing him to attend anger-management counseling would have only
engendered more !@$&AMP; .
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who read his stab at a first-ever apology should
remember he insisted on having the last word. That isn't about to
change. It's like Knight's request to be buried upside down, so his
critics could pay homage in the most uncritical way.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always been too confrontational,'' his Saturday night
apology read, ''especially when I know I'm right.''
</P>
<P>
   So how long before the next blow up?
</P>
<P>
   Not long enough that Brand couldn't afford to wait him out.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that if you stacked all of Knight's accomplishments
on one side of the ledger and all his embarrassments on the other,
there would have been some wiggle room left. But in order to buy
Knight that last chance, Brand had to level the piles.
</P>
<P>
   If Knight thought people were watching him a little too closely
before, just wait. In 29 seasons, he has run over and across
hundreds of kids, assistants, administrators and reporters, and his
file is already packed: 10,000 unfavorable newspaper reviews, a
dozen disciplinary notes, a half-dozen complaints from ballplayers,
run-ins with authorities, and now terrorizing a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Every headline loosens a few more repressed memories. And let's
not forget that the Stockholm syndrome -- in which hostages
gradually come to sympathize with their captors -- is almost
certainly the reason there are not more.
</P>
<P>
   Knight nearly braining a secretary by hurling a vase is
disturbing, because it's a departure from his usual tactics. Knight
rarely takes on guys his own size. That's what a bully is.
Intimidating a secretary is a new low. Even for him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ultimately, it's worth repeating what was said here when the
videotape came out proving Knight wasn't teaching Neil Reed how to
gargle while walking backward. Or what should have been said when
he did everything from intimidate school officials to smack his own
kids to leave a Tampax in a player's locker as a motivational tool.
</P>
<P>
   Duh. Nothing this guy does should surprise anyone anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Change the names and the situations and the stories all coalesce
into one. When he didn't get tossed for the first one or the
second, or the 30th, what was Knight supposed to think? Here's
what: That as long as the Hoosiers won basketball games, he was
bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   And Knight was.
</P>
<P>
   He loved to say that as long as he won, he was called nothing
worse than ''eccentric.'' But Knight hasn't won a Big Ten title
since 1993, or advanced past the second round of the NCAA
tournament the last half-dozen years. Now, he can't even be called
the best coach in his own league. Besides Tom Izzo, who took
Michigan State to the national title, most people building from
scratch would take Illinois' Lon Kruger and Ohio State's Jim
O'Brien ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer any question that some coaches do it better.
Mike Krzyzewski's name always comes up in that context. The Duke
coach played point guard for Knight at Army and served his coaching
apprenticeship there, too. Krzyzewski soaked up the lessons and
moved on; Knight is still teaching kids that basketball is war when
he should know better. The next time he tries will be too late.
</P>
<P>
   Knight has three national championships, though they happened
long enough ago to provide any more cover. The last stop on the
horizon for that select company of coaches that Knight travels is
Dean Smith's 879 career wins. Knight already has 753. He still
averages 20 wins per season, but it's the six or so more seasons
he'll need that now seem unattainable.
</P>
<P>
   It's still worth remembering that on sum, most of those who came
into contact with Knight will swear he had an impact on their
lives, helped determine what they did when they left the team and
in some cases, he even helped get them there.
</P>
<P>
   That's why some guys become coaches and why, so long as they're
successful, they get away with everything short of murder. Because
they can lead.
</P>
<P>
   He could, too.
</P>
<P>
   Once.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1728 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Author Questions Gulf War Actions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retired Gen. Barry McCaffrey and journalist
Seymour Hersh clashed Monday over allegations that troops led by
McCaffrey used unnecessary force in a battle with Iraqi troops
after the Gulf War cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The actions of McCaffrey's troops are questioned by several of
McCaffrey's former military colleagues in a report written by Hersh
in The New Yorker magazine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ex-colleagues, retired Lt. Gen. James H. Johnson Jr.,
is quoted as saying that ''there was no need to be shooting at
anybody'' on March 2, 1991. ''They couldn't surrender fast enough.
The war was over.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They were a defeated army going home and he attacked them,''
Hersh said on NBC's ''Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is nonsense, this is revisionist history,'' responded
McCaffrey, now director of the White House Office of National Drug
Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said two of his company commanders reported they were
under fire and ''we obviously had to support our soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army has investigated the allegations that McCaffrey ordered
an unnecessary attack and concluded there was no evidence of war
crimes or misconduct by McCaffrey or his troops.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Army issued a brief statement saying, ''No new
issues appear to have been raised in the story'' and ''there is no
need to reopen the investigation.'' It added: ''The Army has
confidence in the conduct and integrity of the soldiers of the 24th
Infantry Division.''
</P>
<P>
   Hersh ''is recycling charges that were investigated 10 years
ago. It conclusively demonstrated there was no wrongdoing,'' said
McCaffrey, who also appeared Monday on ABC's ''Good Morning
America'' and CBS's ''The Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart said McCaffrey has
Clinton's full support and said of the article: ''It is false.''
Lockhart also launched an attack on Hersh as a self-promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the article itself is another in a series of articles
by a journalist who thinks if you throw enough stuff up against the
wall, maybe something will stick,'' Lockhart said. ''It's an
attempt to gratuitously go after public officials in an attempt to
try to revive a journalist's career.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine said its research found:
</P>
<P>
   --There was disagreement among officers assigned to McCaffrey's
mobile headquarters about whether Iraqis had attacked American
forces, prompting McCaffrey's strong response. Patrick Lamar, the
operations officer of McCaffrey's division, told the magazine the
initial skirmish that triggered McCaffrey's order to attack was ''a
giant hoax. The Iraqis were doing absolutely nothing. I told
McCaffrey I was having trouble confirming the incoming'' fire.
</P>
<P>
   --Retired Lt. Gen. John J. Yeosock said ''what Barry ended up
doing was fighting sand dunes and moving rapidly'' and McCaffrey
was ''looking for a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   --Maj. Gen. Ronald Griffith said McCaffrey ''made it a battle
when it was never one.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack ordered by McCaffrey destroyed some 700 Iraqi tanks,
armored cars and trucks, The New Yorker reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hersh says that the Iraqi forces at Rumaylah were in
'retreat,''' McCaffrey said in a response. ''However, he wasn't the
one watching a force spanning five miles, made up of hundreds of
Iraqi tanks, trucks and armored personnel carriers face him. The
Iraqis fired on U.S. forces. The Army investigations unequivocally
concluded that the use of force in response was justified.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine noted that there were occasional ''bitter
disputes'' between McCaffrey and other generals over such things as
the perceived hoarding of tank and truck fuel by McCaffrey, whose
division performed the famed ''left hook'' maneuver that blocked
the retreat of Iraqi forces from the war zone in Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
