<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Argues for Open Ties to China  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said Monday he
will visit China this summer to discuss ways of establishing closer
ties to the Chinese military, including possible cooperation on
humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Economic Strategy Institute, Cohen argued for
keeping open lines of communication with China as a means of
influencing the future direction of the world's most populous
nation
</P>
<P>
   ''We in the United States have a particular opportunity to shape
this future course,'' he said. ''That is one of the reasons I have
spend so much of my time traveling to China. I will be going again
this summer to re-establish our military-to-military contacts so we
can discuss issues of how we can cooperate on humanitarian types of
operations, ... basically trying to reduce tensions which could
lead to confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen visited China in January 1998; he had planned to return
last year but that fell through when the United States led NATO's
air campaign against Kosovo. China suspended military-to-military
relations with the United States after the mistaken U.S. bombing of
China's embassy in Belgrade last May.
</P>
<P>
   Relations began to improve early this year when a settlement was
negotiated for damage to the embassy and lives lost in the bombing.
Adm. Dennis Blair, commander of the U.S. Pacific Command, visited
Beijing in late February.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Cohen urged congressional approval of permanent
normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us to reject (it), it seems to me, says to the Chinese
that we are treating you as an adversary,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1732 </TRAILER>
