<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Social Security Plan Reviewed  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Comments on Republican presidential candidate George
W. Bush's
Social Security reform plan and on plans generally to devote part
of the program to personal retirement accounts:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Both Bush and Gore should be commended for saying to the
public, 'Here's where I am' instead of waiting until after the
election.'' -- Martin Corry, AARP's federal affairs director.
</P>
<P>
   ''Social Security would be made a program that saves rather than
spends. Workers, not politicians, would control investment.
Personal accounts would create assets and wealth among lower-income
Americans who currently have none.'' -- Michael Tanner of the
libertarian Cato Institute, in praise of Bush's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are 100 percent against it. That son of a Bush should keep
his hands off my money.'' -- Sol Silverman, 85, joining Democratic
and union critics of the plan in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been talking about doing these things for seven years
and it's about time at least one of the parties caught up to us.''
Richard Thau, president of Third Millennium, a Generation X group
that supports partial privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't privities Social Security.'' -- A misspelled banner towed
by a plane over Bush's campaign event, sponsored by 2030 Action, a
group of people in their 20s and 30s opposed to partial
privatization.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Clinton-Gore administration had not scared people about
the state of the program with their pledges to 'save Social
Security first,' it is questionable that Bush would be proposing a
privatization plan today.'' -- Dean Baker, co-author of ''Social
Security: The Phony Crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The privatization approach endorsed by George W. Bush
partially insulates personal retirement finances from future fiscal
crises.'' -- Paul Hewitt, director of a global aging program at the
Center for Strategic and International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ''For almost every type of worker and family, retirement under
Social Security means receiving fewer dollars in old age and
passing on less wealth to the next generation that they could if
allowed to place their current Social Security tax dollars in
private retirement investments.'' -- David C. John of the
conservative Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''George Bush needs to be straight with voters. The costs of
privatization are unavoidably enormous.'' -- John Sweeney, president
of AFL-CIO, which has endorsed Democrat Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
