<HEADLINE> Sen. Thurmond Leaves Hospital Early  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Strom Thurmond has been released from the
hospital after being admitted for the second time in a week because
of an upset stomach and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond had been scheduled to spend Monday night at the Walter
Reed Army Medical Center but was released early after ''recovering
quicker than expected,'' his office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The 97-year-old lawmaker's office said he checked himself into
the hospital because he wasn't feeling well. It said Thurmond's
doctors had recommended he stay Monday night to ensure he is
completely recovered before returning to work.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond, R-S.C., the oldest senator in American history, also
spent two nights in the hospital last week after being diagnosed as
dehydrated as a result of a stomach ailment. He returned to the
Capitol on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in and out of hospitals several times in recent
years for a variety of problems and had prostate surgery last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
