<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Pushed To Release Fire Funds  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As fire raged in New Mexico, a Democratic
congressman urged Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott on Monday to
stop delaying an emergency spending bill that includes $250 million
to fight fires on federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to approve the money quickly could hurt the government's
ability to fight fires during what could be the worst fire season
since 1994, said Rep. Norm Dicks of Washington state, the ranking
Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee's interior
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the Senate not to act on this ... is just not right,''
Dicks said. The money ''should have been there in the accounts, and
it's not there because one person said, 'No,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., indefinitely postponed votes on the $13 billion
bill because he contends the money can be approved through the
normal appropriations process rather than on an ''emergency''
basis.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lott did not return a telephone call seeking
comment on Dicks' complaint, first made through a letter Friday to
the Senate majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans said firefighters on federal land in New
Mexico and throughout the country will have the money they need to
do the job. If federal officials do not have enough money in
firefighting accounts, they have broad authority to borrow from
other federal accounts, GOP aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has proven willing to reimburse any funds borrowed for
firefighting as part of the normal appropriations process, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is never any reason with the authority they (federal
officials) have to reduce any firefighting activities,'' said Doug
Crandall, chief of staff for the forests and forest health
subcommittee of the House Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency spending bill includes $100 million for
firefighting on Bureau of Land Management, Park Service and Fish
and Wildlife lands through the remainder of this year and early
next year, and $150 million for firefighting on Forest Service
lands.
</P>
<P>
   The House by a 263-146 vote on March 30 approved the bill, which
also includes money for combating drugs in Colombia, peacekeeping
in Kosovo and cleaning up after Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee has approved an agriculture
spending bill that includes $100 million for the BLM, Park Service
and Fish and Wildlife firefighting efforts. But that bill did not
include the $150 million for the Forest Service because it was not
part of the administration's request, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The agriculture spending bill could gain final approval and the
president's signature by July 4, the aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dicks said that would not be soon enough. Only 550
firefighting crews will be available this summer if the funds are
not approved quickly, instead of 625 crews that are typically
available, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP officials disputed that, saying the crews are funded
separately through fire prevention dollars. The request Dicks is
seeking would fund fire operations, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1807 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
