<DOCNO> APW20000515.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers' Group Plans New Standards  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Decrying ''amateurs'' teaching without
credentials, a coalition of educators announced Monday tough new
standards for teachers' colleges seeking endorsement of their
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of showing what classes are taught, colleges would have
to prove their graduates are good teachers to earn accreditation,
the group said. The plan, however, does not specifically call for
testing individual teachers for their expertise, which has had high
failure rates in states like Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe children are well served when anyone can walk
in off the street and be a teacher,'' said Arthur Wise, president
of the National Council for Accreditation of Teacher Education. But
he and other educators remained cool to alternative certification
programs that enlist former businesspeople or other experts without
in-depth teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   The council -- backed by teachers' unions, state school
superintendents and other educators -- unveiled a list of standards
the nation's roughly 600 teacher-college programs would have to
meet before receiving its seal of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the council say the group does little more than keep
the status quo. Teachers, for example, are not required to get
specific training in a subject like algebra or chemistry, nor must
they pass a universal test to become teachers -- much like the bar
exam required of an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the power of the decision of who is a qualified
teacher should be made at the principal level -- and for that you
need to know individual scores,'' said Charles R. Hokanson Jr., a
researcher at Thomas Fordham Foundation, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Wise said by next fall, teacher colleges would have to prove
they are graduating candidates capable of helping children learn.
The proof, he said, would include how many graduates pass state
teachers license exams, what principals and superintendents have to
say about the candidates' internship and job performances and
graduates' rating of how well university programs prepared them for
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges also must prove that graduates have been trained to
work with many children, including minorities and the disabled. The
group was vague on what role student test scores would play in
determining how well these new teachers teach.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a good start, said Jamie Horowitz, spokesman for the
American Federation of Teachers union, which recently proposed
mandatory entrance exams for new hires. Such plans have been
endorsed by President Clinton and presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher college accreditors and their institutions have been
accused of being irrelevant at best and lax at worst in preparing
the next generation of teachers. Wise said Monday however the
agency already rejects 1 in 4 college programs that don't meet its
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department says mass retirements and low-retention
over poor salaries and work conditions will lead to more than 2
million teaching vacancies in the next decade. Currently, filling
empty classrooms is difficult enough for highly populated districts
like Los Angeles, where two in three of last year's new hires
lacked full certification.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Chase, president of the National Education Association
teachers union, said Monday you can't fill classrooms without
paying attention to credentials -- arguing that even Albert Einstein
might not have been a good middle school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ''By no fault of their own, many so-called teachers are in fact
amateurs,'' he said. ''A woman who graduates from MIT with a degree
in physics has an abundance of knowledge ... but does she know how
to manage a classroom of teen-agers?''
</P>
<P>
   The accreditation, though endorsed by the Education Department,
is not required universally. But states like Maryland are moving
toward tying such credentialing to grants for universities.
</P>
<P>
   Just eight of Maryland's 22 teachers colleges have the
credential, but state schools superintendent Nancy Grasmick doesn't
expect the requirements to drive schools out of the
teacher-education business.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the teacher shortage, we are here to build capacity, not
reduce capacity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The standards can be found at: http://www.ncate.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1809 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Baseball Sites Announced  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Three newcomers, defending champion Miami and
perennial
selection Florida State are among the 16 schools given regional
sites for the NCAA's 64-team baseball tournament.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hosts, announced Monday, are guaranteed invitations to the
tournament. The entire field will be announced May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 16 regionals will run May 26-28 and feature four
teams in a double-elimination format. The survivor of each regional
advances to the ''super regionals,'' at eight sites to be announced
May 29. The eight winners of the super regional competition will
play in the College World Series in Omaha, Neb., beginning June 9.
</P>
<P>
   The regional hosts are Miami, Florida State, Arizona State, Cal
State Fullerton, Clemson, Georgia Tech, Lousiana-Lafayette, LSU,
Minnesota, Houston, Baylor, Mississippi State, Oklahoma, Rutgers,
South Carolina, and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers, Cal State Fullerton and Louisiana-Lafayette were all
given their first regionals. It will be Minnesota's first since
1977 and South Carolina's first since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers is the only school from the Northeast, a region that was
not represented last year.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State, which lost to Miami in last year's championship
game, was given its 16th regional in 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   All regionals are on campus except at Rutgers, which will use
Yogi Berra Park at Montclair State University, and Oklahoma, which
will use the Bricktown Ball Park at Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament expanded from 48 to 64 teams last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1811 </TRAILER>
