<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Says He Doesn't Have Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENSIDE, Pa. (AP) -- The latest mini-debate between George W.
Bush and Al Gore: whether the vice president has money in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing for his plan to allow Americans to privately invest
Social Security money, Bush said Monday, ''Al Gore, who calls these
bipartisan proposals risky, has a substantial amount of his money
invested in the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If he is building his own retirement security in the market,
why does he object to young Americans doing the same?'' Bush said
in Rancho Cucamonga, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who argues that privatizing Social Security would be a
dangerous gamble, does not have money in the stock market,
spokesman Chris Lehane told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush must be listening to the same ''little birdie''
that incorrectly told him Gore was a member of the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Who's right this time?
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp isn't counting at least one investment, in
Occidental Petroleum Inc., because it is part of a trust fund that
he does not own.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign says Gore will benefit from that trust
fund after his mother dies so it is, for all practical purposes, a
personal investment in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''That money will be a big part of his retirement nest egg,''
said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
