<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Venture Capital Fever  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL LIEDTKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Big business is playing an increasingly
larger role in venture capital investment, according to statistics
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A first-quarter survey by PricewaterhouseCoopers identified a
division of Chase Manhattan Bank as the leading venture capital
investor during the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Chase Capital's venture capital investments
totaled $289 million during the quarter, according to accounting
firm's ''Money Tree'' survey. Two other banks, Wells Fargo's
Norwest Equity Partners and BancBoston Capital Ventures, also
ranked among the most active in the venture capital market,
investing a total of $119 million and $115 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think big banks and companies are here to stay,'' said Tracy
Lefteroff, a PricewaterhouseCoopers' managing partner specializing
in venture capital.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and corporations are forming venture capital divisions
because of the huge payoffs generated in recent years by Internet
startups after they sold their stock in initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Established technology giants such as Intel Corp. and Microsoft
Corp. also are providing venture capital to startups.
</P>
<P>
   The allure of a windfall isn't the only draw for corporate
America. Lefteroff said many major companies have realized that
funding technology startups can give them the inside track on
innovations developed by entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America's interest in using the Internet to lower its
purchasing costs also played a big role in venture capital
investment during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists poured $1.4 billion into firms trying to
develop ''business-to-business'' Web sites that handle electronic
transactions between companies and their vendors. The $1.4 billion
invested in those firms represented a 15-fold increase from last
year and eclipsed the amount funneled into the once-hot
''business-to-consumer'' segment.
</P>
<P>
   Business-to-business entrepreneurs are catering to demand
created largely by corporate giants that expect to reap huge
savings by using e-commerce to buy supplies and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   Internet businesses accounted for the bulk of the first
quarter's total venture capital investments of $17.2 billion.
PricewaterhouseCoopers' figure is about $5 billion less than the
first-quarter total reported by the National Venture Capital
Association because of different calculation formulas, Lefteroff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-related companies attracted $10.8 billion, or 58
percent, of venture capital invested in the first quarter,
PricewaterhouseCoopers said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stock market's losses since March 31, venture
capitalists don't expect to turn off the investment spigot anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we are going through a real renaissance period in
technology and entrepreneurialism,'' said Stewart Alsop, a general
partner at New Enterprise Associates in Menlo Park. ''A guy who
drew up a good idea on a napkin on a coffee table could maybe get
$1 million or $2 million in venture capital a couple years ago.
Now, that guy with the napkin is getting $4 million or $5
million.''
</P>
<P>
   New Enterprise invested $186 million in the first quarter and
isn't pulling back, Alsop said.
</P>
<P>
   The PricewaterhouseCoopers survey also found that venture
capital is increasingly finding its way in regions outside the
country's technological hubs in the San Francisco Bay area, Los
Angeles, Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, venture capital investment in the Midwest totaled
$982 million in the first quarter, up 69 percent from 1999's final
quarter. The Silicon Valley remained the nation's entrepreneurial
hotbed with $6.1 billion in venture capital investments, a 7
percent increase from the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1819 </TRAILER>
