<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Speeds Phone Equipment Approval  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now that consumers have an abundance of
choices for their phones, modems and fax machines, federal
regulators are looking to privatize the process that helped build
that competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications equipment -- like phones and faxes -- must meet
certain technical criteria to show that they will not harm the
phone network once they are connected. Currently, the Federal
Communications Commission sets the standards and gives its stamp of
approval to the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But that can slow down the introduction of new products because
the commission has to examine about 4,000 items a year. Each review
can take four or more weeks. The process also puts additional costs
on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules proposed Monday, the FCC would hand over many of
these responsibilities to the private sector. In other words,
industry groups would set and maintain the technical standards to
make sure phones and other equipment don't harm the network. Other
groups or independent labs could then certify the products that
comply with the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''Retail outlets for telephone equipment would have been
unthinkable thirty years ago,'' said FCC Chairman William Kennard.
But now there is ''a very vibrant, robust, marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Industry Association predicted that such
streamlining could save manufacturers millions of dollars a year
and would ''expedite the process for bringing innovative
telecommunications equipment to the marketplace,'' said the group's
president Matthew J. Flanigan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Bell monopoly system -- and before the commission
established its approval process in 1975 -- only phones made by the
company typically were allowed to be hooked into the network. That
created another monopoly in the market for telecommunications
products.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC rules allowed other companies to certify their products
as safe to connect to the Bell network and helped foster
competition. Now retail store chains carry many varieties of phones
and faxes at a variety of prices.
</P>
<P>
   By reducing governmental involvement in the approval process,
the commission hopes to fuel even more innovation in the
marketplace for phone equipment. It could take several months
before the FCC votes to implement the proposed rules, and they take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1822 </TRAILER>
