<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court says patients in psychiatric hospital competent to vote  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- They may be patients in a state psychiatric
hospital, but a judge said Monday they are ''presumed competent''
enough to vote and cannot automatically be excluded from casting
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercer County Republican Committee contested any absentee
ballots cast in November 1998 by some patients at the Trenton
Psychiatric Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The county election board deadlocked on how to handle the
ballots, and a lower court judge ordered five of the seven sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a state appeals court says the ballots should be opened,
the votes counted and the election laws interpreted so psychiatric
patients at least get the opportunity to vote.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey law provides that every citizen of the appropriate
age can vote, except those who are ''an idiot or insane,'' Judge
Ariel A. Rodriguez wrote in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, there is no statutory definition of the terms
''idiot'' or ''insane'','' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no evidence ever presented ''as to the competency
of the individual voters,'' Rodriguez wrote. Without evidence
showing an individual voter is incompetent, ''involuntarily
committed residents of a psychiatric hospital are presumed
competent to vote,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   State election law does allow challenges to a specific
individual's right to vote, the judge noted. But ''there are
specific limitations on the powers of the challengers,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such policy derives from the basic precept that the right to
vote is quintessential to our democratic process,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Some may ask whether patients who have been involuntarily
committed to psychiatric hospitals are even able to register an
opinion on candidates, let alone vote, said S. Paul Prior, a staff
attorney for New Jersey Protection and Advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   That question ''goes to the heart of society's misconceptions of
people with mental illness or in psychiatric hospitals,'' said
Prior, who filed the original lawsuit on behalf of the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Patients in state hospitals are usually well enough to make
decisions for themselves after a few weeks of treatment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The blanket objection would be ''almost exactly like'' a
prescription barring residents in senior citizens' homes from
voting, Prior said. Some may be ''infirmed or invalid, but not all
are like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling lays out that the burden of disqualifying the
voter lies with the challenger, Prior said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is no different than any political party, any political
organization, challenging anyone else,'' Prior said. ''People with
mental illness should not be treated any differently than anyone
else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 1824 </TRAILER>
