<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Could Hurt Whistleblowers  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal agency that protects
whistleblowers says a recent decision by the Merit Systems
Protection Board could ''gravely threaten'' its ability to prevent
retaliation against employees who raise allegations of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Kaplan, head of the U.S. Office of Special Counsel,
criticized a recent ruling by the merit board that ordered OSC to
pay lawyers' fees to officials who are found ''substantially
innocent'' of any charges, even if the decision to prosecute was
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   If the decision stands, it could ''gravely threaten OSC's
ability to deter retaliation against whistleblowers,'' Kaplan said.
''While OSC would never seek to prosecute an agency manager without
possessing a well-founded belief that they had violated the law,
the board's decision would require us to predict to a certainty
that we will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   If the agency has to pay lawyers' fees every time it loses a
case, that could take a big chunk of cash out of an agency whose
annual budget is just $9.7 million, according to a watchdog group
that lobbied for the Whistleblower Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes it financially unrealistic for the OSC to take those
actions in all but the most extreme cases,'' said Tom Devine, legal
director for the Government Accountability Project, which defends
whistleblowers. ''By requiring victory, the decision's impact is to
raid the Office of Special Counsel's budget when it tries to impose
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a ruling by the merit board earlier this month that
the OSC had to pay the lawyers' fees for two Internal Revenue
Service supervisors cleared of retaliating against employees who
complained to the IRS assistant commissioner for investigations.
The merit board not only dismissed the charges, but agreed that the
supervisors could collect $33,000 in lawyers' fees from OSC.
</P>
<P>
   OSC spokeswoman Jane McFarland said the agency has asked the
Office of Personnel Management to request the merit board to
reconsider its decision. Failing that, the agency can appeal to the
U.S. Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland said OSC, instead of bringing charges itself, often
asks federal agencies to discipline employees. ''Agencies could be
more reluctant to self-police themselves if they feel we're not
going to pursue the matter,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
