<HEADLINE> American Home Products Investigated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A federal grand jury is investigating whether
American Home Products adequately reported adverse events involving
patients taking its diet drugs to the Food and Drug Administration,
the company reported in a filing Monday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, Pondimin and Redux were taken off the market in 1997
after studies linked them to serious heart problems. The drugs were
one half of the fen-phen diet drug combination that was taken by 6
million people.
</P>
<P>
   American Home has agreed to pay $3.75 billion to settle several
thousand lawsuits from people who took the drugs. A federal judge
in Philadelphia is now weighing whether to approve the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, American Home said it was unaware of a Federal Bureau
of Investigation inquiry into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In its filing on Monday, American Home said in early May it had
receive a grand jury subpoena from the U.S. Attorney for the
District of Maryland seeking documents regarding the company's
adverse event reporting system and its reports involving Redux and
Pondimin.
</P>
<P>
   American Home, in the filing, denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
