<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Skeptical of Russia Economic Aid  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration encouraged new
Russian President Vladimir Putin on Monday to speed up economic
reforms but said Russia still had not met conditions for receiving
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
   As International Monetary Fund staffers flew to Moscow for
preliminary talks, State Department officials said Russia still had
not completed necessary reforms in several areas, including its
banking system and safeguards for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   The officials, who declined to be identified, said the
administration was encouraging Putin's government to keep working
to meet the requirements necessary to receive funds.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF last July approved $4.5 billion in loans to Russia, and
paid out $640 million before suspending the program until further
reforms were passed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States plays a dominant role in IMF decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Belanger, the IMF's mission chief, is due in Moscow early
next week for technical discussions with Russian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has pledged to reform the economy and bring it closer to
Western standards. He appointed a brain trust in March to draft a
plan for a new economic program. It is expected to make
recommendations later this month.
</P>
<P>
   German Graf, who heads the group, has said Putin prefers rather
radical reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Putin has named a pro-reform economist, Mikhail
Kasyanov, to be Russia's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   These moves coincide with the approach of President Clinton's
trip to Moscow for talks with Putin June 4-5. Economic reform -- and
the difficult conditions much of the Russian population is trying
to cope with -- is high on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov said last week that a new, leaner tax code should be
prepared by the end of May to ''improve the investment climate and
reduce the tax burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, elected in March, has pledged to continue market reforms,
but neither he nor Kasyanov has outlined specific proposals for the
economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1833 </TRAILER>
