<HEADLINE> INS Calls Haddam's Asylum an Error  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Algerian Islamic leader alleged to have
terrorist links was mistakenly granted asylum in the United States,
an immigration official said Monday. The asylum was revoked when
the error was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's been in detention for more than three years since
his original asylum request was denied, Anwar Haddam was granted
the special status on an application filed for him by his wife in
the last several months, said the official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the error was made by the wife or the
INS, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Haddam's wife, Nassima, was granted asylum in November, a status
which allows her to apply for her family members. A section of the
application asks whether the family members are in detention or
have other status that makes them ineligible, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether she filled that out incorrectly -- or
whether she did it correctly and the INS overlooked it, the INS
official said.
</P>
<P>
   A physics professor and one-time candidate for parliament,
Haddam and his fundamentalist Islamic Salvation Front party won the
first round in Algeria's first-ever multiparty elections in late
1991. But the army canceled the second round in early 1992 when it
became clear the Salvation Front would win.
</P>
<P>
   The party was banned and many of its members were jailed or went
into exile.
</P>
<P>
   Haddam had been living in the Washington area from 1993 through
1996, as a representative of the parliamentary wing of the party
and awaiting a decision on his asylum request.
</P>
<P>
   He was jailed pending deportation in December 1996, when his
asylum was denied on so-called ''secret evidence,'' said his
lawyer, Malea Kiblan.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Nihad Awad of the Council of American Islamic
Relations, said the evidence included allegations that Haddam has
links to terrorist activities in the North African nation. Neither
Haddam nor his lawyer has been given access to this evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It has been alleged that Haddam is tied to the Armed Islamic
Group, a guerrilla movement fighting the military government in
Algeria. More than 100,000 people have been killed in the fighting
in Algeria over the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The (immigration) service has never produced an iota of
evidence that he belongs to anything other than the Islamic
Salvation Front, which is the party, period,'' Kiblan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has never advocated violence and has always advocated a
peaceful resolution to the conflict in Algeria,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Nassima Haddam filled out the form completely and
correctly, Kiblan said, ''Yes. And we provided them with his alien
registration number.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she got notification by mail Thursday that the asylum
had been granted May 5 and tried for much of the day Friday to
learn why Haddam hadn't been released from detention.
</P>
<P>
   Kiblan said she found a notice revoking the asylum on her fax
machine Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is deemed by the United States to be dangerous,
Haddam has remained in detention since December 1996 while he
fights an immigration order that he be removed from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   While he's been held here, he was convicted and sentenced to
death in absentia in Algeria for militant acts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1836 </TRAILER>
