<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Burns Historic WWII Buildings  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MacDONALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- The cluster of sagging, wooden buildings
where U.S. scientists created the world's first atomic bomb were
only recently spared the ravages of time. Now almost all of them
have been destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the six buildings that were home to World War II's
top-secret Manhattan Project were reduced to a pile of rubble last
week by the devastating Cerro Grande blaze that also burned more
than 200 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The fire that scorched its way across the Los Alamos National
Laboratory grounds did spare more modern buildings that are key to
the country's nuclear weapons projects. But lab officials said it
destroyed an irreplaceable link with the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those were some of the last really significant buildings from
the Manhattan Project era,'' said John Isaacson, who manages
cultural resources at the lab. ''We had really hoped to preserve
them. It's a real loss to our history.''
</P>
<P>
   The buildings were known in the 1940s as V Site. They served as
the center of operations for scientists who perfected and assembled
the explosive lenses used to detonate the Trinity test device, the
world's first nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The one building to survive was the project's final assembly
plant, said Ellen Bradbury, who heads the nonprofit group Recurosos
de Santa Fe, which was raising money to save the structures.
</P>
<P>
   That building was the most historically significant of the six,
Bradbury said Monday, adding her group's fund-raising efforts would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings, like many others at Los Alamos from that era,
were abandoned at the end of Word War II. While others were torn
down to make room for more modern facilities, V Site survived,
mainly because its secluded location made demolition hardly
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   For 55 years the buildings slowly decayed. Their roofs began to
sag and leak, and the desert sun baked their wooden frames to a
brittle texture.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently, efforts had begun to save them. After the lab won
a federal grant to restore the structures, volunteers began a drive
to raise matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson said the goal was to turn V Site -- once a
high-security, off-limits area -- into an interpretive center open
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But then last week flames from a National Park Service burn that
got out of control spread onto lab property.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were able to save the nation's only active
plutonium facility and other sites, but five of V Site's buildings
fell to the flames one after another.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 60 other World War II-era buildings scattered
around the 43-square mile lab site, Isaacson said. But none of them
hold such historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most just served as storage facilities or an administrative
building,'' he said. ''But V Site was different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1837 </TRAILER>
