<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: NJ hospitals getting better at cardiac surgery  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- More people are surviving coronary bypass
surgery in New Jersey hospitals, according to a state health
department report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Better medical practices, spurred in part by the state's annual
''report card,'' have improved care for cardiac patients, state
health officials said during a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1998, the percentage of bypass patients who
died fell from 3.75 percent to 2.6 percent -- a 30 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, surgeons at 14 New Jersey hospitals performed 8,377
bypass surgeries, with 218 patients dying either during the
procedure or in the hospital afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are even better when state health officials adjust
for the severity of a patient's illness. Since very sick patients
are more likely to die, health officials account for various risk
factors -- age, sex and other health conditions, such as whether a
patient also has kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   The adjusted rate dropped nearly 40 percent -- from 4 percent in
1994 to 2.6 percent in 1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiac surgeons said the report has led doctors and hospitals
to closely examine their techniques, identify problem areas and
institute better practices.
</P>
<P>
   Coronary artery bypass graft surgery is a treatment used when
one or more coronary arteries are clogged. It's the most common
type of heart procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Health and Senior Services Commissioner Christine
Grant said the report's intent is to get hospitals and surgeons to
scrutinize themselves. She said consumers can also use the
information to seek better care and ask better questions of their
providers.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant warned against avoiding a hospital because it has a
higher-than-average death rate. Hospitals may have made changes in
their programs since 1998, including having different surgeons or
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''It gives patients one more bit of information as they make
decisions with their doctors,'' said Dr. Alfred Casale, associate
chief of cardiac surgery at the Atlantic Health System.
</P>
<P>
   The report shows that two hospitals -- Newark Beth Israel and
Cooper Hospital/University Medical Center in Camden -- had
above-average death rates in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Newark Beth Israel has had higher than average rates for each of
the three years the report has been compiled. State officials
couldn't say exactly why, although they acknowledged that poverty
may be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Poor people tend to wait longer to get medical care and so would
have more serious problems -- some of which are not adjusted for in
the risk factors, explained Dr. Jan Weber, a cardiologist at Our
Lady of Lourdes Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Craig Saunders, cardiology chief at Newark Beth Israel, said
his hospital has completely overhauled its cardiac unit, replacing
many surgeons. He expects patient outcomes to improve.
</P>
<P>
   Volume may also be a factor. National studies show hospitals
that perform more procedures generally get better results. Beth
Israel doctors performed 414 bypasses in 1998, while Cooper
surgeons did 273. That compares to 1,177 at Morristown Memorial
Hospital, which has the best bypass results in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But volume isn't everything. St. Francis in Trenton was the only
other hospital that had lower than average death rates, and the
hospital performed only 238 bypasses in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The other 10 hospitals had death rates that were in line with
the state averages.
</P>
<P>
   The report also shows that University Hospital in Newark failed
again to meet state requirements to perform at least 350 surgical
heart procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Health department spokeswoman Rita Manno said the hospital is
hiring a consultant to evaluate the program and come up with ways
to increase volume. The hospital scrapped a plan to merge with
another cardiac unit -- a solution offered when last year's report
card also showed the hospital failing to meet state requirements,
Manno said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous years, this report does not list the success
rate of surgeons who performed more than 100 procedures per year.
Changes in the way the data are collected prevented that, state
health officials said, but promised the information will be on next
year's report card.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.state.nj.us/health
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 1839 </TRAILER>
