<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Continental Drops Fare Increase  </HEADLINE>
By C. BRYSON HULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- After leading a round of air fare increases over
the weekend, Continental Airlines Inc. surprisingly rescinded its
decision Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was uncertain whether other carriers also would
abandon the increases of $10 to $30 a round trip on business and
leisure fares. But they predicted future attempts to raise fares
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Continental spokeswoman Julie Gardner confirmed that the
nation's fifth-largest air carrier dropped plans for the fare
increase that was announced Thursday but would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the nation's three largest air carriers -- United
Airlines, American Airlines and Delta Air Lines -- said they would
match Continental's increase.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 US Airways Inc. had matched both increases Friday but
changed course Monday. ''The fare increase is in effect on our
busines fares but not on our leisure fares,'' US Airways spokesman
David Castelveter said Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Continental's reversal left the fare picture clouded at the
onset of the peak vacation travel season.
</P>
<P>
   Though American, Northwest and Delta all said they were
increasing all fares, industry watchers said it appeared those
airlines had rolled back the leisure increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to have to wait until Tuesday, but my guess is the
leisure hike will be dropped and the business fare will hold,''
said Terry Trippler of 1travel.com, an online seller of discount
travel tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines Corp., the fourth-biggest carrier, fell in
line with the increase Sunday after announcing Friday it would not
raise its prices. Trans World Airlines and America West Airlines
also confirmed Monday they would match the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said Delta's tardiness in announcing its
intentions may have doomed a price raise.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of those where they had it 100 percent if Delta
moved, but because Delta was slow to match it, and some of the
other airlines chickened out, they all may lose this fare hike,''
said Tom Parsons, editor of Bestfares.com, a website that sells
discounted airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But Parson said because this attempt nearly succeeded, the
airlines will take it as a sign to try again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's anything we should be looking for, we should look
for another fare hike attempt,'' Parsons said. ''It doesn't mean
it's over, it just means its over today.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked the fourth time this year Continental tried to
raise fares. Two Continental-led increases stuck this year, one in
January and one in March.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggested Continental was taking advantage of high
service rankings. The airline took first place last week in a
survey of frequent flyers by research firm J.D. Power and
Associates. Airlines were scored on on-time performance, food
service, flight attendants and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they feel they're more in a position to lead on
price,'' said Glenn Engel, an airline industry analyst with
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Continental cited rising fuel costs as its original reasons for
boosting fares.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, crude oil prices hovered near $30 a barrel. An
expectation of strong U.S. summer demand pushed the prices over the
$30 mark on Friday for the first time since March 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1856 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Still Unsure of Candidacy  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani canceled a fund-raising
trip to California but said Monday he has still not decided whether
to run for the Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton or what course
of treatment he'll take for his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he still needed to consult with doctors and decide
whether to undergo surgery or radiation treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last week, because of things involving my personal life, my
family and everything else, I didn't have the time,'' he said.
''So, I'm going to need to do that this week. ... You have to make
the decision when you are ready to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past three weeks, Giuliani, 55, has disclosed that he
has treatable prostate cancer and that he is seeking a legal
separation from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, TV personality and actress Donna Hanover, has accused
him of having had a relationship with a former City Hall aide, and
Giuliani himself has acknowledged an ongoing relationship with
another woman, whom he has characterized as a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   Some aren't waiting to see what the mayor will do next.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Building and Construction Trades Council,
representing 200,000 workers in 300 unions, on Monday endorsed
Clinton for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The union previously backed Giuliani for mayor and other
Republicans as well, including Gov. George Pataki and former Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato. Union president Edward Malloy said the group made
its choice in the Senate race a month ago, before Giuliani's health
problems and the extent of his marital woes became known.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Giuliani, Clinton said she was not focused on
her rival.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no control over what the Republicans do,'' the first
lady said. ''I'm just not thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Further clouding his future in the race, Giuliani canceled a
planned fund-raising swing to Southern California scheduled for
Tuesday and Wednesday, saying he needs to consult with doctors.
</P>
<P>
   He still planned on appearing at a fund-raiser in Manhattan on
Monday evening and is scheduled to appear Thursday at a town
hall-style meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
