<HEADLINE> NBC Expanding 'Today' to 3 Hours  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The workday is about to expand for Katie Couric
and Matt Lauer. NBC announced Monday it will expand the dominant
''Today'' show from two to three hours this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The show will air from 7 a.m. to 10 a.m., starting Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has talked internally about expanding ''Today'' for about 20
years. But a series of factors, including the show's ratings
strength and its immense profitability, made the time right for NBC
President Andrew Lack to announce the move to affiliates on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something we've wanted to do for years,'' said ''Today''
executive producer Jeff Zucker. ''The 'Today' show has never been
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Later Today,'' which airs from 9 to 10 a.m. on most NBC
stations, will be pushed back an hour on the 13 NBC
owned-and-operated stations.
</P>
<P>
   Couric and Lauer will be part of the extra hour, but the
additional time will also give NBC the chance to increase the roles
of newscaster Ann Curry and weatherman Al Roker. Both have been
eager to do something more.
</P>
<P>
   The network and its stations clear an estimated $200 million in
profits a year through the ''Today'' show, which dominates ABC's
''Good Morning America'' and ''The Early Show'' on CBS. The chance
for another highly profitable hour was too hard for NBC executives
to resist.
</P>
<P>
   NBC didn't want to try it last fall, when ''Later Today''
debuted, because it was concerned about tougher competition for
''Today.'' But ''The Early Show'' has been a ratings disaster for
CBS. ''Good Morning America'' has picked up steam, but has not
seriously challenged NBC's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The network also perceives a potential weakness at 9 a.m. on
many ABC stations when Kathie Lee Gifford leaves ''Live with Regis
and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger for NBC lies in overexposure or stretching its
''Today'' team too thin. The cable network MSNBC recently tried
airing reruns of ''Today'' in the early afternoon, but it did
poorly in the ratings and was quickly replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Although ''Later Today'' is continuing, Monday's news doesn't
augur well for the talk show. It began last fall to tepid reviews
and mediocre ratings. It will be on at 10 a.m. for roughly
one-third of the nation's television viewers but must be sold in
syndication to the other markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
