<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Peacekeepers Stranded  </HEADLINE>
By TIM SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- More than 100 U.N. peacekeepers
freed by Sierra Leone's rebels were stranded Monday in a remote
corner of neighboring Liberia as negotiators worked for the release
of hundreds of others still being held captive.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend releases of some U.N. hostages gave guarded hope
that the imperiled U.N. peacekeeping mission in Sierra Leone could
be put back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ''As you can imagine, the morale (of U.N. personnel) is good and
their men are encouraged by this,'' U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said in New York. ''Things are improving every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-month-old peace agreement was shattered this month after
Revolutionary United Front rebels seized about 500 U.N. captives
and fighting broke out between rebels and government troops. Most
of the hostages are believed to be Zambian.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels freed a total of 157 hostages over the weekend, but
as of Monday, only a small number had been able to return safely to
their units. The biggest group of freed hostages -- about 124 -- was
awaiting evacuation from the town of Foya on Liberia's border with
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are facing very serious logistical problems to airlift
them,'' said Lassana Kouyate, a senior official with the 14-nation
West African economic group, ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian officials who negotiated the captives' release said
they did not have enough aircraft to evacuate those released. In
addition, road access to Foya is almost impossible during the
spring rainy season.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, a U.N. official in Liberia
said the United Nations was unwilling to fly its own helicopters
near rebel territory for fear they would be shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Another 18 hostages were allowed Sunday to return to an Indian
U.N. contingent in eastern Sierra Leone. However, their safety, was
not guaranteed. The area remained surrounded by rebels, and U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard called it a ''kind of relaxed detention.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 15 freed U.N. captives were flown by a
government-chartered helicopter to Liberia's capital, Monrovia, on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels continued to hold about 350 U.N. hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Oluyemi Adeniji, the U.N. special representative to Sierra
Leone, said no concessions had been made for the releases, and he
praised Liberia's President Charles Taylor for his role in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is the RUF's closest ally in the region and had been
asked by West African leaders to mediate with rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor claimed the United States had refused air transport to
evacuate the freed hostages, and that the men were therefore forced
to trek through the jungle for nearly three days after their truck
got stuck on bad roads. U.S. ambassador to Liberia Bismark Myrick
declined immediate comment on the claims Monday, describing the
hostage crisis as ''delicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who has long had strained relations with the West,
warned that continued attacks by Sierra Leone's government and its
allies against the rebels ''threaten the lives'' of the remaining
U.N. captives.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the U.N. Security Council heard a closed-door
briefing on Sierra Leone from Bernard Miyet, the
undersecretary-general for peacekeeping who returned from the West
African country last week.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters afterwards, Miyet defended the U.N. force
arguing that it had succeeded in protecting the capital, Freetown.
He said Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front ''is on the
defensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan hinted Monday that the hostage crisis could cost RUF
leader Foday Sankoh the ministerial post he was given as part of
the peace agreement made last July. As commissioner for the
management of strategic resources, national reconstruction and
development, Sankoh is in charge of the diamond industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot have a state where a group of rebels arrogate
themselves the right to exploit the riches of the country either
for themselves or for a war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In their eight-year campaign against the government, the rebels
have killed tens of thousands and mutilated and dismembered many
more in a bid to gain power through intimidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1911 </TRAILER>
