<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Slams Bush on Social Security  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush proposed letting
Americans invest Social Security taxes in the stock market Monday,
appealing for support from the millions of people who have thrived
in a booming market.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential rival Al Gore condemned the idea as a dangerous
gamble that would turn the solemn obligations of the 65-year-old
retirement plan into ''a system of winners and losers.''
</P>
<P>
   In what could be one of the defining issues of the general
election campaign, Bush outlined his plans for modernizing Social
Security in a speech to senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, the Republican said, ''this generation and this
president will save Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ''I am here with a message for America and to put my
opponent on notice: The days of spreading fear and panic are
over.'' Yet he also said that unless proper action is taken the
system is heading for ''the moment of financial collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he raised a vision that under his plan -- with
many details still to come -- ''a worker who invests even a limited
portion of his or her paycheck could, over a career, end up with
hundreds of thousands of dollars for retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not say how much of the current 12.4 percent Social
Security tax should be freed for private investment; the most
commonly discussed option is for 2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in suburban Philadelphia, contended that diverting money
into the stock market would risk Social Security's promise of a
guaranteed income to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we turn the Social Security system into a system of winners
and losers, we will be jeopardizing retirement security for too
many Americans and in the end we will all have to pay to make up
the differences,'' the Democratic vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Bush's event, a group with apparently more passion than
spelling ability hired a plane that trailed a banner reading:
''Don't privities Social Security.'' The group, 2030 Action, says
it speaks for people in their 20s and 30s who oppose partial
privatization of the program.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, however, is supported by many younger workers who are
not averse to risks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Grandma always said, 'Don't put all your eggs in one
basket,''' said Richard Thau, president of Third Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Bush is betting his proposal will show he is
willing to tackle vexing issues in a bipartisan manner. He also
hopes it will be embraced by the new class of investors and
e-traders who have propelled the stock market to unprecedented
heights.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is exactly what the American workers want,'' said Leanne
Abdnor, director of a lobbying coalition of employers, including
the National Association of Manufacturers and the Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But AFL-CIO President John Sweeney said the costs of
privatization ''are unavoidably enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore retains an advantage in polls among senior citizens -- a
group that considers Social Security sacred and is a consistent
voting bloc. The vice president led Bush 49 percent to 40 percent
among those 65 and over in a poll this month by the Pew Research
Center.
</P>
<P>
   However, he had led the Texas governor by more than three times
that margin in a Pew poll in March.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a reduction in the payroll tax, that money has to be made
up or unfortunately it leads to difficult trade-offs,'' said Martin
Corry, director of federal affairs for AARP, the nation's largest
organization of older adults.
</P>
<P>
   Americans trust Gore over Bush on the issue of handling Social
Security, 47 percent to 39 percent, according to a CBS-New York
Times poll released Monday. The idea of allowing people to invest
some of their Social Security funds is supported by just over half
the public, with more than half of 18- to 44-year-olds supporting
it, and a majority of adults over age 45 opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of Social Security reform is driven by demographics:
Life expectancies are increasing, the 77-million-member baby boom
generation is about to retire and fewer workers will be working to
cover benefit payments. As it now stands, the system is projected
to become insolvent in 2037.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also pledged to:
</P>
<P>
   --Maintain current benefits for those at or near retirement.
</P>
<P>
   --Put payroll taxes off limits to prevent borrowing against the
Social Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   --Refuse to increase payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   --Preserve the system's current provision to pay benefits to
widows, widowers and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   --Prohibit the government itself from investing Social Security
funds in the stock market, preferring instead to let individuals
make the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, at Beaver College in Glenside, Pa., said: ''Today when
Wall Street is booming, I know that plan sounds appealing ... but
in reality the Bush Social Security privatization plan would weaken
our economy and undermine the basic guarantee of a minimum decent
retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's advisers also say Bush hasn't fully
accounted for up to $1 trillion in costs that would be incurred as
the system began taking in less money from workers but paying out
the same benefits until the transition was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's chief economic adviser, Lawrence Lindsey, conceded that
some of the costs might have to be paid out of the treasury, but
said such projections are too far off to allow for accurate
accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also outlined his principles for Medicare, the medical
insurance program for the elderly, such as giving every recipient a
choice of health plans including at least one providing
prescription drug coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1913 </TRAILER>
