<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Boosts School Impact Aid  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House lawmakers agreed to increase the funds
that go to school districts where federal operations, such as
military installations, cut into the local tax base.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, on a voice vote Monday, provided $906 million for
Impact Aid, one of the largest programs in the federal K-12 budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''Impact Aid is truly a federal responsibility,'' Rep. Bill
Goodling, R-Pa., said of the legislation -- which enjoyed a
bipartisanship rare among the latest round of education lawmaking.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also allowed schools to count children living in
privatized military housing and sets aside construction money for
schools with health or safety hazards.
</P>
<P>
   School systems get most of their money from state income taxes
or local property taxes on homes and businesses. But they can lose
revenues because the military pays no property taxes and service
people shop at commissaries and avoid sales taxes. The 1950 law
first signed by President Truman mainly funds school districts
according to how many of the nation's 1.3 million military children
they teach.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 17 million children are affected by financially
struggling districts, said John Forkenbrock, executive director of
the National Association of Federally Impacted Schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can expect stability,'' Forkenbrock said Monday.
''There's been a lot of anxiety among school administrators over
what happens when property is deeded to private developers'' who
build housing for military families.
</P>
<P>
   Many military posts have schools run by the Defense Department,
but military families often send their children to civilian schools
-- either because they live off base or the post doesn't have a
nearby Defense Department school.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Scott, a Democrat from the Norfolk, Va., area, also
said schools suffer in metro areas such as his district -- where
many families are connected with the military but not necessarily
living on bases.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, said Forkenbrock, downsizing overseas has brought more
military families to U.S. installations. The new plan would give
more money to a school systems like Killeen, Texas, which is
expanding because of new arrivals to the nearby Fort Hood army
post, he said.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers approved nearly $200 million more than proposed
for this year's budget by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Education Department spokeswoman Erica Lepping said the House
legislation expands the number of districts eligible for the
money,and doesn't properly target the neediest schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the needs of the Impact Aid community would
adequately be met by the funding level the president proposed,''
Lepping said. She said the department had no overall objections to
the bill, but would like to negotiate changes in the funding
formulas that ''reflect current costs and needs rather than be
based on outdated calculations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lee Terry, R-Neb., whose district includes Offutt Air Force
base, said Monday: ''Our students and teachers should not be
treated as second class citizens. Every year Congress rides to the
rescue of these schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's version of the program also calls for more funds
and formula adjustments. But unlike the separate House bill, its
Impact Aid funding is part of a larger bill renewing all of the
programs under the Elementary and Secondary Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   That $20 billion bill -- the subject of much debate over federal
control of education -- is pending because Senators agreed to work
on military construction issues this week.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   The Impact Aid bill number is H.R. 3616.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Legislative information: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1914 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
