<DOCNO> APW20000515.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Saves the Day on 'Futurama'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENSIDE, Pa. (AP) -- It's a cartoon Al Gore on a TV show that no
one would mistake for the nightly news. But when you're running for
president, saving the day in any form is worth noting.
</P>
<P>
   Extending the perks of power beyond Air Force Two, Gore takes a
guest turn on ''Futurama,'' the Fox cartoon featuring characters
making their way through the 30th century.
</P>
<P>
   Producer David Cohen read that ''Futurama'' was one of Gore's
favorite shows and arranged for the vice president to play himself
in the season finale airing Sunday, May 21.
</P>
<P>
   In the episode, the mad scientist, Prof. Farnsworth, invents a
''What If?'' machine that lets each character find out what would
happen if one of their wishes was granted.
</P>
<P>
   Fry, a 20th century guy who is cryogenically frozen and wakes up
in the future, asks what would have happened had he not bumped his
head and fell into the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   He goes back to 1999, learns that his life was just as lame as
before the bump on the head, and it falls to Gore and his team of
''Action Rangers'' to return Fry to the 30th century.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting Gore are physicist Stephen Hawking, Star Trek actress
Nichelle Nichols and Gary Gygax, creator of Dungeons &AMP; Dragons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1917 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Rips GOP on 'Pork' Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Flashing his maverick instincts anew, Sen.
John McCain warned his own Republican Party leadership on Monday
that the voters will ''repudiate'' them for ''profligate''
pork-barrel projects they put into spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The vanquished GOP presidential contender used words including
''offensive,'' ''appalled'' and ''ashamed'' to describe projects
lawmakers included in an $8.6 billion military construction bill
while omitting $6 million to help 12,000 military families come off
the food stamp rolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican said there are $900 million worth of
projects in the bill that the Defense Department has not requested.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Republican leadership and the chairmen of these
committees continue to spend taxpayers' dollars in this profligate
manner, sooner or later the American people will repudiate these
actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added later, ''This bill is a classic example of the
abrogation of our responsibilities to average taxpayers, those who
are not represented'' in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   For years, McCain has complained about home-district projects
his colleagues add to spending bills, and Monday's remarks were a
continuation of that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, this time they came after a presidential campaign
in which he strove to cast himself as an independent voice who is
not afraid to take on causes, even ones unpopular among other
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, McCain's comments were loaded with specific examples
of projects he found objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the first one he mentioned was the bill's section 2109,
which he dryly described as ''a funding profile for a ship that has
not been requested by the Navy, cannot be built under the expedited
process the ship's congressional sponsor seeks to impose.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he mentioned no names, that project is sponsored by
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. Lott supported Texas
Gov. George W. Bush for the GOP presidential nomination and made
several tart remarks about McCain while the senator's campaign was
still under way.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for providing at least a $263 million installment
on a $1.5 billion LHD-8 amphibious assault ship to be built at a
shipyard in Lott's hometown of Pascagoula, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about McCain's remarks, Lott spokesman John Czwartacki
cited comments from a speech he said McCain made last December 7 in
New York. According to Czwartacki, McCain said the Navy has
''neglected modernization'' of such ships, adding, ''We must begin
immediately to buy equipment on which our future security
depends.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's exactly what we're trying to do,'' Czwartacki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
