<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires May Uncover Historical Sites  </HEADLINE>
By JOLYN OKIMOTO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Although dangerous and destructive, wildfires
like those raging across New Mexico and Arizona can also have
beneficial effects. One is uncovering archaeological sites crucial
to understanding an area's history, experts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fire reduces vegetation, sometimes revealing clues to earlier
civilizations. Archaeological findings in the wake of fires are so
common that firefighting teams routinely include archaeologists who
advise on how to protect potential sites.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists are assisting in the fire that has consumed more
than 44,000 acres of forest and destroyed 260 homes in Los Alamos,
N.M. As of now, they are sure the fire has damaged more sites than
it will reveal.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is very little good about this fire,'' said Mike
Elliott, an archaeological assistant at the Santa Fe National
Forest. He noted that among other things, the fire is so hot it can
split and chemically alter rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The fire has already destroyed some sensitive archaeological
sites on the edge of the Santa Clara Pueblo, an Indian reservation
15 miles northeast of Los Alamos, said tribal fire spokesman Alvin
Warren. He did not elaborate on the damage.
</P>
<P>
   An example of fire than did some good from an archaeological
perspective is a 1996 blaze at the Mesa Verde National Park in
Colorado. It exposed more than 400 archaeological sites, mainly
cliff dwellings and small dams.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sites had been covered by dense oak brush and a pinon
juniper forest until the fire eliminated the density,'' said Jane
Anderson, the project manager for the rehabilitation of the nearly
4,800-acre area.
</P>
<P>
   The sites, dating back to the 1200s and 1300s, had been
inhabited by the ancestral Pueblo Indians who now live along the
Rio Grande, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists were surprised by the sites' density, which
suggested more people living in the area than initially thought,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several fires in 1996 near Flagstaff, Ariz., revealed both
historic and prehistoric sites. They ranged from logging and
railroad lines about 80 years old to artifacts dating from 700 to
1100, said Linda Farnsworth, a Forest Service archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
   But while fires can reveal archaeological sites, firefighters'
suppression efforts can damage them.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers and heavy machinery can destroy sites and fire
retardants dropped from helicopters can stain rocks, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Often the only vestige of a wall is a row of rocks, she said.
''To an untrained eye, it would be very easy to dig that up,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said archaeologists are already planning how to protect
what may be left after the fire near Los Alamos is extinguished --
particularly from erosion expected once summer rains hit deforested
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't fix what the fire has done to the sites,'' Elliott
said. ''But we can slow erosion and other problems in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
