<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Says Drifter Not Insane  </HEADLINE>
By MARK BABINECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Admitted serial killer Angel Maturino Resendiz
did not suffer from paranoid schizophrenia or any other major
psychosis when he killed a Houston-area physician, a
court-appointed psychiatrist testified Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to testimony from two defense experts, Dr. Ramon Laval
said the 40-year-old Mexican drifter suffers from several
personality disorders and harbors ''strange'' beliefs, but was not
insane when he killed Dr. Claudia Benton in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''He knew what he was doing,'' said Laval.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz's beliefs that he has supernatural powers,
such as the ability to predict disasters or leave his own body, are
not signals of major mental illness, Laval testified.
</P>
<P>
   ''However idiosyncratic, strange or weird, these are not
delusions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has pleaded innocent by reason of
insanity in the slaying of Benton, one of nine killings he
acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Dr. Bruce Cohen, a forensic psychiatrist
testifying for Maturino Resendiz, said the defendant suffered from
delusions brought on by paranoid schizophrenia, or the inability to
discern reality.
</P>
<P>
   During his third and final day on the stand, Cohen acknowledged
that Maturino Resendiz knew that killing Benton and eight others in
three states between 1997 and 1999 was illegal, but maintained that
he thought he was doing God's work in his diseased mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would agree he was acting out of severe anger,'' Cohen said.
''But the question is, what was the basis of that anger?''
</P>
<P>
   Before resting, defense attorney Allen Tanner attempted for a
second time to admit into evidence a videotape of Maturino
Resendiz's initial interrogation the night after his surrender in
El Paso in July. State District Judge Bill Harmon withheld a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Melissa Ferguson, another psychiatrist and director of the
Harris County Mental Health-Mental Retardation Authority's jail
unit, said she detected no severe mental illness upon his arrival
July 14.
</P>
<P>
   He was later admitted to the jail's psychiatric ward on a
suicide watch, but Ferguson said she diagnosed him with
depression-related psychosis, never paranoid schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   She did note, however, that his thoughts seemed to revolve
around ''hyperreligious'' subjects that indicate a personality
disorder. The defense claims deluded Judeo-Christian beliefs are at
the root of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Tanner, Ferguson said a regimen of
anti-psychotic drugs caused Maturino Resendiz to tone down his
religious rantings, adding that his delusions had stemmed from
depression instead of schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's first rebuttal witness was a convicted bank
robber who testified that he and Maturino Resendiz counseled fellow
inmates on pleading insanity while they were in prison in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Mitchell Rollins, 43, who remains at a federal prison in
Florence, Colo., said Maturino Resendiz even helped him make a
bogus incompetence claim to try to win a new trial when they were
cellmates in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ordered some books and read up on it,'' Rollins said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers expected jurors to get the case Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   If found innocent, Maturino Resendiz likely would be sent to a
mental institution for an undetermined time and still would face at
least six other capital murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   A guilty verdict would mean either lethal injection or life in
prison, with no chance of parole for 40 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1932 </TRAILER>
