<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Girl Killed in Teen Driver Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. (AP) -- A teen-ager too young to hold a
driver's license was fleeing from police when he crashed his
parents' car through a drainage ditch and sent it airborne into a
swimming pool, killing a 12-year-old passenger, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers were investigating a report of a suspicious car at 2:30
a.m. Sunday when they spotted the sedan with Michael Singh, 14, at
the wheel, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the car sped away, but officers didn't chase it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We suspect that when he saw the police car in back of him that
he panicked because he had no license and did not have
authorization to have the car,'' police spokesman Chuck Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The car went through a stop sign, careened through a vacant lot
and crashed into a 50-foot wide drainage ditch, which sent the car
over a fence and into a swimming pool, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaily Pittman, 12, was conscious when pulled from the vehicle by
a police officer who dove into the pool, but collapsed shortly
after and died at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Singh and sisters Jeanna Collins, 15, and Carly Ann Collins, 12,
were pulled from the car and were being treated for undisclosed
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   No charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, teen-agers must be 15 before they can get a
learner's license, and 15-year-olds are allowed to drive only
between 6 a.m. and 7 p.m. with an adult licensed driver in the
front seat.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Florida rules for teen-age drivers:
http://www.hsmv.state.fl.us/ddl/teendriv.html
</P>
</TEXT>
