<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL a Houston Topic Again  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL A. LUTZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A new home for Houston's NFL expansion team
being built to replace the Astrodome isn't the only construction
going on. Charley Casserly is quietly building a team to play there
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 23 years helping the Washington Redskins become
archrivals of the Cowboys, Casserly has moved closer to Dallas as
executive vice president and general manager of the Houston
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to sign 100 players our first year, that's our
challenge that we have to make and beat the odds,'' Casserly told a
gathering of the Southwest Region of the Associated Press Sports
Editors on Monday. ''There are some people who say we can't beat
the odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly put together Redskins teams that won three Super Bowls
before he was fired in 1999 by new owner Daniel Snyder. Houston
franchise owner Bob McNair quickly took Casserly off the
unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Casserly is taking aim at the Cowboys with the same
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to realize the great job that Tex Schramm (former
Cowboys general manager) did in really promoting the state of
Texas,'' Casserly said. ''What we have to do is to build a solid
base and take one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Dave Campo said he's looking forward to having a
cross-state rival beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is good there are two professional football teams in Texas.
It is too big a state to have just one,'' Campo said. ''We want to
have a relationship with them, playing scrimmages somewhere or
something along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston franchise doesn't even have a name yet, but Casserly
is busily completing a scouting staff to begin searching out talent
for the team's first draft in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is money spent with nothing coming in,'' Casserly said.
''This is a part of a philosophy that Bob McNair has of wanting to
do things the right way. I believe that's why we're going to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Casserly will put his scouting crew to work this summer and then
turn his attention to getting the city ready for a return to NFL
football; the Oilers left for Tennessee after the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are getting some great input on our practice facilities ...
will be the finest in the league and our stadium will be among the
finest,'' Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly expects McNair to build his new football franchise in
much the same way as he got into horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been in horse racing for five years and it was a slow
process,'' Casserly said. ''He's already bred a Kentucky Derby
winner. We are building a house. If we don't finish it in Year 1,
we've got Year 2 and we've got Year 3. We are going to be there for
a long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiring a coach will come next year, provided Casserly and McNair
find the right man.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a perfect world, we would want a head coach who had been
successful in the NFL,'' Casserly said. ''You just never know who's
going to be available. Then, you look for a successful college
coach who's been in the league as an assistant or a successful
coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction is under way on a $367 million, 69,500-seat
retractable roof football stadium that is being built next to the
Astrodome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 1944 </TRAILER>
