<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky River Fish Kill Reported  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- An eight-mile stretch of contamination,
apparently from a distillery fire last week, has caused a massive
fish kill on the Kentucky River, an official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A plume of contamination permeated the river from surface to
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sucking all the oxygen out of the water, and fish are
dying,'' said Mark York, a spokesman for the Natural Resources and
Environmental Protection Cabinet. ''It's pretty much wiping out
everything that's in the river.''
</P>
<P>
   The contamination apparently was caused by alcohol runoff from a
May 9 fire that destroyed a warehouse at the Wild Turkey Distillery
near Lawrenceburg, upriver from Frankfort, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bourbon is not toxic, but something in the water -- perhaps
bacteria -- was fed by the alcohol and depleted the water's oxygen,
York said.
</P>
<P>
   The plume was ''bank to bank and top to bottom. It's not just on
the surface,'' so it could not be contained with a boom, like an
oil spill, York said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Fish and Wildlife Resources said the nature of
the contamination had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Water-treatment plant workers in Frankfort reported a drop in
water oxygen and began spotting dead fish on Thursday, two days
after the fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
