<HEADLINE> Hernandez-MLS Transfer Slowed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Negotiations to bring Mexican star Luis
Hernandez to Major League Soccer's Los Angeles Galaxy have been
''slowed'' by his team's ownership change.
</P>
<P>
   The league ''continues to remain upbeat'' about an eventual
signing, however, MLS spokesman Dan Courtemanche said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month of discussions have been held between MLS,
Hernandez's representatives and Tigres, Hernandez's Mexican First
Division team.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, a news release announcing Hernandez's signing
and the players the Galaxy would have to relinquish to obtain him
was prepared.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sale of Tigres and a coaching change after their
failure to qualify for the playoffs has caused them to re-evaluate
the planned transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Under MLS' single-entity structure, all players sign contracts
with the league. Players of Hernandez's stature are then assigned
to teams.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez would be assigned to the Galaxy, and would be expected
to stimulate ticket sales among the region's extensive Latino
population.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy will have to give up players to obtain Hernandez to
stay under the MLS salary cap and foreign-player limitations. Los
Angeles also is not due to be allocated a player.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 31, is the career leading goal scorer for Mexico's
national team.
</P>
</TEXT>
