<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Makes Congo War Accusations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Human Rights Watch has accused the Rwandan
army and its allied Congolese rebels of raping and killing
civilians who were caught in eastern Congo during the 1{-year civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Tuesday, the U.S.-based human rights
watchdog said its staff had conducted interviews in eastern Congo
in which Congolese civilians blamed the Rwandan Patriotic Army and
the Congolese rebels of punishing them for allegedly supporting
Rwandan Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Hutu militia sought support from Congolese President Laurent
Kabila after fleeing Rwanda in fear of reprisals for the 1994
genocide of more than 500,000 people, most of them minority Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
   In one example, the rights group said, the Congolese rebels and
the Rwandan army attacked civilians in the village of Kilambo in
North Kivu province on Feb. 5. Soldiers tied up men, raped their
wives in front of them and then killed 30 of them.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre took place in revenge for earlier attacks by Hutu
militia, Human Rights Watch said.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan government spokesman Joseph Bideri denied the
accusations, saying they were ''malicious, baseless and biased''
and aimed at discrediting his government.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Congo is the most volatile part of Africa's third
largest nation, where a dozen tribes are hostile to minority
Tutsis. Congolese Tutsis form the core of the anti-Kabila
rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tutsis say they are the victims of ethnic hatred spread
by Rwandan Hutu militiamen and the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
   The Tutsi-dominated Rwandan government has poured troops and
arms across the border in pursuit of Hutus suspected of taking part
in the genocide and backs the rebels who took up arms against
Kabila in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila and the rebels signed a peace accord last year, together
with Rwanda and Uganda which also backs the rebels, and Zimbabwe,
Angola and Namibia, which back Kabila. Foreign troops have promised
to withdraw from Congo after the United Nations deploys 5,537 U.N.
observers and troops.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch said that rape and other forms of sexual
violence have increased in eastern Congo, perpetrated mostly by
armed Hutu militia.
</P>
<P>
   It quoted one woman from the village of Chabwinemwami as saying
that Hutu combatants attacked her home on June 17, pillaged her
house, beat her with clubs then raped her in front of her four
sons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2010 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
