<DOCNO> APW20000515.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> O'Hair Disappearance Trial Opens  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Federal prosecutors began laying out their
case Monday against the only person facing charges in the
disappearance of missing atheists Madalyn Murray O'Hair, her son
and granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   A trail of money transfers and missing gold coins are key
elements in the trial of Gary Paul Karr, a 52-year-old ex-con
charged with conspiracy to kidnap and extort money from the atheist
activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you follow the money, you can pretty much figure out what
happened in this case,'' Assistant U.S Attorney Gerald Carruth said
in opening statements.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair is best known for starting the legal challenge that led
to the 1963 Supreme Court decision that struck down organized
prayer in public schools as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators believe she, son Jon Garth Murray and
granddaughter Robin Murray O'Hair were killed, dismembered and then
put into 55-gallon drums and buried.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's defense attorney, Tom Mills, countered that the
prosecution is missing a key piece of evidence: dead bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The three disappeared from San Antonio in 1995 with $500,000 in
gold coins purchased with money from their organization, United
Secularists of America. Their bodies have never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the trio was kidnapped from Austin by
Karr, O'Hair's former office manager, David Roland Waters and their
cohort, Danny Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Only Karr has been charged. Waters is in prison on federal
weapons charges and Fry was found dead in Dallas County in 1995
with his head and hands missing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Waters has not been charged, investigators consider him
the mastermind behind the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
   Mills suggested the atheists fled to escape an investigation by
the Internal Revenue Service and that federal authorities haven't
diligently pursued reported sightings of them in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know she was extremely smart, clever, lied and responded to
problems by traveling out of the country sometimes with false
identification,'' Mills said. ''It may be the simplest explanation
is that she did what she said she was going to do for a year -- she
fled to escape the Internal Revenue Service.''
</P>
<P>
   After they vanished, authorities questioned whether the atheists
were victims of foul play or merely ran off with the money.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested O'Hair, who was 77 and ailing, had gone off to
die quietly so Christians wouldn't pray for her soul. She wasn't
reported missing for a year until her son, William Murray, called
Austin police.
</P>
<P>
   Karr wasn't indicted until December 1999. If convicted, Karr
could face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, who has a violent criminal history dating back to the
1960s, has said the O'Hairs were not kidnapped, but voluntarily
left Austin with Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Waters, who had intimate knowledge of O'Hair's
financial holdings and had previously been convicted of stealing
from her organization, became enraged when her newsletter was
highly critical of him.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a tale of not only financial greed, but also of
revenge on the part of Waters,'' Carruth said. ''He became obsessed
with separating the O'Hairs from their money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2011 </TRAILER>
