<DOCNO> APW20000515.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florio attacks Corzine for ducking major broadcast debate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jim Florio on Monday
blasted opponent Jon Corzine for avoiding a debate on
network-affiliated television stations here and in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four primary campaign debates, only two were to be
televised, one last week on New Jersey public television and one
scheduled Thursday on the cable news channel News 12 New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine replied that he had agreed to four debates, the second
at a radio station here Monday and the third Tuesday night at a
synagogue in Livingston, and so would agree to no others. He said
network stations had been free to cover any of the debates and it
was not his fault that they had chosen not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a diversion away from talking about the fundamental
issues,'' Corzine said. ''I think it is important that we have
debates. Four is more than the Republicans are having, it is more
than the governor did at other periods of time. There is no walking
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said Corzine's reply was hollow because his campaign had
refused an invitation directly from WPVI, the ABC network affiliate
in Philadelphia, to tape a debate on May 26 at WPVI's Trenton
studio. The debate was to be aired on WPVI Philadelphia and WABC
New York on Saturday, May 27, in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The four Republican candidates -- U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, state
Sen. Bill Gormley, Essex County executive Jim Treffinger and
college professor Murray Sabrin -- have agreed to tape a debate on
the same day at the same studio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jon has made a lot about wanting to help the Democratic Party.
Here we are going to have the Republican Party with this ideal
opportunity to show off their four candidates. They have all
agreed. I have agreed. But for whatever reason Jon doesn't want to
agree,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would really plead with Jon for the interests of the state
to allow us all to talk about the issues to accept this debate,''
Florio said on the air during the radio debate Monday at WLIB-AM
here. ''We have not had mass outlets that are at the network
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio said Corzine's refusal to debate him on network
television was all the more striking since he has been spending
millions on TV ads on those same affiliated stations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Florio claimed Corzine's campaign spending of $1
million a week on TV commercials has now increased to $2.6 million
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine refuted this. ''I am not going to talk about what I am
spending but I can tell you those numbers are wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine said Florio was trying to make debates themselves a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have been debating about debates most of this year,'' he
said during Monday's radio debate. ''We have been on any number of
platforms together where we spoke about the issues that we care
about. At some point, I think we need to converse with the voters
directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Tieman, executive director of the League of Women
Voters, confirmed that Florio accepted the WPVI debate, which they
are cosponsoring, but that Corzine so far has declined.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have kept the time open,'' Tieman said. ''We are going to
determine soon when we are absolutely going to call it off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-15-00 2017 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault, Nissan in European Venture  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French car maker Renault and Japan's Nissan Motor
Corp. on Monday announced plans to save $1 billion over the next
five years by combining their European sales and marketing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Renault and Nissan said the move was intended to deepen the
alliance between the two companies by using Renault's network to
raise Nissan's profile in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan will similarly be supporting the development of Renault
in Australia, Mexico and Japan, the two companies said in a joint
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The automakers said their European sales divisions, which now
employ 5,600 people, would be trimmed by 9 percent by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third, $338 million, of the expected savings in Europe
would come from ''cross-badging'' their models. Renault will sell
Nissan sports utility vehicles under its name, while Nissan will
sell Renault's light commercial models.
</P>
<P>
   They expect to raise their share of the European auto market to
17 percent from 14 percent over the medium term.
</P>
<P>
   Another $500 million of the savings will come from restructuring
and some $250.7 million would come from additional sales and cost
reductions and a streamlined marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's sales and marketing operations will move from Amsterdam
to Paris which will be the center for the combined group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
