<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Slams Bush on Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush today proposed letting
Americans invest Social Security taxes in the stock market, appealing for
support from the millions of people who have thrived in a booming market.
Presidential rival Al Gore condemned the idea as a dangerous gamble that would
turn the solemn obligations of the 65-year-old retirement plan into ''a system
of winners and losers.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Columbine Report Is Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A sheriff's department report released today indicates
the 12 Columbine High School students killed by teen-age shooters were dead
within 16 minutes. It appears to counter claims by the victims' families that
law officers could have saved lives if they had acted more quickly. However, the
report also confirms that teacher Dave Sanders, who died, and some of the 23
wounded waited for hours until the school was evacuated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Bans Federal Rape Lawsuits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rape victims cannot sue their attackers in federal court,
the Supreme Court ruled today, saying it is up to the states -- not Congress --
to give such help to women victimized by violence. The 5-4 ruling threw out a
key provision of the 1994 Violence Against Women Act and continued the court's
trend of expanding states' rights at the expense of the federal government.
''The Constitution requires a distinction between what is truly national and
what is truly local,'' Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Most of Los Alamos, N.M., Reopens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- More than three-quarters of Los Alamos was reopened
to residents today, while the fire that burned down 260 homes and destroyed
historic Indian sites threatened to turn back toward town with an increase in
the winds tomorrow. Residents were allowed back into the less-severely damaged
parts of this town of 11,000, but Police Chief Rich Melton said they would have
to get by without gas and electricity, possibly for a week. The Los Alamos
nuclear laboratory remains closed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
4 Palestinians Killed in Clashes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank (AP) -- Carefully orchestrated Palestinian protests spun
out of control Monday and escalated into gun battles between Israeli troops and
Palestinian police, killing four Palestinians and injuring more than 330 people.
At one West Bank junction, Israeli snipers commandeered a Palestinian-run hotel
and took aim at Palestinian gunmen holed up in buildings nearby. One Palestinian
guest who ventured out was wounded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Showdown Likely Over Kosovo Funding
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton might veto a $4.7 billion package of
emergency defense funds because it would also require Congress' consent to keep
U.S. peacekeeping troops in Kosovo, Defense Secretary William Cohen is warning.
A defiant Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., an author of the bipartisan provision,
called the threat a ''scare tactic that can easily backfire'' because the White
House wants Congress to approve billions in emergency spending for Kosovo and
other programs in that and other bills.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Alters Outlook E-mail
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Charged with enabling easy access for computer viruses like
the Love Bug, Microsoft is altering its popular Outlook e-mail software. It will
prevent users from running any ''executable'' program attachments, good or bad.
Plus when a computer program attempts to access Outlook's address book or tries
to send e-mail via Outlook, users will receive a warning and will be urged not
to allow it.
</P>
