<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Agrees To Pay Fine  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Merrill Lynch has agreed to pay a $750,000 fine to
settle state charges that it failed to properly oversee one
executive who committed fraud and another who mismanaged clients'
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The company neither admitted nor denied the finding of facts in
the agreement, which was announced Monday by Secretary of State
William Galvin's office.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch spokesman Joe Cohen said Merrill Lynch entered the
agreement to allay client concerns about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was the largest ever imposed by the Massachusetts
Security Division.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Merrill Lynch will pay the Massachusetts Investor
Education fund $100,000 to cover the cost of the investigation. It
also agreed to retain a consultant to review compliance policy in
its Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement charged inappropriate supervision of two
executives. One of them, former vice president and senior financial
consultant David Martineau, pleaded guilty in February to six
counts of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Martineau persuaded clients to invest funds
through him, diverted the money, then lost nearly all of it through
risky trading of stocks and options. Martineau was fired by Merrill
Lynch in August 1998 and had already agreed to be barred for life
from working as a stockbroker. The company has denied it was aware
of his schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Greene, who retired in 1998 after 38 years at Merrill
Lynch, is still under investigation by the Securities Division and
could face an administrative fine.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement alleged that Merrill Lynch failed to prevent
Greene, one of the firm's top producers, from improperly
concentrating clients' money in a few stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Nestor, director of the Massachusetts Security Division,
said Merrill Lynch should have paid closer attention to Greene's
investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
