<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils Says They Need To Be Better  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Winning doesn't seem to be good enough for
the New Jersey Devils these days.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's got to be almost perfect, and in their estimate,
Sunday's 4-1 win over the Philadelphia Flyers in Game 1 of the
Eastern Conference final wasn't close.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers got too many chances against goalie Martin Brodeur.
The Devils didn't play good positional hockey at times. Players
were getting caught standing still and not reacting. The litany
from coach Larry Robinson and the players was long.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: The Devils have to play a lot better in Game 2 on
Tuesday night if they want to go home to New Jersey with a 2-0 lead
in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone is aware we didn't play our best,'' defenseman Scott
Stevens said after the Devils practiced for less than an hour at
the First Union Center late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to play better and we have a lot of things to work
on,'' the Devils captain said. ''Everybody in this room believes
that. It's not like we had a false sense of security after that
game, that we played a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the Devils gave the Flyers too much room to skate
and move the puck, making it too easy for them to come out of their
zone.
</P>
<P>
   While his team pursued the puck better as the game went on, it
wasn't anywhere as good as New Jersey did in the first two rounds
against Florida and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a funny game on our part because we played really well
for periods of time and we stood around for periods of time and
watched,'' Robinson said. ''We can't afford to do that. Marty came
up with some key saves for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson wasn't concerned about the Flyers' 36-24 edge in shots
because many of those were from the side boards. He was more
concerned about how the Devils reacted at times in their zone.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had at least a half dozen very good scoring
chances, and they could have had a few more, had the puck not
bounced the wrong way a couple of times in front.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to play a much more all-around solid game,'' Robinson
said. ''We won about 30-some percent of our faceoffs, which means
we didn't have the puck for a lot of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that said, the Devils also know the playoffs can be a
weird time. New Jersey has won nine of 11 games in the postseason.
The only two losses were against Toronto in games where the Devils
had the better of the play, only to see Maple Leafs goalie Curtis
Joseph steal games.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing about the playoffs is we could have played a
terrific game, made no mistakes, whatever and unfortunately, it's
Game 2 and you have to do it all over again,'' Robinson said.
''That's the glory of the playoffs. You can't rest on your laurels
and you can't hang your head (over) what you should have, could
have or would have done. You have to bounce back. We have to forget
about Game 1 and go on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The one area Robinson expects the Flyers to change is their
patience. They gambled a few times and got burned on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I expect them to play a much tighter defensive style game,
instead of getting themselves caught,'' Robinson said. ''But they
played a pretty good game. They don't have a lot to change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2023 </TRAILER>
