<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Journals Showed Anger  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN K. PAULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold grew up as
apparently normal kids, but authorities said Monday there were
clues to a ''darker side'' that no one fathomed and that the two
shared only with each other.
</P>
<P>
   In their report on the Columbine High School massacre,
investigators said Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17, also kept detailed
journals describing their love for anger and their hatred for
mankind.
</P>
<P>
   The final entries are detailed plans for their attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Klebold's words, the day before the shootings: ''About 26.5
hours from now the judgment will begin. Difficult but not
impossible, necessary, nerve-racking &AMP; fun. What fun is life
without a little death?''
</P>
<P>
   Klebold's last entry: ''Walk in, set bombs at 11:09 for 11:17.
Leave, drive to (Clement) Park. Gear up. ... Set car bombs for
11:18, get out, go to outside hill, wait. When the first bombs to
off, attack. Have fun!''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said friends and teachers described Klebold as a
nice, normal student, ''but there was another darker side.''
</P>
<P>
   In Klebold's 1997 journal, he described not feeling comfortable
with peers, being depressed and hating life. A bit later, his tone
changed as he talked about his first love. Deputies found a letter
he wrote to one girl but apparently never sent.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997, he first wrote about getting a gun and going
on a killing spree. He found a soulmate in Harris, who began
expressing similar thoughts the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold both wrote of not fitting in, not being
accepted and their lack of self-esteem. Investigators who analyzed
the writings said ''they plotted against all those persons who they
found offensive -- jocks, girls that said no, other outcasts or
anybody they thought did not accept them.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said most of the teens contacted were unaware they
had ever offended Harris or Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ''Harris and Klebold seemed to have lived two lives,''
investigators said. ''Their friends and family described them as
normal teenage boys. Others described them as outcasts. But they
left behind evidence of a much darker and sinister side. This
darker side was an aspect they apparently shared only with each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   In his academic day planner, Harris wrote random thoughts. One
entry simply said, ''The lonely man strikes with absolute rage.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Klebold wrote in Harris' yearbook that the two would
seek revenge, apparently for their arrest for breaking into a
vehicle in January.
</P>
<P>
   ''My wrath for January's incident will be godlike,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' journal began in April 1998 and he wrote about how much
he hated the world. ''Before I leave this worthless place, I will
kill whoever I deem fit,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1998, he wrote that he wanted to kill everyone
''except about five people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I ain't going out without a fight,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   In his own 1998 yearbook, Harris wrote on the photographs of
almost every student words such as ''worthless'' and ''die.'' On
other students, he simply put an ''X'' on those he did not like.
Few students escaped his wrath.
</P>
<P>
   On the page for Mother's Day 1999, Harris wrote, ''Good wombs
have born bad sons.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only one journal entry in 1999. In it, Harris
evaluated preparations for the attack, including their weapons and
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate piece of paper from his day planner, Harris
recorded his plans for the April 20 attack:
</P>
<P>
   11 (a.m.) go to school
</P>
<P>
   11:10 set up duffel bags
</P>
<P>
   11:12 wait near cars, gear up
</P>
<P>
   11:16 HAHAHA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0209 </DOCNO>
