<HEADLINE> GOP Picks Platform Panel Leaders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Tennessee senator and a North Carolina
congresswoman on Monday were named co-chairs of the committee that
will draft the party platform during the Republican National
Convention this summer in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist and Rep. Sue Myrick will work with Wisconsin
Gov. Tommy Thompson, who was named chairman of the committee on May
1.
</P>
<P>
   ''Senator Frist and Representative Myrick offer sound
leadership, extensive policy experience and balanced political
skills to the delegates who will join them and Governor Thompson in
drafting a document that portrays the ideals and vision that have
cemented the Republican Party as the majority party in America,''
said Jim Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The platform must be approved by a majority of the 2,066
delegates at the July 31-Aug. 3 convention. The Resolutions
Committee, or Platform Committee, consists of 107 delegates,
including a male and a female delegate from each state, the
District of Columbia and Puerto Rico, and one delegate each from
American Samoa, Guam and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Separately on Monday, presumptive GOP presidential candidate
George W. Bush named Jim Wray as convention manager. Wray will be
responsible for day-to-day convention operations on Bush's behalf
and will work with Andy Card, the convention chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
