<HEADLINE> Tobacco Case Punitive Phase Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Faced with a 10-inch stack of motions that
accumulated in his two-week vacation, a judge delayed for a week
Monday's scheduled start of the punitive damage phase in a landmark
smokers' case.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are far apart on issues besides money. The
smokers' attorneys want to exclude most of the industry's proposed
witnesses, and the tobacco industry wants to limit potentially
damaging testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also wants Circuit Judge Robert Kaye to impose a
cap on the dollar request for punitive damages rather than allow
the smokers' attorney to set the figure, calling the $100 billion
amount listed in the lawsuit ''patently and absurdly excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry seemed to be worried about the unpredictability of
an unfriendly jury, which already has ruled the nation's five
biggest cigarette makers conspired to produce a deadly product and
awarded $12.7 million in damages to three sick smokers. Punitive
damages would cover an estimated 500,000 sick Florida smokers.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye, who rescheduled the punitive damages phase to begin May
22, should keep smokers from asking for anything more than 10
percent of the industry's net worth, the tobacco motion said.
Industry supporters value Big Tobacco as low as $8 billion, and
anti-smoking activists consider $100 billion low.
</P>
<P>
   Florida law bars a punitive verdict from driving a company out
of business, but the party seeking damages normally sets the amount
without a judge's intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also wants to exclude:
</P>
<P>
   -- Testimony that the industry has not made meaningful changes in
policies and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   -- The possibility of a verdict to be paid over time, like $250
billion worth of state settlements covering tobacco payments
through 2025.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mention of parent and affiliated companies, the industry's
financial reserves for lawsuits, corporate activity abroad and
punitive damage awards in other lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The industry, which has not paid any money to smokers on a jury
verdict, has agreed to limit youth promotions, remove billboards
and cut other marketing in its settlements with states.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Co., Brown &AMP; Williamson, Lorillard Tobacco Co., Liggett Group Inc.
and the industry's Council for Tobacco Research and Tobacco
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco links: http://www.umich.edu/umtrn/resources.html
</P>
<P>
   Trial transcript service: http://www.engle.cc
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
