<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Protest U.N. Resolution  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia -- Tens of thousands of Ethiopians vented
their anger Monday against a U.N. resolution threatening sanctions
if Ethiopia and Eritrea don't end the latest round of fighting in
their two-year border war.
</P>
<P>
   The protest came as an Ethiopian offensive rolled across the
northern Badme front into Eritrea, its much smaller neighbor in the
Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In Addis Ababa, well-coordinated demonstrators, including groups
of schoolchildren, men on horseback and priests from the Ethiopian
Orthodox Church, marched in Meskel Square. Many carried banners in
English and Amharic warning the United Nations not to repeat an
arms embargo imposed by its precursor, the League of Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936 the League imposed sanctions against Italy and Ethiopia,
then known as Abyssinia, after Italy invaded. At that time,
Ethiopia was the only independent nation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the United States introduced a U.N. Security
Council resolution Monday calling for an arms embargo against the
warring Horn of Africa neighbors. But Russia strongly objected.
</P>
<P>
   The council met Monday afternoon to follow up on the resolution
it adopted Friday calling for ''immediate steps'' to be taken if
the two countries didn't immediately cease hostilities and resume
stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no agreement on what steps to take, and experts
from the 15 nations on the council were scheduled to meet Tuesday
morning to try to reach consensus on a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ''We obviously hope we can get broad support and vote this
tomorrow, but we have to go through a lot of discussions and
meetings before we get there,'' Deputy U.S. Ambassador Nancy
Soderberg said. ''We are deeply concerned about the cost of human
life to this conflict and want to see it brought to an end as soon
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The war is ostensibly about the two nations' poorly demarcated
border. But observers say it is driven as much as anything by the
rivalry between Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and Eritrean
President Isaias Afwerki. Eritrea, once a province of Ethiopia,
gained its independence in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A military analyst, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said it appeared that Ethiopia clearly had the upper hand and had
broken through Eritrean defenses in the northern Badme front along
the disputed 620-mile border as well as at Zalambessa, 255 miles
northwest of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst said Ethiopian aircraft were supporting the infantry
offensive, which he called much bigger than the one in February
1999 when Ethiopia retook Badme with thousands of casualties on
both sides. The war was sparked by Eritrea's seizure of Badme, 400
miles north of Addis Ababa, in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eritrean capital, Asmara, government spokesman Yemane
Gebremeskel said Eritrean forces shot down an Ethiopian SU-27 jet
fighter and a Mi-24 helicopter gunship during what he called
''extremely heavy fighting'' at the Mereb-Setit front, the Eritrean
name for the Badme region.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to disclose Eritrean casualties in the four days of
fighting since the Ethiopians launched their offensive on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite numerous attempts at shuttle diplomacy by U.S. and U.N.
diplomats, there have never been face-to-face talks between the two
belligerents. The closest they got was separate rooms last month in
Algiers for ''proximity talks,'' which collapsed over disagreement
on implementing a peace agreement drawn up by the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries have accepted the blueprint. But Eritrea wants a
cease-fire first, which would include a pullback by both sides and
a U.N.-supervised demarcation of the border that has separated the
two countries since Eritrea gained independence. Ethiopia wants the
implementation first and says Eritrea's position amounts to
''setting preconditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2050 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Arafat Trying To Keep Order  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration acknowledged Monday
that Yasser Arafat has had ''some difficulties'' in restraining
Palestinian militants, but said the Palestinian leader was
committed to peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   As bloody disorder swept the West Bank, sparked by Palestinian
protests on Israel's 52nd birthday of the country's existence, the
State Department equally praised Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak as being peace-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned about the violence and particularly regret
the loss of life,'' spokesman Richard Boucher said. ''But the
parties themselves have committed a serious effort, and are
committed to a serious effort at the negotiating table.''
</P>
<P>
   He also praised the chief Palestinian negotiator, Yasser Abed
Rabbo, who resigned and accused Israel of trying to divide the
Palestinians by setting up rival negotiating channels.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do have a great deal of respect for Yasser Abed Rabbo, and
we hope that he'll continue to be part of the negotiations,''
Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   While not directly confirming the United States approved holding
talks in Stockholm, Sweden, separate from those in the region,
Boucher said ''over the last several years we have been involved in
helping the Israelis and Palestinians work through a variety of
interim and permanent status issues.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been expectations Arafat would not permit Palestinians
demonstrators to go beyond stone-throwing. But thousands of
Palestinians battled Israeli troops on the west Bank and in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   A key issue for Israelis as their government proceeds to
relinquish more of the West Bank to Arafat and contemplates
agreeing to the establishment of a Palestinian state is whether
their security would be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has insisted Arab attitudes toward
Israel have undergone change since Israel was founded in 1948 and
that Israel would be safer if it yielded territory to the Arabs on
all fronts in exchange for recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Monday whether Arafat could have controlled the
demonstrators, Boucher said ''there's obviously difficulties in
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he went on, ''it's our view that he is also prepared to
pursue peace and take the historic decisions necessary to end the
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, meanwhile, registered
concern with the violence and said violence would not solve
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's very important,'' she said, ''that the leaders
themselves try to do everything they can to control any violence.
It's very important there be the right climate that the peace
efforts will be able to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   American mediator Dennis Ross left Sunday for Israel, planning
talks with Barak and Arafat. Boucher said Albright probably would
go to the area, as well, but did not say when she would make the
trip, designed to keep Israel and the Palestinians focused on a
mid-September deadline for a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher welcomed, meanwhile, a move by Barak to turn over to
Arafat three village on the outskirts of Jerusalem. Arafat is
demanding part of the city, as well, as a capital for a Palestinian
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2057 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: Underworld smuggles cash overseas for laundering  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A web of financial reporting requirements
for banks and other institutions has forced many criminals to put
their ill-gotten cash into different financial instruments: truck
transmissions, candy wrappers and battery chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Those are some of the vehicles the underworld employs to smuggle
tons of cash -- billions of $5, $10, $20 and $100 bills, many from
street drug sales -- out of the United States, according to law
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The cash often goes into banks in South America or the
Caribbean. In that sanitized form, it can be wired back into the
U.S. banking system -- the final leg of the ''Black Market Peso
Exchange,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Northern New Jersey and New York, with bustling airports and
shipping docks, along with the Texas-Mexico border, are among the
nation's busiest areas for bulk cash movement, they said Monday at
a congressional hearing here.
</P>
<P>
   Those areas often fall under the jurisdiction of the U.S.
Customs Service, which has seized more than $256 million being
smuggled over the past four years, according to John C. Varrone,
the agency's acting deputy assistant commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   But smugglers can use a venue his agents cannot touch without a
warrant: U.S. mail bound for other countries. A single 4-pound
letter-class parcel, the maximum weight for non-Canadian addresses,
can hold about $180,000 in $100 bills, Customs said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the agency would like to see legislation that would
allow such searches when officers have ''reasonable cause'' to
suspect that cash (or drugs or weapons of mass destruction) are in
international mail. They already have authority for warrantless
searches on incoming international mail and goods.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marge Roukema, R-Ridgewood, who convened Monday's hearing
as chairwoman of the House Subcommittee on Financial Institutions
and Consumer Credit, said that provision would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   She has introduced a bill aimed specifically at bulk cash
smuggling, which officials described as a clumsy but integral part
of the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   The small-denomination bills used to pay for 700 pounds of
cocaine on the street yield more than a ton of cash, Varrone said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the money laundering task forces that combine
officers from federal, state and local law agencies have turned
more attention to bulk smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest cash seizure at Port Newark came in June 1998, when
Customs agents, acting on a tip, searched a 20-foot cargo container
on a ship bound for Venezuela. A mobile X-ray uncovered $11.2
million hidden in truck transmissions, Varrone said.
</P>
<P>
   Currency has also been found stuffed into other objects being
exported, including battery chargers and candy wrappers.
</P>
<P>
   Cash handlers for drug dealers have turned to buying gold with
their proceeds, melting it into various objects, such as nuts and
bolts, which are then painted to disguise their value, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Customs inspectors found $460,000 on a passenger
going to Venezuela from Newark International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can legally carry cash out of the country, but must
declare it on a form as they leave.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage compliance, Customs has 17 currency-sniffing dogs
deployed around the nation, including Kelly, a 3-year-old, 66-pound
Belgian Malinois, who performed Monday for Roukema and the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The dog sniffed several volunteers, and within seconds was
circling Gloria Bryant, director of congressional affairs for
Customs, who had been given a sealed bottle of the ink used to
print cash.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is trained to recognize the smells of a big roll -- over
500 bills, said her handler, Canine Officer Gene Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who mainly works at Kennedy International Airport, is one
of only five dogs who can work around passengers, since she will
signal her handler by sitting, while the others signal a cache of
cash by pawing at a container or suitcase, Schneider said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
