<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Decries Bush on Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) -- Appealing for support from the millions of
people who have thrived in stocks, George W. Bush today proposed letting
Americans invest Social Security taxes in the stock market. Presidential rival
Al Gore condemned the idea as a dangerous gamble that would turn the solemn
obligations of the 65-year-old retirement plan into ''a system of winners and
losers.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Murders of Lawmen Hit Record Low
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Forty-two law enforcement officers were murdered on duty
in the United States during 1999, a decline of more than 31 percent from the
year before and the lowest total on record, the FBI said today. The FBI said 19
fewer officers were slain at work last year than the 61 who were feloniously
killed in 1998. The drop is consistent with an eight-year-long, nationwide
decline in major crimes. The FBI says its national figures on lawmen murdered go
back 36 years to 1963.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Columbine Report Is Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A sheriff's department report released today indicates
the 12 Columbine High School students killed by teen-age shooters were dead
within 16 minutes. It appears to counter claims by the victims' families that
law officers could have saved lives if they had acted more quickly. However, the
report also confirms that teacher Dave Sanders, who died, and some of the 23
wounded waited for hours until the school was evacuated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
INS Calls Haddam's Asylum an Error
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Algerian Islamic leader alleged to have terrorist links
was mistakenly granted asylum in the United States, an immigration official said
today. The asylum was revoked when the error was discovered. Though he's been in
detention for more than three years since his original asylum request was
denied, Anwar Haddam was granted the special status on an application filed for
him by his wife in the last several months, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. It was unclear whether the error was made by the wife or
the INS, the official said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Bans Federal Rape Lawsuits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rape victims cannot sue their attackers in federal court,
the Supreme Court ruled today, saying it is up to the states -- not Congress --
to give such help to women victimized by violence. The 5-4 ruling threw out a
key provision of the 1994 Violence Against Women Act and continued the court's
trend of expanding states' rights at the expense of the federal government.
''The Constitution requires a distinction between what is truly national and
what is truly local,'' Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Shows Promise for Alcoholics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A drug widely used outside the United States to help keep
alcoholics from drinking shows promise in its first American test, researchers
report. Acamprosate worked best in people who aimed to avoid alcohol entirely,
rather than just cutting down, said researcher Barbara Mason of the University
of Miami School of Medicine. It has to go hand-in-hand with having abstinence as
your treatment goal,'' she said. Mason presented the study's results today at
the annual meeting of the American Psychiatric Association. Acamprosate is now
sold in Europe, South America, Asia and elsewhere, and more than a million
people have taken it, Mason said. It is manufactured by Lipha s.a. of Lyon,
France, which paid for the new study.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Most of Los Alamos, N.M., Reopens
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- More than three-quarters of Los Alamos was reopened
to residents today, while the fire that burned down 260 homes raged out of
control on other fronts, including an Indian reservation where historic sites
have been destroyed. Nearly 9,000 residents were allowed back into the
less-severely damaged parts of this town of 11,000, which was evacuated entirely
last Wednesday. Police Chief Rich Melton said they might have to get by without
gas and electricity for a week. The Los Alamos nuclear laboratory remained
closed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 198, Nasdaq Is Up 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today as investors anticipated that the Federal
Reserve tomorrow will complete its cycle of interest rate hikes. The Dow Jones
industrials rose 198.41 to close at 10,807.78. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,775-1,146. The Nasdaq was up 78.59 at 3,607.65.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IU Players Glad Knight Stays
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Indiana players welcomed today's announcement that coach
Bob Knight had saved his job by accepting a fine, a suspension and agreeing to
watch his temper. ''Coach is going to have to make a change,'' said Jarrod Odle,
a reserve. Knight was slapped with a three-game suspension, fined $30,000 and
made to apologize in a deal he struck following an investigation into his
conduct.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
