<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Residents Check on Homes  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) --When flames drove John Jaramillo from his
home in Los Alamos last week, he didn't try to stay with friends
nearby, he headed all the way to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   But Jaramillo, who was worried about the possibility of nuclear
fallout from the Los Alamos National Laboratory, was one of the
first back when authorities lifted their evacuation order for 80
percent of the fire-ravaged town on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He and his 14-year-old daughter had gotten bored with Colorado
and decided to return home. They were driving through Espanola,
just a few miles away, when the evacuation order was lifted for all
but the most severely damaged parts of Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bittersweet return.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo's home and the Mexican restaurant he operates with his
brother were unharmed. But his girlfriend's house had burned to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   ''We come and go from it and you take it for granted,'' he said
of his home, adding he was happy it survived but disappointed he
couldn't save more of his girlfriend's belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it's like I don't even know if we want to stay,'' he said.
''You wonder how many people are going to come back to stay and how
many are going to go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who returned Monday seemed glad to be back,
though, having rushed home as soon as word spread that they could.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly jammed the winding road leading to Los Alamos from
Pojoaque High School, which had served as an evacuation center
after people were driven out of their homes on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They could still see the smoke from the fire in the mountains
beyond their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the first to return was Bill Starkovich, who had been
waiting behind a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately set about watering his grass and flowers and
sweeping ash from his driveway. ''I wanted to make the house look
nice for my wife,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Kurt Duerre was doing pretty much the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to see if I can keep things from dying. That's the
first order of business,'' he said as he watered his lawn.
</P>
<P>
   He also must deal with a stench in his house, caused not by
smoke from the fire but by food that spoiled in the refrigerator
when the power failed.
</P>
<P>
   The reopened neighborhoods showed few outward signs of the
devastation that had occurred just a few blocks away, where more
than 250 homes were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a coating of ash, lots of wilted flowers and dried-up
lawns, it appeared to be just another quiet day in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   One exception was Ed's Food Market, where people began lining up
for groceries Monday afternoon, although a sign said the store
wouldn't reopen until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe they're finally reopening the town,'' said
employee Jerry Kindsfather, who was busy throwing out cartons of
frozen food, eggs and milk that had spoiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2147 </TRAILER>
