<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Says It Must Ease Regulations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The government said Tuesday Japan must learn from
the United States in easing regulations and encouraging competition
to keep up with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In an annual white paper, the Ministry of International Trade
and Industry recommended structural changes, especially in the
service industry.
</P>
<P>
   Japan would benefit from various policy steps the United States
has taken in that area, given that America's competitive edge comes
from its lower prices and constant market innovations, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's service sector has fallen far behind that of many other
developed countries, mainly due to higher prices for services, the
MITI report said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. communications sector, including long-distance
telephone and Internet connection services, has also posted growth,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   In the manufacturing sector, however, Japan's auto exports
remain superior to those of the United States, the white paper
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan's semiconductor exports have begun to lag as the
United States beats Japan in technological areas and other East
Asian countries catch up.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also noted that growing foreign investment in Japan
will likely help bring about much-needed changes in the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign capital flowing into Japan has been rising in the latter
half of the 1990s, reaching a record high in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign entry into Japanese companies, such as tie-up between
Renault of France and Nissan Motor Co., is likely to help
revitalize the nation's economy, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
