<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, May 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Decries Bush on Social Security
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) -- George W. Bush today proposed to let
Americans invest Social Security taxes in the stock market. Presidential rival
Al Gore condemned the idea as a dangerous gamble that would turn the obligations
of the 65-year-old retirement plan into ''a system of winners and losers.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Murders of Lawmen at Record Low
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI said today that the lowest total on record of law
enforcement officers -- just 42 -- were murdered on duty in the United States
during 1999. It's a decline of more than 31 percent from the year before. The
drop is consistent with an eight-year-long, nationwide decline in major crimes.
The FBI says its national figures on lawmen murdered go back 36 years to 1963.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Columbine Report Is Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A sheriff's department report released today indicates
the 12 Columbine High School students killed by teen-age shooters were dead
within 16 minutes. It appears to counter claims by the victims' families that
law officers could have saved lives if they had acted more quickly. However, the
report also confirms that teacher Dave Sanders, who died, and some of the 23
wounded waited for hours until the school was evacuated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
INS Calls Haddam's Asylum an Error
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Algerian Islamic leader alleged to have terrorist links
was mistakenly granted asylum in the United States, an immigration official said
today. The asylum was revoked when the error was discovered. He's been in
detention for more than three years since his original asylum request was
denied. Anwar Haddam was granted the special status on an application filed for
him by his wife in the last several months, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. It was unclear whether the error was made by the wife or
the INS, the official said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ethiopians Protest U.N. Resolution
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia -- Tens of thousands of Ethiopians vented their anger
Monday against a U.N. resolution threatening sanctions if Ethiopia and Eritrea
don't end the latest round of fighting in their two-year border war. The protest
came as an Ethiopian offensive rolled across the northern Badme front into
Eritrea, its much smaller neighbor in the Horn of Africa. In Addis Ababa,
well-coordinated demonstrators, including groups of schoolchildren, men on
horseback and priests from the Ethiopian Orthodox Church, marched in Meskel
Square.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OKs Africa AIDS Victim Fund
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House moved today to set up a ''Marshall Plan'' for
AIDS-devastated Africa. The action comes days after both the White House and
major drug companies took steps to ensure access to cheaper drugs for the
continent's exploding AIDS-stricken population. The disease kills 6,000 people a
day in Africa, has orphaned some 15 percent of children in the worst affected
cities, and by some estimates will lower life expectancy in sub-Saharan Africa
from 59 in the early 1990s to 45 by 2015. The House bill, passed by voice vote,
directs the Treasury Secretary to negotiate the creation of a trust fund in the
World Bank to gather public and private funding to combat HIV and AIDS in
sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UPI Sells Its Name and Trademark
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- United Press International has been sold to the parent
company of The Washington Times, which will continue to operate the news service
as an independent news organization, the companies announced today. Under the
deal, News World Communications Inc. owns all the major assets of UPI including
its name and trademark, said Arnaud de Borchgrave, who will remain UPI's chief
executive officer. He not disclose terms of the sale.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged up Tuesday, supported by gains on Wall
Street. The Nikkei gained 4.67 points to 17,318.36 in early trading. In New
York, the Dow Jones industrials rose 198.41 to close at 10,807.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Defeat Blue Jays 8-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Pete Schourek allowed four hits in eight innings as the
Boston Red Sox won their sixth straight, 8-1 over the Toronto Blue Jays tonight.
The first-place Red Sox moved a game ahead of the idle New York Yankees in the
AL East. Schourek (2-3) didn't allow an earned run.
</P>
