<HEADLINE> Canadian Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressCanadiens Legend Beliveau Has Tumor in Neck
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Montreal Canadiens legend Jean Beliveau says he
is determined to beat a malignant tumor discovered in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Beliveau, 68, who played 20 seasons and won 10 Stanley Cups with
the Canadiens before he retired in 1971, is to begin therapy soon
on the tumor discovered during his annual medical examination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I rely totally on the expertise of my doctors and I intend to
follow their instructions and recommendations to the letter,''
Beliveau said in a statement released Monday by the NHL team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good and I fully intend to win this next battle. During
my treatments, for the next few months, I very humbly ask everyone
to respect the privacy of my family and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The team gave no details of the tumor or what type of treatment
Beliveau would undergo.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Newfoundlanders Angered by Alberta Strip Club Ad
</P>
<P>
   FORT McMURRAY, Alberta (AP) -- A new strip club's claim to be
''drunken Newfie approved'' has folks from The Rock who live in
this oilsands town ranting and roaring.
</P>
<P>
   Showgirls, which also operates clubs in Edmonton and Saskatoon,
targeted Newfoundlanders in a full-page ad in Monday's edition of
the Edmonton Sun and on its X-rated Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to party our asses off . . .'' says the Internet
site. ''(With) all them drunken, crazy Newfies, how can we lose?
</P>
<P>
   ''Newfies are the only people on Earth that can outparty the
Showgirls staff, so we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Newfoundlanders have worked hard over the past two decades to
help build their adopted home, said Paulette Dobbin, president of
the nonprofit Fort McMurray Newfoundlanders Club.
</P>
<P>
   ''This doesn't paint a very good picture for our community,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Chretien Hints at Smooth Byelection for Clark
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien had some sympathetic
words for Conservative Leader Joe Clark on Monday and said he
''wouldn't make life difficult'' for his rival in a federal
byelection.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a former Tory prime minister who doesn't hold a Commons
seat, emerged from his party's weekend policy conference with the
matter of the seat unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation a Conservative MP from Atlantic Canada will
resign to allow Clark -- who's passed on five byelections already --
to run for a seat before a federal election, expected next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is a resignation, I will want to call a byelection,''
Chretien said. ''When? I don't know . . . But I will not make life
difficult for him.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
Justice Stacked Against the Poor, Report Says
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The justice system is ''an abysmal failure'' that
discriminates against the poor while apprenticing future crooks,
says the National Council of Welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of developing effective ways of dealing with conflicts
within our families, our schools and our communities, we dump all
our disadvantaged social misfits into the criminal justice
system,'' says a report released Monday by the council.
</P>
<P>
   ''We arrest thousands of low-income young men and lock them up
with experienced criminals who give them advanced lessons in
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The council is an Ottawa-based citizens group that advises the
federal human resources minister. Its 155-page report, called
Justice and the Poor, was written by independent Ottawa consultant
Louise Dulude.
</P>
<P>
   She holds a Ph.D. in law and culled data from a wide range of
studies, legal journals and Statistics Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Student Musicians Attempt World Record Performance
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Canada boasted the largest
orchestra in the world for almost 10 minutes Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Symphony Orchestra was joined by 6,452 music
students from all over British Columbia in the cavernous British
Columbia Place Stadium to challenge the current record, held by the
city orchestra in Birmingham, England.
</P>
<P>
   From as far away as Prince Rupert in northern British Columbia --
a 20-hour bus ride away -- students arrived to fill much of the
stadium, which is more accustomed to the screams of football fans
than the fine sounds of Beethoven.
</P>
<P>
   There was an official time keeper and an auditor from KPMG to
ensure the record was broken. A tape and photographs will be sent
to Guinness.
</P>
</TEXT>
