<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Return After Dutch Blast  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENSCHEDE, Netherlands (AP) -- Residents wept and gazed in
amazement Monday as they began returning to their damaged homes
after an explosion at a fireworks storage site devastated an entire
neighborhood, killing an estimated 20 people and wounding another
628.
</P>
<P>
   The search for bodies by a 144-member forensics team continued
two days after the blast. Firefighters sprayed the blisteringly hot
rubble left by the enormous blast of 100 tons of fireworks in a
low-income neighborhood of this Dutch town, 85 miles east of
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Disaster Victim Identification Team, wearing
white jumpsuits and safety masks, sifted through the ruins in
search of clothing fragments, jewelry and any signs of life. But
officials said it was unlikely any more survivors would be found.
</P>
<P>
   City workers struggled to track down 200 people reported
missing, but officials insisted that most would be found and stuck
to their death toll estimate of 20.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer force of the explosion made it ''extremely difficult
to identify victims,'' said Dick de Jong, head of identification
team.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Erik Helder told reporters the number of injuries
rose Monday after officials discovered that 25 people had been
treated at an air force base.
</P>
<P>
   Police opened up the outer part of the disaster area for many of
the 2,500 residents who fled the blast or were evacuated from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want to go home,'' said 45-year-old Aryan Curre as he
stared down an obliterated street while gripping his children's
hamster cage. ''We never thought something like this could happen
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In areas where unstable structures made the return too
dangerous, people gazed through security fences and cried.
</P>
<P>
   One man was so desperate to know what was left of his home that
he climbed a six-foot fence to get a closer look. He was
apprehended by security guards.
</P>
<P>
   The city organized bus tours that took people to see their homes
nearer the heart of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understand that people who no longer have homes want to see
it for themselves,'' said Helder.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were increasingly being raised across the country why
the warehouse was allowed in the heart of a residential area and
how the fire caused such devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ''How Could This Happen?'' read the headline in the nation's
largest newspaper, De Telegraaf, which ran a giant photo of the
devastation on its entire front page.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Wim Kok, cutting short a visit to Hungary, urged
people to focus on rehabilitation efforts and wait for the results
of a government investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''A thorough investigation will have to take place to ascertain
what happened, but our immediate concern is to help those in
need,'' Kok told a news conference in Budapest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
