<HEADLINE> SOCOG Directors Will Run Relay Legs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- All 14 directors on the board of the
Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games will run sections
of the torch relay in its 100-day Australian tour, a SOCOG
spokesperson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will all run portions of the relay,'' said Kat Vidovic of
the Sydney torch relay team. ''There's nothing odd about that as
it's happened in previous Olympics as well. Directors have always
had an opportunity to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Vidovic was commenting on published reports Sunday in the Sydney
Sun-Herald that also said all directors of the Australian Olympic
Committee have taken places in the relay as have hundreds of
full-time workers from SOCOG and their families.
</P>
<P>
   SOCOG received about 43,000 public applications for the torch
replay positions from which it chose about 5,000. Another 5,000
went to Olympians, sponsors and VIPs, including Australian golfer
Greg Norman, who will run the torch across the Harbor Bridge in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   A New South Wales state legislator has condemned the high number
of Olympic officials carrying the torch.
</P>
<P>
   ''First it was nepotism, now it is self-promotion,'' said
Charlie Lynn, a state Liberal member. ''I'm so fed up with the
whole thing I've decided to go to Papua New Guinea for the duration
of the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   The torch relay has been dogged by controversy following a
decision by IOC vice-president Kevan Gosper to allow his daughter
to replace another schoolgirl as the first Australian to carry the
Olympic flame.
</P>
<P>
   Yianna Souleles, a 16-year-old Greek-Australian student from
Melbourne, was scheduled to be first Australian in line for the
torch relay before Greek officials switched the order.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper apologized last Friday for what he called ''fatherly
pride'' and a ''lapse in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gosper was cleared by an IOC ethics committee in
Lausanne, Switzerland over misconduct charges concerning the 2002
Salt Lake City Winter Olympic bid.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper was cleared of charges that he and his family had
accepted excessive hospitality from the organizers of the
successful Salt Lake City bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I have ever felt such a sense of release and
relief,'' Gosper told a news conference after Monday's
announcement. ''It has been very hard for my family and my close
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosper has declined to take his spot in the torch relay into the
Melbourne Cricket Ground, where he won a silver medal for the
1,600-meter relay at the 1956 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Souleles, who did carry the flame on a later leg of the relay
last week in Greece, has declined an offer by Gosper to run his
portion of the torch relay.
</P>
<P>
   The torch is scheduled to arrive June 8 in Australia after
traveling through Greece and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The torch will land at Uluru, in Central Australia, to mark the
100-day countdown to the Sept. 15 opening ceremony. It will be
carried by about 11,000 people on its journey around Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
