<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Would-Be Examiner Owner Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT ANDREWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The would-be publisher of the San Francisco
Examiner testified Monday that he'll compete successfully against
the San Francisco Chronicle by focusing on local issues and
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang said he expects to fill a market niche now poorly
served in the city -- intense daily coverage of local issues, along
with advertising focused on the city's readers, at one-tenth the
price of ads that now appear all over the Bay area in the Chronicle
and Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not going to make any pretense of being a metropolitan
newspaper, but rather a local daily newspaper,'' Fang testified in
a lawsuit seeking to block the Hearst Corp. from buying the morning
Chronicle and giving him the afternoon Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Hearst plans to Fang a $66 million subsidy
over three years to keep the Examiner publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is being sued by Clint Reilly, a real estate investor and
former mayoral candidate, on antitrust grounds to block its $660
million purchase of the Chronicle. Reilly claims Hearst wants to
let the Examiner fail quickly and leave the city with a single
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony in the nonjury trial wrapped up after Fang's testimony
Monday afternoon. Lawyers must file briefs, then deliver arguments
in court on May 31 before U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker issues
his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Fang, along with executives of the Chronicle and Examiner, have
been trying to show that Hearst's proposed deal will improve
competition in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But if a federal judge allows Hearst to buy the Chronicle and
end a joint operating agreement between the two daily papers, Fang
will have a huge challenge ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to build a staff from scratch -- the Examiner's
employees will go to the Chronicle. He'll also have to do without
the Examiner's printing presses. And while some experts have
testified that it will be a losing proposition without spending up
to $250 million, Fang said he can do it with just the $66 million
subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White testified
that he had offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable editorials in
return for his political support of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst denied that White's superiors knew of his offer and
replaced White as publisher following his testimony. He told the
Examiner on Saturday that he welcomes an inquiry by Charles
Renfrew, a retired federal judge Hearst hired to look into possible
violations of journalistic ethics.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, White told the Examiner his remark to Brown
was a meaningless ''throwaway'' line, and his testimony made the
comment sound more substantial than it was.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am completely confident,'' White said. ''It will show there
was never a deal of any kind, that there was not, in fact, horse
trading. The firestorm that followed is really unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Hearst executives who followed White to the witness stand
said they were shocked by White's testimony, even though White gave
essentially the same statement to Justice Department investigators
in December and sent e-mails about his meeting with the mayor to
his superiors last August.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was horrified,'' Hearst Corp. CEO Frank Bennack Jr. said
Friday. ''If true, it is clearly outside and contrary to our
policies ... and Journalism 101.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2251 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops Lost in Cambodia Mourned  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS FONTAINE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- The last American soldiers killed in
the Vietnam War were quietly remembered during a ceremony in
Cambodia Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service held by the U.S. Embassy in Phnom Penh in
honor of 18 servicemen killed in the Mayaguez Incident contrasted
with the fanfare marking the April 30 anniversary of the fall of
Saigon,
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of frustration over how things were handled,''
said Leon ''Nick'' Vileo, 82, who was stationed in Thailand when
word came through of the Mayaguez affair.
</P>
<P>
   The Toledo, Ohio, native was one of eight members of the
Veterans of Foreign Wars on hand to witness the tiny ceremony and
to open a Phnom Penh chapter of their organization. In all, about
two dozen Americans were present at U.S. ambassador's residence.
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, 1975, about 200 U.S. Marines were launched on a
daring attempt to rescue the 39 American crewmen of the merchant
ship Mayaguez from a Cambodian island.
</P>
<P>
   The container vessel had been captured by Khmer Rouge patrol
boats in the Gulf of Thailand shortly after the Vietnamese and
Cambodian communists defeated U.S.-backed regimes in their
countries.
</P>
<P>
   In a final effort to show American strength after the
humiliating retreat from Indochina, President Gerald Ford ordered
the bombing of the Cambodian coast and the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Despite superior firepower and sophisticated surveillance, the
American military disastrously underestimated its enemy and was
forced to abort the mission after suffering heavy casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue force descended upon Tang Island in helicopters and
''met unexpectedly fierce resistance,'' Embassy Charge d'Affaires
Carol Rodley recalled in a speech at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Khmer Rouge shot down three helicopters; Marines who made
it to shore were pinned down on the beaches fighting for their
lives,'' Rodley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''U.S. soldiers gave their lives to save the men of the
Mayaguez, including some, tragically, who may have been left alive
on the island,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to the Marines, the Mayaguez crew had been released by
the Khmer Rouge -- whose rule became a watchword for merciless
brutality -- a few hours before the attack and were safely aboard a
Thai fishing boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-15-00 2252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000515.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-15 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 4, Astros 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Aaron Boone homered with two outs in the seventh
inning to break a scoreless tie, and Ron Villone allowed two hits
in seven innings as the Cincinnati Reds beat the Houston Astros 4-3
on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. hit a two-run homer for the Reds, who won for
the seventh time in eight games to move into a tie for first place
in the NL Central with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Villone (5-1) struck out three and walked five in matching his
longest outing of the year. He won his third straight decision.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima (1-6), who has lost a career-high six straight
decisions, pitched his best game of the season, allowing two runs
and seven hits in seven innings to lower his ERA from 9.53 to 8.49.
</P>
<P>
   Lima didn't allow the Reds until the seventh, his longest
scoreless stretch this season.
</P>
<P>
   Boone broke up Lima's shutout by hitting a 2-2 pitch over the
right-field fence with Eddie Taubensee on first in the seventh. It
was the 17th homer allowed by Lima this season.
</P>
<P>
   Villone was methodical, retiring 10 of 11 batters in one span
from the second to the fifth inning. Ken Caminiti's single in the
first was the only hit he allowed until the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Villone, who had lasted seven innings only one other time (April
11 at Colorado), lost his shutout in the bottom of the inning when
Tony Eusebio homered.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Graves pitched two innings for his sixth save despite
allowing an RBI double to Jeff Bagwell in the eighth inning and a
solo homer to Daryle Ward in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Lima is 0-4 with a 9.00 ERA in four starts at Enron Field.
... The Astros are 0-18 in games in which they trail after eight
innings ... Counting Monday's crowd of 41,710, the Astros have had
eight sellouts in 19 home games ... Cincinnati's Michael Tucker is
0-for-12 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
</TEXT>
