<HEADLINE> Notes From Monday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Red Sox-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON: The Red Sox are 40-28 at SkyDome. ... Boston was 9-3
against Toronto last season. ... Tim Wakefield replaces Ramon
Martinez as the starter on Tuesday. Martinez tweaked his left
hamstring last week.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays play all 12 games against the Red Sox
this season in the next five weeks. After June 25, the teams won't
meet again. ''It's awful,'' Toronto manager Jim Fregosi said. ''You
should be playing teams in your own division during the last month
of the season.'' ... Closer Billy Koch shaved the head of a cop
before the game. The officer is raising money for the Canadian
Cancer Society. Cops for Cancer started in 1994 when police
officers in Edmonton, Alberta, shaved their heads to make a little
boy with cancer feel better about his appearance.
Devil Rays-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays have gone 70 games without being shut
out, the longest current streak in the AL. They were last blanked
on Aug. 28 at Cleveland by Charles Nagy. ... The Devil Rays are 0-8
when the opposition starts a left-handed pitcher. ... Fred McGriff
went into the game 17 hits from 2,000, five home runs from 400 and
67 games from 2,000. He is 19 homers shy of becoming the second
player to hit 200-plus homers in both leagues. Frank Robinson is
the other.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: An MRI on Monday revealed pitcher Kenny Rogers has a
strained left shoulder. Rogers was pulled out of his scheduled
start Tuesday, but is scheduled to return to the rotation after
missing only one start. ... Rusty Greer, on the DL since April 13
with a pulled left hamstring muscle, has been sent to Double-A
Tulsa on a rehab assignment. ... Ivan Rodriguez's pinch-homer
Sunday against Anaheim was his second of the season. It's the first
time a Ranger has hit two pinch-hit homers in a season since Mike
Simms in 1997. Texas leads the majors with its .700 average
(7-for-10) in pinch-hit appearances this year. ... The Rangers have
grounded into a major league-high 48 double plays, 12 more than any
other club. That's a pace of 210, or 36 more than the major league
record set by Boston in 1990.
Twins-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: GM Terry Ryan did not accompany the team to Seattle.
Instead, he went to New Britain, Conn., to scout some Double-A
Twins' prospects, including 2B Luis Rivas, 20, from Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: LHP Jamie Moyer made 60 pitches, 40 off the bullpen
mound, for the first time since being sidelined April 15 because of
a strained muscle in the back of his left shoulder. The Mariners
have no idea when he will be able to rejoin their rotation. ... RHP
Freddy Garcia, another starter, is off his crutches, but the
Mariners don't know when he'll be ready to pitch again. Garcia went
on the DL on April 22 with a hairline fracture of his right tibia.
Royals-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Royals reliever Jerry Spradlin picked up his first
save in two years when he struck out Travis Fryman and Richie
Sexson to finish Kansas City's 5-4 win over Cleveland on Sunday.
Spradlin began the 1999 season in Cleveland but was traded early
last season to the Giants, who dealt him to the Royals during
spring training. ''I'm kind of savoring it,'' Spradlin said of the
save, his first since May 25, 1998 as a member of the Philadelphia
Phillies. In earning his fifth career save, Spradlin extended his
scoreless innings streak to 10. ... The Royals went into Monday's
game at Oakland with the worst road record in the AL (5-14). At
home, it's a different story, where they're a league-best 14-4.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Right-hander Gil Heredia, who tweaked his right
hamstring during a winning outing Sunday, is expected to make his
next start as scheduled. ''He's fine,'' Oakland manager Art Howe
said. ''As far as we're concerned, he'll be ready.'' Heredia was
running to cover first base when he felt a twinge in the hamstring
and he was lifted two batters later as a precaution. Heredia (5-2)
still got the win, working 5 2-3 innings in the A's 7-2 win Sunday
over Seattle.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Reds-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: During Dmitri Young's 18-game hitting streak,
snapped Sunday with an 0-for-4 outing, he hit .362 with two homers
and 12 RBI. ... The Reds are 9-1 in games in which Ken Griffey Jr.
homers. Eight of his 12 homers have either tied games or put the
Reds ahead. ... Hal Morris is batting .385 (5-for-13) with one
homer and three RBI as a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: INF Bill Spiers has an eye infection and could not wear
his contacts Monday. Spiers, who has started the last five games at
shortstop, was not in the starting lineup but said he was available
for pinch-hitting duty. He'll wear his glasses should he be called
on to play. ... Catcher Mitch Meluskey has thrown out only two of
22 basestealers this year but says he's not worried. ''I've never
had this problem before,'' he said. ''But it's just like batting
averages. You have slumps sometimes and then you get going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
